<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 03:45:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Paper: China Had Details on US Nukes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- China had significant details of several  
classified U.S. nuclear warheads -- everything from the weight and 
accuracy to sketches of the re-entry vehicles -- more than a decade 
ago, The Los Angeles Times reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1988 Chinese military document, obtained by the CIA in 1995,  
is key to current investigations into admitted security breaches at 
U.S. security installations. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. officials who have seen the classified material told the  
newspaper that it doesn't contain sufficient information for 
Beijing to copy or construct American-style nuclear weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``Knowing the dimensions and the size doesn't tell you how to  
build a nuclear weapon,'' the Times quoted an unidentified official 
as saying. 
</P>
<P>
	At least 10 congressional committees are looking into how the  
Clinton administration responded to allegations of lax security at 
weapons labs and the discovery in 1996 of a major theft of secrets 
by China at the Los Alamos National Laboratory in New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Nearly all the nuclear weapons on the 1988 document were  
developed and built at Los Alamos, The Times reported. 
</P>
<P>
	The Times, citing U.S. intelligence officials it did not  
identify, said the Chinese-language document included a chart with 
data on six U.S. weapons, including the most sophisticated -- the 
W-87, which has 10 independently targeted warheads in a re-entry 
vehicle and is used in the MX Peacekeeper missile. 
</P>
<P>
	The document also mentioned the eight-warhead W-88, used on  
Trident submarines, and the W-78, a three-warhead system used in 
Minuteman III missiles. 
</P>
<P>
	Three other systems, the W-56, W-67 and W-72, date to the 1960s  
and 1970s and are no longer deployed. 
</P>
<P>
	The document -- not blueprints, according to The Times -- included  
projections, in yards, of each missile's accuracy as well as 
hand-drawn sketches of the re-entry vehicles with the dimensions of 
the nose cones. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the details, though officially classified, have been  
published in U.S. books and magazines but others remain top secret. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0002 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:14:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Foreign Money Pours Into Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Foreign companies are pouring more money into Japan  
than ever before as it deregulates its financial services industry 
and land prices continue to fall, a newspaper reported Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Direct foreign investment in Japan for the first eleven months  
of fiscal 1998 rose to a record high 1.08 trillion yen ($8.93 
billion), an increase of 107 percent from the year earlier, the 
Nihon Keizai newspaper reported, quoting the Finance Ministry. 
</P>
<P>
	The figure was well above the previous record for a full fiscal  
year of 770 billion yen ($6.37 billion), invested in fiscal 1996, 
the paper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Finance Ministry spokesman Toshiyuki Kawabata said the  
government could not comment on the report as the full figures for 
fiscal 1998, which ended March 31, have not yet been compiled. 
</P>
<P>
	The surge in foreign investment has been fueled by Japan's ``Big  
Bang'' deregulation measures, which have made it easier for 
overseas companies to take stakes in Japanese insurers and other 
financial institutions, the Nihon Keizai said. 
</P>
<P>
	American companies like Merrill Lynch and GE Capital have been  
aggressively picking up the pieces of failed Japanese financial 
services firms at bargain prices. 
</P>
<P>
	At the same time, the ongoing deterioration of land prices in  
Japan has spurred interest in the country's real estate market. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, many Japanese firms that have been weakened by the  
protracted economic slump are looking to companies abroad for 
financial and managerial assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nihon Keizai said foreign direct investment is expected to  
climb even higher this fiscal year, which ends in March 2000. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
