<DOCNO> APW19990511.0004 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 01:11:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pete Rose Back with Independent Team </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Pete Rose is banned from the major  
leagues and ineligible for the Hall of Fame. That means little to 
the Sacramento Steelheads, who look at the career hits leader as an 
inspiration and a publicity windfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose, who insists his stint as special instructor for the  
Western Baseball League team is not an effort to generate public 
support for his bid to overturn the ban, was back on a diamond 
Monday with a bat in his hands. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose, who will get paid about $50,000 to work with players  
averaging $1,250 a month, said he took the job because he loves to 
teach young players. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is just to help Sacramento. This is not to help Pete  
Rose. This is fun,'' he said. ``I don't go to bed every night and 
pray I can go to the Hall of Fame. I can't live my life in the 
past. Life goes on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rose wore a black long-sleeved shirt, along with designer  
sunglasses and a Steelheads cap. In addition to working with the 
players and giving them a 75-minute inspirational speech Monday, 
Rose will be back May 28 to toss out the ceremonial first pitch at 
Sacramento's home opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose hit fungoes to Steelheads outfielders Monday, and then  
worked with the infielders on rundowns and other game situations. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can still hit, I just can't run. I still have good  
hand-to-eye coordination,'' said Rose, who slammed liners and sharp 
grounders toward the aspiring major league outfielders. ``I'm 58 
years old -- I don't look it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rose, indeed, looks pretty good. He has gotten heavier and is  
slowed by aching knees. But he is tanned and fit, and retains the 
intense gaze and peripatetic style that were among his trademarks. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose, a 17-time All-Star and the NL MVP in 1973, agreed in  
August 1989 to accept a lifetime ban after commissioner A. Bartlett 
Giamatti concluded Rose bet on games involving the Cincinnati Reds 
while he was their manager. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose served five months at a federal prison after pleading  
guilty in April 1990 to two counts of filing false income tax 
returns by failing to report $354,968 in income from autograph 
appearances, memorabilia sales and gambling. 
</P>
<P>
	The career leader in hits with 4,256 and games with 3,562 is  
ineligible for the Hall of Fame as long as the ban is in effect. 
Rose applied for reinstatement in September 1997, but has not 
received a response from current commissioner Bud Selig. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the 14 people banned for life by baseball for gambling  
has been reinstated. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose is prohibited from going on the field or clubhouse of any  
major league team, or any minor league team in organized baseball. 
The Western Baseball League is independent and not covered by those 
rules. Monday's appearance was the first time Rose has actually 
worked with players since the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Rose said he gave a speech to Reds minor leaguers last week in  
Rockford, Ill., and both Rose and his agent, Warren Greene, 
defended that appearance as allowable under the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Selig's spokesman, Rich Levin, was unaware of the Rockford  
speech, but said if Rose spoke with Reds minor leaguers, it would 
appear to violate the ban. 
</P>
<P>
	Reds general manager Jim Bowden said one of the team's minor  
league officials was in Rockford when Rose visited and had been 
reminded of the terms of Rose's ban. Rockford general manager Bruce 
Keiter also was informed. 
</P>
<P>
	Bowden was unaware of any speech Rose might have made to the  
minor leaguers. Keiter did not return a telephone message. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were no violations to our knowledge while he was  
there,'' Bowden said. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelheads players said they know about the ban, but appreciated  
hearing from Rose. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't idolize Pete Rose, but I respect his accomplishments.  
I loved watching him play,'' said pitcher Ryan Bowen, who played 
for the Houston Astros and Florida Marlins and is now trying to 
resurrect his career with the Steelheads. 
</P>
<P>
	Steelheads owner Bruce Portner said he went looking for a  
controversial figure to create a buzz around his expansion team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course it's for publicity. It helps keep Sacramento in the  
nation's eyes as a baseball town. Remember, there's been no 
professional baseball here for 25 years,'' Portner said. ``Let's 
face it, he's Pete Rose. He's banned but also a legend in 
baseball.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rose was scheduled to give a 15-minute pep talk to the  
Steelheads, but ended up giving a 75-minute speech while standing 
near the pitcher's mound at Sacramento City College's Union 
Stadium. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's incredible to sit and listen to him,'' said catcher Tim  
McIntosh, a former major leaguer who went to spring training with 
the New York Yankees this year. ``He's an idol. He a god. You see a 
lot of guys coming through the clubhouse, but he's got 4,000 
hits.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0005 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:08:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Panel Rejects Steel Tariffs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Domestic stainless steel producers will  
consider appealing a federal agency's decision rejecting punitive 
tariffs on some stainless steel imports. 
</P>
<P>
	The industry had sought tariffs to curb imports of stainless  
round wire from Japan and five other countries. But the U.S. 
International Trade Commission rejected tariffs Monday, ruling 6-0 
that foreign pricing practices do not hurt American producers. 
</P>
<P>
	The Commerce Department determined earlier that Canada, India,  
Japan, South Korea, Spain and Taiwan illegally dumped stainless 
round wire in U.S. markets at prices below production costs. A 
commission finding of threat or actual injury was the last step 
needed before Commerce could impose tariffs of up to 36 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	George Kurisky, chairman of the Stainless Wire Action Committee,  
said the industry will review the commission's written opinion, 
expected in a few weeks, before deciding whether to appeal to the 
U.S. Court of International Trade in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	He said steel-makers were disappointed and ``continue to believe  
that the data prove injury to a competitive and efficient American 
industry.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stainless round wire is a low-quantity but high-value product --  
a $300 million-a-year domestic industry, with imports adding 
another $100 million. It is used to produce springs, wire rope and 
fasteners in construction and other applications. 
</P>
<P>
	Last month, Commerce found that Japan dumped a more common steel  
product, hot-rolled carbon steel. Japanese representatives 
denounced the ruling as politicized and looked to the autonomous 
trade commission for what they consider will be a more independent 
review. 
</P>
<P>
	Monday's ruling means that the federal government will refund  
deposits and bonds collected on stainless round wire since November 
to cover any tariffs applied retroactively. 
</P>
<P>
	The cases were filed by ACS Industries Inc. of Woonsocket, R.I.;  
Al Tech Specialty Steel Corp. of Dunkirk, N.Y.; Branford Wire &AMP; 
Manufacturing Co. of Mountain Home, N.C.; Carpenter Technology 
Corp. of Reading, Pa.; Handy &AMP; Herman Specialty Wire Group of 
Cockeysville, Md.; Industrial Alloys Inc. of Pomona, Calif.; Loos &AMP; 
Co. Inc. of Pomfret, Conn.; Sandvik Steel Co. of Clarks Summit, 
Pa.; Sumiden Wire Products Corp. of Stockton, Calif.; and Techalloy 
Co. Inc. of Mahwah, N.J. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0006 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 16:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Hawks, Mutombo Lead Pistons 2-0  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	AUBURN HILLS, Mich. (AP) -- He has heard and read the Mount  
Mutombo comments. They don't bother him. Dikembe Mutombo is a man 
on a mission. 
</P>
<P>
	Right now, the early work on that mission appears nearly  
complete. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind the inspired play of Mutombo, Atlanta's 7-foot-2 center,  
the Hawks take a 2-0 lead over Detroit into Game 3 of their 
best-of-5 first-round series Wednesday night at The Palace. 
</P>
<P>
	``I like to be mean on the floor,'' Mutombo said. ``I have no  
friends out there. After the game, I'll hug you and say `Hi' to 
you. When we're on the floor, we're on a mission.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If they can finish off the Pistons -- or when they do -- Mutombo  
and the Hawks will go on in search of a bigger prize. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, no one wearing a Detroit uniform has been able to  
control Mutombo at either end of the court. He burned the Pistons 
for 17 points, 19 rebounds and six blocks in the opener -- which 
Atlanta won 90-70. 
</P>
<P>
	``You just never get any easy baskets with him out there,''  
Pistons guard Joe Dumars said. ``During the course of a game you 
will normally get five or six easy baskets. You don't get those 
with him, and that magnifies everything else you do.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Playing all but two minutes, he scored 28 points, grabbed a  
game-high 13 rebounds and virtually shut down any thought by the 
Pistons of driving the lane during an 89-69 rout in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``The playoffs are where the great athletes come to play,''  
Mutombo said. ``They've been throwing a lot of bodies at me the 
last two games, trying to get me tired, trying to get me fatigued. 
But my body feels great. I feel great.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Pistons have complained that Mutombo positions himself  
illegally in the lane on just about every possession. Without help 
from game officials, however, they know there is only one way to 
move Mutombo out of there. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our big guys have to step out and make some shots,'' Detroit  
coach Alvin Gentry said. ``To challenge him in the paint is 
probably not the most intelligent thing to do, since he blocks a 
ton of shots.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So far, the Pistons haven't been able to make enough outside  
shots to lure Mutombo out of the lane. 
</P>
<P>
	After scoring 26 points in the opener, making him the only  
Detroit player in double figures, Grant Hill was held to 15 points 
in Game 2 and went nearly 17 minutes in the second and third 
quarters without scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with that subpar effort, he still led the Pistons in  
scoring. 
</P>
<P>
	Bison Dele, the Pistons' center, has been completely overmatched  
against Mutombo. He had just seven points and 12 rebounds with four 
fouls while playing 32 minutes in the opener. 
</P>
<P>
	Things got even worse in Game 2. Dele had no points, one rebound  
and picked up five fouls in just 11 minutes of playing time. 
</P>
<P>
	``We knew we could take advantage of them because they don't  
have a dominant center,'' Hawks swingman Steve Smith said. 
</P>
<P>
	Atlanta forward Chris Crawford, with an mild shoulder  
separation, did not travel to Detroit on Tuesday, but was to join 
the team Wednesday if his condition improved. He was listed as 
day-to-day. 
</P>
<P>
	``Chris has been playing terrific for us,'' Hawks coach Lenny  
Wilkens said. ``When he went down, Ty (Corbin) came in and stepped 
up real big and played well for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Alan Henderson also was held out of practice and was still  
wearing a patch over his injured left eye. He still has double 
vision from an abrasion late in the regular season. Henderson 
played only four minutes in Game 1 and not at all in Game 2 and was 
listed as questionable for Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	The injuries mean the Hawks have lost three forwards who were  
with them at the start of the season. LaPhonso Ellis has been out 
since the 20th game because of a sports hernia. 
</P>
<P>
	``Guys have been stepping up all year,'' Wilkens said. ``We've  
got, all of a sudden, three starting forwards out. We just keep 
playing hard. We don't take anything for granted. We're just going 
to go out and play as hard as we can.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Detroit has lost the first two games of a playoff series 10  
times in franchise history. The Pistons have never recovered from 
such a deficit. 
</P>
<P>
	``Whatever we're doing wrong, we'd better fix it fast,'' Detroit  
guard Lindsey Hunter said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Hawks have never lost a series after going up 2-0, winning  
on six previous occasions with such a lead. Atlanta's last 2-0 lead 
was the first round of the 1988 playoffs against Milwaukee. The 
Hawks won that series 3-2. 
</P>
<P>
	``We know they're a quality ballclub that hasn't played up to  
its capabilities in the first two games,'' Atlanta's Tyrone Corbin 
said. ``We can't afford to think it's over.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0007 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 16:21:02 </DATE_TIME>
