<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> World Cup Still Expecting Chinese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	STANFORD, Calif. (AP) -- Even while canceling a military visit  
and suspending talks with the United States on arms control, 
international security and human rights, China has not threatened 
to pull out of the Women's World Cup this summer. 
</P>
<P>
	So despite the recent deep freeze in U.S.-China relations, World  
Cup president Marla Messing said Tuesday she is confident the 
Chinese -- among the tournament favorites -- will participate in the 
three-week event. 
</P>
<P>
	Messing said tourney organizers have not had any contact with  
Chinese soccer officials in the past few days, but that she has no 
reason to believe China will pull out of the event to protest the 
mistaken U.S. bombing of its embassy in Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are hoping things are going to settle down on the political  
side,'' she said. ``If they were to bow out, I think it would be 
disappointing from a competitive standpoint.'' 
</P>
<P>
	China has expressed outrage over the bombing, which killed three  
Chinese and seriously wounded six. It has led to days of street 
protests in Beijing that have made ambassador James Sasser a 
virtual prisoner at the U.S. Embassy in the Chinese capital. 
</P>
<P>
	Beijing canceled a planned visit next week by Gen. Charles  
Krulak, commandant of the Marine Corps, and Chinese President Jiang 
Zemin has refused to accept a telephone call of apology from 
President Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not heard anything from China,'' Messing said. ``It  
would be inappropriate for us to contact China. That kind of a 
decision is up to them. We welcome them to play in the 
tournament.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The tournament begins June 19 and runs through July 10. The  
Chinese team, which has defeated the U.S. squad in two of their 
last three games, is expected to arrive in San Jose, Calif., around 
June 7 or 8. 
</P>
<P>
	China is scheduled to use San Jose State as its base and  
training center before its opening game there June 19 against 
Sweden. Its other first-round matches would be June 23 in Portland, 
Ore., and June 26 at Giants Stadium in East Rutherford, N.J. 
</P>
<P>
	If the Chinese qualify for the quarterfinals, as expected, they  
would play June 30 in San Jose. They could not face the United 
States until the final on July 10 in Pasadena, Calif. 
</P>
<P>
	Tourney organizers rearranged the World Cup draw to ensure China  
would play its first game in the San Francisco Bay area, hoping to 
attract fans from the region's large Asian-American population. 
</P>
<P>
	The Chinese won the silver medal at the 1996 Atlanta Olympics,  
losing to the United States in the final. 
</P>
<P>
	With 37 days remaining before the start of the World Cup,  
Messing said more than 350,000 tickets have been sold for the 32 
games scheduled in seven cities around the country. Organizers hope 
to sell 475,000 tickets. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
