<HEADLINE> Speedway Deal Creates Racetrack Giant </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	INDIANAPOLIS (AP) -- International Speedway Corp. is buying  
sports promoter Penske Motorsports Inc. for about $610 million in 
stock in a deal that will put 10 auto racing tracks in the United 
States under one owner. 
</P>
<P>
	The deal, announced Monday, gives the International Speedway a  
tighter hold on some of auto racing's premier events, especially 
the NASCAR Winston Cup series. 
</P>
<P>
	Penske owns and operates Michigan Speedway in Brooklyn, Mich.;  
Nazareth Speedway in Pennsylvania; California Speedway in San 
Bernardino; and North Carolina Speedway near Rockingham. 
</P>
<P>
	ISC, which promotes about 80 events a year, owns or operates  
Daytona International Speedway, Talladega Superspeedway in Alabama, 
Phoenix International Raceway, Darlington Raceway in South 
Carolina, and Watkins Glen International in New York. 
</P>
<P>
	``ISC will have a better, stronger hold on sponsors wanting to  
sponsor races or have a presence at race tracks,'' said Chris 
Hansen, motorsports analyst at NationsBanc Montgomery Securities in 
San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	ISC, of Daytona Beach, Fla., is paying $50 per share in stock  
and cash for 12.2 million shares of Detroit-based Penske. ISC 
already held 12 percent of Penske Motorsports. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1999, the two companies will promote more than 100 events.  
The companies generated more than $300 million in revenue last 
fiscal year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
