<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Republicans Restate Tax-Cut Pledge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans used Tuesday's symbolic ``Tax  
Freedom Day'' to renew their promise to pass tax relief in Congress 
this year. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're going to have a tax cut,'' pledged House Majority Leader  
Dick Armey, R-Texas. ``Today's American family is overtaxed at all 
levels.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Tax Foundation, a nonprofit research organization oriented  
toward business, calculates ``Tax Freedom Day'' as the time it 
takes Americans on average to finish paying all federal, state and 
local taxes each year and begin working for themselves. This year's 
date is 131 days into 1999, one day later than last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Although that formula is frequently criticized as overstating  
the burden on middle-class Americans, Republicans lined up to 
deliver floor speeches in the House to underscore the date. Senate 
Majority Leader Trent Lott, R-Miss., even capped a news conference 
with a ``hallelujah'' and asked reporters if they knew what day it 
was. 
</P>
<P>
	``The money you get now is yours,'' Lott said.  
</P>
<P>
	Republicans are trying to put together a tax relief bill that  
probably would start out small in 2000 and 2001 and eventually grow 
to nearly $800 billion over the next decade. The effort is 
hamstrung because projected budget surpluses are almost all Social 
Security dollars in the first years -- an account the GOP promises 
not to touch. 
</P>
<P>
	``The tax cut in the first couple of years is going to be  
modest,'' said Rep. Jerry Weller, R-Ill. ``But then it's going to 
widen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Among the items under consideration are elimination of estate  
taxes, cuts in capital gains taxes, relief from the so-called 
marriage penalty paid by many two-income couples and business tax 
reduction. Tax-writing committees in the House and Senate expect to 
have legislation ready in July. 
</P>
<P>
	One decision has already been made: Expiring tax provisions  
affecting business that are likely to be renewed in this year's 
bill will have a retroactive effective date of July 1. Four of 
them, including the popular research and development tax credit, 
are set to expire June 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement by House Ways and Means Committee Chairman Bill  
Archer, R-Texas, and Senate Finance Committee Chairman William 
Roth, R-Del., is important to companies attempting to put together 
financial plans for next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0016 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Braves' Jordan Thrown Out of Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN FRANCISCO (AP) -- Atlanta outfielder Brian Jordan, unhappy  
with a called third strike, let plate umpire Bruce Dreckman know 
how he felt and wound up getting thrown out of Tuesday night's game 
at San Francisco. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the second ejection of the night for the Braves. Manager  
Bobby Cox was tossed in the first inning for arguing a balk call 
against Odalis Perez. 
</P>
<P>
	San Francisco pitcher Shawn Estes had a 1-2 count against Jordan  
in the fifth inning when he delivered a pitch that Jordan thought 
was low and outside. Dreckman called him out, and Jordan walked 
slowly back to the dugout. 
</P>
<P>
	After Estes fanned Andruw Jones to end the fifth, Jordan walked  
onto the field and confronted Dreckman. As the two argued, a couple 
of Jordan's teammates rushed to restrain him but not before 
Dreckman ejected him. 
</P>
</TEXT>
