<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0017 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 18:21:47 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Bill Sparks Fights </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Multibillion-dollar legislation to pay for  
U.S. military attacks on Yugoslavia and to help Central America 
recover from Hurricane Mitch has become a battleground on 
environmental issues ranging from mining regulations to Alabama 
sturgeon. 
</P>
<P>
	House-Senate leaders met Tuesday to begin composing a compromise  
package they hope to send to President Clinton by week's end. The 
main focus is a fight between the White House and Republicans over 
billions of dollars lawmakers want to add to the Pentagon's budget 
atop Clinton's request for $6 billion to cover U.S. costs in the 
NATO bombing campaign and refugee aid. 
</P>
<P>
	But numerous battles are being waged over environmental  
provisions included in an earlier, Senate-approved version of the 
legislation or that senators were trying to squeeze into the final 
package. 
</P>
<P>
	Environmental groups accused sponsors of the provisions of using  
the must-pass legislation to carry provisions that otherwise would 
have little chance of becoming law. 
</P>
<P>
	``The folks in the Senate pushing this stuff have reached a new  
low in cynically trying to take advantage of victims of natural 
disaster and war,'' said Marty Hayden, policy director for the 
Earthjustice Legal Defense Fund. 
</P>
<P>
	Republican moderates in the House were also joining the fray.  
Rep. Sherwood Boehlert, R-N.Y., said more than 20 of his colleagues 
signed a letter objecting to senators' environmental provisions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our party should be seen as expediting the release of this  
money, not delaying it with non-germane matters that do not belong 
in these spending bills in the first place,'' the letter said. 
</P>
<P>
	In one such fight, Sen. Richard Shelby, R-Ala., is trying to  
block the Fish and Wildlife Service from listing the Alabama 
sturgeon as an endangered species, a battle that has raged since 
1993. 
</P>
<P>
	Alabama officials believe they are adequately protecting the  
fish with their own protection program. If the fish is listed as 
endangered, Shelby says, dredging in state waterways would be 
restricted, harming the timber and other industries that ship their 
products on barges. 
</P>
<P>
	``They are wrong and they know it,'' Shelby said of Fish and  
Wildlife officials. 
</P>
<P>
	After House members argued that Congress had never before  
blocked a species from being listed as endangered, Shelby said he 
would halt his effort if the Interior Department would promise to 
delay its effort until next year. That would let him wage his fight 
later. 
</P>
<P>
	Sen. Slade Gorton, R-Wash., is waging another effort to overturn  
a court ruling that mining companies can't use public lands to 
expand their milling operations. Environmentalists complain those 
operations pollute water. The ruling affects the Crown Jewel gold 
mine in Gorton's state and other Western hard-rock mines. 
</P>
<P>
	The ruling, if upheld, would cause ``a tremendous degree of  
injustice,'' Gorton said. 
</P>
<P>
	Other fights include:  
</P>
<P>
	--An effort by Sen. Frank Murkowski, R-Alaska, to prevent the  
National Park Service from phasing out commercial fishing in the 
waters off Glacier Bay National Park until courts decide the issue. 
Environmentalists say that could take years. 
</P>
<P>
	--An attempt by Sen. Harry Reid, D-Nev., to delay the Interior  
Department in implementing stricter rules that would require mining 
companies using federal lands to do more thorough clean-ups. 
</P>
<P>
	--An amendment by Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison, R-Texas, to extend a  
moratorium on increasing the royalties oil companies using public 
lands must pay the government. Administration officials say this 
would cost the Treasury $5.3 million per month. 
</P>
<P>
	--Sen. Pete Domenici, R-N.M., was considering trying to block the  
Interior Department from designating a protected habitat for the 
endangered silvery minnow. That designation would restrict New 
Mexicans' use of water from the Rio Grande River. 
</P>
<P>
	As always with spending bills, other issues are also cropping  
up. 
</P>
<P>
	The two chambers' negotiators tentatively agreed to add $900  
million to the measure to cover the costs of the recent Midwestern 
tornadoes and to buttress the Federal Emergency Management Agency's 
coffers for future disasters. That amount is more than $500 million 
more than Clinton sought. Aides said another $141 million or more 
might be added before the measure is finished. 
</P>
<P>
	They also tentatively agreed to provide $566 million -- $400  
million above Clinton's request -- for U.S. farmers staggered by 
plummeting prices for cotton, hogs, livestock and other 
commodities. Farm-state senators might try to boost the aid later. 
</P>
<P>
	An effort by Sens. Richard Durbin, D-Ill., and Arlen Specter,  
R-Pa., to add $265 million for anti-violence programs in schools 
went nowhere after House Republicans balked. Durbin initially 
sought nearly $1 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
