<DOCNO> APW19990511.0018 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Pilot Sentenced in Italy Ski Tragedy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMP LEJEUNE, N.C. (AP) -- A Marine pilot convicted of  
obstruction of justice for helping destroy a videotape of his fatal 
flight over the Italian Alps will spend six months in prison. 
</P>
<P>
	The jury of seven officers deliberated about two hours Monday  
before announcing the sentence for Capt. Richard Ashby, 32, of 
Mission Viejo, Calif. Twenty people died when his jet cut an 
Italian ski gondola cable. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby, who faced a maximum sentence of 10 years, is the only  
person charged in the February 1998 accident to serve prison time. 
He also will be dismissed from the Marines. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby stood at attention as the sentence was read by Col. Gerald  
Yanello, commander of New River Air Station. He was then led away 
to the brig by two officers from his air wing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were all surprised,'' said defense attorney Frank Spinner.  
``No one thought that confinement was a final option. We were 
appalled the government even asked for two years of confinement.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Spinner said he would appeal the case once a review is conducted  
by Lt. Gen. Peter Pace, commander of Marine Forces Atlantic. The 
review could take six months. 
</P>
<P>
	Ashby had no comment as he walked to a white Jeep driven by a  
military policeman. Before Ashby was taken away, he cried and 
hugged his mother, stepfather and girlfriend, Spinner said. 
</P>
<P>
	In March, a separate jury acquitted Ashby of 20 counts of  
involuntary manslaughter for the deaths of the passengers aboard 
the Mount Cermis gondola cable. The verdict enraged relatives of 
the victims, as well as Italian leaders 
</P>
<P>
	The EA-6B Prowler's navigator, Capt. Joseph Schweitzer, 31, of  
Westbury, N.Y., pleaded guilty to obstructing justice and was 
sentenced to dismissal from the service but no prison time. 
</P>
<P>
	Once Ashby landed the crippled jet at the NATO air base at  
Aviano, Italy, he took out the videotape, which was made earlier in 
the flight and was intended as a souvenir. 
</P>
<P>
	He testified that he later gave it to Schweitzer at the  
navigator's request. Schweitzer said he later threw it into a 
bonfire because he was afraid his face was on the tape and could be 
used by Italian media. 
</P>
<P>
	While acknowledging that he helped get rid of the tape, Ashby  
denied he had a criminal intent -- impeding the investigation into 
the accident. 
</P>
<P>
	Two back-seat officers in the jet were charged with involuntary  
manslaughter soon after the accident but the charges were 
dismissed. One of those officers, Capt. Chandler Seagraves, told 
investigators about the tape after he was granted immunity from 
prosecution. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
