<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 11:25:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 7th Hiker Presumed Dead in Hawaii </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAUULA, Hawaii (AP) -- A California woman hiking with friends and  
relatives in a tropical gorge is still missing, and authorities 
consider her the seventh person killed by a weekend landslide. 
</P>
<P>
	Searchers were not trying to locate or retrieve the unidentified  
24-year-old's body from Sacred Falls State Park because of the high 
risk of another landslide. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm not willing to risk our personnel for what may be a body  
retrieval,'' Honolulu Fire Chief Attilio Leonardi said. ``There is 
nothing more we can do without putting our people in harm's way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Authorities learned of the woman's disappearance from her  
boyfriend, who is hospitalized with a broken leg. The two were 
side-by-side when the wave of rocks and trees washed over them. The 
woman hasn't been seen since. 
</P>
<P>
	The search effort first broke off Monday morning when military  
dogs and a chopper using heat-seeking cameras failed to detect any 
more bodies in the bottom of the narrow gorge, which is carpeted 
with debris from the cliffside. 
</P>
<P>
	Crews returned in the afternoon upon hearing the woman was still  
missing, but soon called off the operation. 
</P>
<P>
	The park itself has been indefinitely closed, as state  
geologists warned of the potential for more landslides like the one 
on Mother's Day that injured dozens more at one of Hawaii's most 
spectacular hiking spots. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we were up there this morning, several rocks came down  
and went into the pool and one came down between the other 
geologist and myself,'' state geologist Glenn Bauer said. 
</P>
<P>
	The hikers were sunning themselves near a 90-foot waterfall  
Sunday afternoon when tons of boulders, some the size of small 
cars, ricocheted down into the narrow valley from 850 feet above. 
</P>
<P>
	``The site looked like something out of a war zone,'' Honolulu  
Fire Capt. Richard Soo said. 
</P>
<P>
	Six bodies have been recovered, four females and two males.  
</P>
<P>
	They were identified as Air Force Master Sgt. Scott Huling, 36,  
stationed at Hickam Air Force Base near Honolulu; Danielle 
Williams, 7, also of Hickam; Jennifer Johnson, 24, of Los Angeles; 
Aaron Bann, 31, of Placentia, Calif.; Donna Forsch, 38, of Elk 
Grove, Calif., and Teri Zerebeski, 42, of Sherwood Park, Alberta, 
Canada. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirteen people remain hospitalized, including a 29-year-old man  
in critical condition. 
</P>
<P>
	``There were bodies everywhere,'' said David Pahk, 37, a  
volunteer with the Sacred Falls Assistance Program that hands out 
bottled water and sunscreen to often-unprepared hikers. 
</P>
<P>
	He and a dozen others worked frantically to save the life of a  
young girl, carrying her out the trail on a stretcher and sharing 
CPR efforts. 
</P>
<P>
	``She just died in our hands,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Deborah Bianchi, a registered nurse, and her husband, Lt. Col.  
Michael Bianchi, an Army Ranger, had just started their hike when 
the landslide hit. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was such a beautiful day. That's what was so eerie about  
it. You'd go by rocks with blood on them, see discarded shoes 
covered with blood, but the birds were singing and it was so 
quiet,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	The park in the lushly forested Koolau Range is about 30 miles  
north of Honolulu and across the road from the Pacific Ocean. 
</P>
<P>
	It long has been considered one of Hawaii's most popular natural  
attractions, with 56,000 annual visitors. It also is one of its 
most dangerous, with at least a dozen deaths since 1970. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
