<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> MIT Awards Online Commerce Prizes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- The Massachusetts Institute of  
Technology's Sloan School of Management has honored six companies 
as innovators in Web-based business. 
</P>
<P>
	The awards, presented Tuesday night, were developed by Sloan  
students as part of the school's electronic commerce and marketing 
curriculum. The school plans to give out the E-Commerce Awards 
annually. 
</P>
<P>
	The award winners were:  
</P>
<P>
	-- MP3.com Inc., of San Diego. The company is one of the leading  
sources of music in a digital, MP3 compressed format and was 
awarded for creating opportunities for customers through electronic 
commerce. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Egghead.com, based in Spokane, Wash., for successfully  
transforming itself from an established physical company to a 
Web-based business. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Dell Computers Corp., of Austin, Texas, for serving a large  
international base of Web customers. The company serves 44 
countries and covers 21 languages. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Akamai Technologies Inc., based in Cambridge, for showing  
potential to dominate new industries. It offers a service that 
speeds up delivery of Web pages. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Net Perceptions, based in Minneapolis, for developing  
innovative technology. The company develops real-time technology. 
</P>
<P>
	-- Impact Online, of Palo Alto, Calif., for socially responsible  
Web services. The company provides ``VolunteerMatch,'' a service 
that pairs volunteers with nonprofit organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
