<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Refugees To Move to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIRANA, Albania (AP) -- An operation to transfer Kosovo refugees  
from crowded camps in Macedonia to Albania is finally under way, 
relief officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Melitta Sunjic, spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for  
Refugees, said three buses carrying about 150 refugees arrived from 
Macedonia late Monday at a new camp near the southern Albanian town 
of Korca. Sunjic said all the refugees had relatives in Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korca camp was built to accommodate 6,000 refugees, but thus  
far few refugees in Macedonia have expressed interest in the move, 
and the U.N. refugee agency says it won't transfer refugees against 
their will. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonian authorities, worried about overcrowding at refugee  
camps and possible political instability, have been pressing the 
international community to help move abroad some of the more than 
238,000 Kosovo refugees in Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Albania, which is already accommodating more than 426,000  
refugees, says it will take in as many as necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials estimate more than 750,000 ethnic Albanians have  
fled their homes in Kosovo, many of them forced by security forces 
to leave the southern province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant 
republic. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO launched a bombing campaign March 24 to force Yugoslavia to  
accept a peace deal for Kosovo, which includes an international 
force to ensure the safe return of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	In Geneva, a spokeswoman today said the United Nations is  
running out of money for Kosovo refugees. UNHCR has received only 
$71 million of the $143 million it said it needed for its Kosovo 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has all been spent or fully committed,'' spokeswoman Judith  
Kumin said. ``If there are no new contributions, it means that 
we're not able to continue to procure relief supplies which the 
refugees need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Kukes, on the Albanian border with Kosovo, the UNHCR began  
tent-to-tent lobbying to try to persuade refugees to move further 
into the country and out of range of Serb artillery. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be very difficult. These people have been here a  
while, they're giving us very good, cogent reasons why they 
shouldn't leave,'' said spokesman Ray Wilkinson. ``It's going to be 
a hard sell.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0024 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:54:27 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Head Slows Declassification </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stung by an espionage scandal, Energy  
Secretary Bill Richardson ordered a broad array of security 
upgrades Tuesday and directed a slowdown of the administration's 
aggressive declassification of Cold War-era nuclear documents. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's critical that we guard our secrets more thoroughly,'' and  
there has been some concern that the declassification program was 
moving too fast, he said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said he will consolidate the department's $800  
million widely dispersed security apparatus under a single 
``security czar,'' who will report directly to him with increased 
power over the weapons laboratories, which traditionally have 
cherished their independence. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``security czar'' will have ``juice and clout'' and report  
directly to him, said Richardson. He called the security 
consolidation a dramatic change from how the department long has 
operated and said he wants ``a three-star general with extensive 
security background'' for the top job. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, at a briefing with reporters, Richardson criticized the  
department's longtime security structure as ``nondirectional'' and 
``diffuse'' with a lack of accountability that over the years left 
nuclear secrets exposed to espionage and potential theft. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is clear that over the past several decades security and  
counterintelligence have not been given the necessary priority and 
attention,'' said Richardson, who took over the department last 
November. 
</P>
<P>
	Criticism has been widespread in Congress about security  
problems at the government's nuclear weapons research labs and 
reports of theft of nuclear secrets -- in the 1980s and possibly as 
late as 1995 -- at the Los Alamos lab in New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Seeking to blunt the attacks, Richardson also announced:  
</P>
<P>
	--Implementing new controls on top-secret as well as unsecured  
computer systems at weapons labs, including mechanical devices to 
prevent downloading and transfer of files to disks. 
</P>
<P>
	--Creating a team to evaluate espionage threats and DOE  
facilities' vulnerability to theft of secrets. 
</P>
<P>
	--Requiring banners on all computers warning users their machines  
are subject to search. 
</P>
<P>
	--Requiring that all foreign visits to weapons labs and other  
facilities be tracked and cleared by a central office at DOE 
headquarters. 
</P>
<P>
	The department also will ask Congress for an extra $50 million  
over two years for computer security improvements. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson also said the department's declassification of Cold  
War-era documents will be reviewed to ensure that material 
involving nuclear weapons design and other sensitive data is not 
inadvertently declassified. 
</P>
<P>
	An executive order that requires declassification by April 2000  
of all material at least 25 years old will be put on hold and 
extended for 18 months to allow a further review, officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department has been criticized in the past for its  
secretiveness. In 1993, then-Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary 
overruled reservations from some of the DOE's defense and security 
experts and began an aggressive move toward more openness. 
Declassification efforts were stepped up further after disclosure 
of improper radiation experiments on people in the early days of 
the Cold War. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said while some declassification will continue, the  
program will be reviewed to ensure that sensitive weapons-design 
documents are not released by mistake when mixed with other 
material. Officials said spot checks of files showed this to be a 
problem. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson said the overhaul of the department's security  
operation was designed to bring ``more responsibility, 
accountability and high-level attention'' to security within the 
department. 
</P>
<P>
	But he said he opposes suggestions making the rounds in  
Congress, such as turning over to the FBI all security and 
counterintelligence work, ending foreign visits to research labs or 
removing the labs from the Energy Department. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can demonstrate that the labs are accountable to us. We'll  
run the labs,'' said Richardson. Some critics complain that the 
prestigious weapons labs -- Los Alamos and Sandia in New Mexico, 
Lawrence Livermore in California -- often have considered themselves 
independent fiefdoms. 
</P>
<P>
	``I run the labs now. This has not always been the case,'' said  
Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	Los Alamos and Lawrence Livermore have been managed ever since  
their inception by the University of California, and some critics 
have suggested a campus atmosphere has added to security problems. 
While praising the labs for cooperating in imposing new security 
measures, Richardson said he has not ruled out putting the 
management contracts up for competitive bidding when they come up 
for renewal. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0025 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 08:46:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Kosovo Refugees To Move to Albania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TIRANA, Albania (AP) -- An operation to transfer Kosovo refugees  
from crowded camps in Macedonia to Albania is finally under way, 
relief officials said today. 
</P>
<P>
	Melitta Sunjic, spokeswoman for the U.N. High Commissioner for  
Refugees, said three buses carrying about 150 refugees arrived from 
Macedonia late Monday at a new camp near the southern Albanian town 
of Korca. Sunjic said all the refugees had relatives in Albania. 
</P>
<P>
	The Korca camp was built to accommodate 6,000 refugees, but thus  
far few refugees in Macedonia have expressed interest in the move, 
and the U.N. refugee agency says it won't transfer refugees against 
their will. 
</P>
<P>
	Macedonian authorities, worried about overcrowding at refugee  
camps and possible political instability, have been pressing the 
international community to help move abroad some of the more than 
238,000 Kosovo refugees in Macedonia. 
</P>
<P>
	Albania, which is already accommodating more than 426,000  
refugees, says it will take in as many as necessary. 
</P>
<P>
	U.N. officials estimate more than 750,000 ethnic Albanians have  
fled their homes in Kosovo, many of them forced by security forces 
to leave the southern province of Serbia, Yugoslavia's dominant 
republic. 
</P>
<P>
	NATO launched a bombing campaign March 24 to force Yugoslavia to  
accept a peace deal for Kosovo, which includes an international 
force to ensure the safe return of refugees. 
</P>
<P>
	In Geneva, a spokeswoman today said the United Nations is  
running out of money for Kosovo refugees. UNHCR has received only 
$71 million of the $143 million it said it needed for its Kosovo 
operations. 
</P>
<P>
	``It has all been spent or fully committed,'' spokeswoman Judith  
Kumin said. ``If there are no new contributions, it means that 
we're not able to continue to procure relief supplies which the 
refugees need.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Kukes, on the Albanian border with Kosovo, the UNHCR began  
tent-to-tent lobbying to try to persuade refugees to move further 
into the country and out of range of Serb artillery. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be very difficult. These people have been here a  
while, they're giving us very good, cogent reasons why they 
shouldn't leave,'' said spokesman Ray Wilkinson. ``It's going to be 
a hard sell.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0026 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 11:25:09 </DATE_TIME>
