<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 05:35:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> High-Tech, Banking Propel Lobbying </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Demonstrating that special interest lobbying  
follows the hot issues, a report shows that the biggest spenders in 
trying to influence federal officials are the health care, 
financial, insurance and high-tech industries. 
</P>
<P>
	Special interests averaged $117 million a month in lobbying  
expenses during the last half of 1998, according to the report 
Monday by Public Disclosure Inc., an Internet consulting firm. The 
figure compared with $100 million a month in lobbying expenditures 
in the first half of 1997, company co-founder Kent Cooper said. 
</P>
<P>
	Old-line sectors such as agriculture, manufacturing, defense  
contractors and real estate were far behind in total lobbying 
expenditures, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	The modern-day giants of Internet technology and  
telecommunications; the banking, insurance and securities firms 
that are becoming financial ``supermarkets''; and health-care 
companies with managed-care issues are among the interests now 
leading the lobbying pack. 
</P>
<P>
	``The lobbying expenditures reflect where the growth of the  
economy is right now,'' Cooper said. ``A lot of the rust-area 
manufacturing is not as big a factor as it used to be. This 
reflects that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The report calculated the cost of special interest lobbying at  
$702.8 million for the last half of 1998. Communications and 
technology firms spent $94.3 million; followed by the 
finance-insurance sectors, with $91.8 million; and health-care 
firms, with $87.5 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The next highest spenders were energy and natural resources, the  
retail and services industries, transportation, agriculture, 
manufacturing, defense, real estate and construction and organized 
labor. 
</P>
<P>
	Among issues linked to lobbying expenses that Congress has or  
will consider are regulation of the Internet; mergers; services 
that banks, insurers and securities firms can provide; managed 
care; personal savings accounts; telecommunications; and world 
trade. 
</P>
<P>
	The lobbying ``exposes who the players are, who the big ones  
are,'' Cooper said. ``For the lobbying community it will be 
startling, because the report will show who else their client ... 
hired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Long-distance and local telephone companies led the spending in  
the communications field, followed by computer and electronics 
manufacturers, cable television firms and technology companies. In 
the financial and insurance fields, insurance companies, banks and 
financial firms and investment advisers were top spenders. 
</P>
<P>
	In the health-care sector, pharmaceutical companies, hospitals,  
health care systems, physicians, health maintenance organizations 
and medical plans were the top spenders, the report said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of the big-name companies and their trade associations that  
doled out large amounts of lobbying money: Sprint, AT&AMP;T, all the 
major regional phone companies, insurance groups such as American 
International, pharmaceutical firms including Pfizer. Trade groups 
with significant lobbying expenses included the Health Insurance 
Industry of America, the American Council of Life Insurance and the 
American Hospital Association. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
