<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Storm Victims Re-Establish Identity </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MOORE, Okla. (AP) -- People who lost all their identification in  
the Oklahoma tornadoes now have to prove that they are who they say 
they are. 
</P>
<P>
	Maps are being pulled out for people to point out where they  
once lived, and many are being asked for a thumbprint. 
</P>
<P>
	For many victims, the twisters that killed 41 people in Oklahoma  
carried away nearly all of their vital papers: birth certificates, 
driver's licenses, titles to homes and other documents. 
</P>
<P>
	In Midwest City, residents who ask for duplicate documents but  
have no ID are given a pop quiz to prove they were homeowners. 
Police records specialist Hazel Hamer takes out a map and asks them 
to point to where their houses were before the tornadoes blew them 
away. 
</P>
<P>
	``We realize some people have lost everything,'' she said. ``We  
just go by the map and we check the utility records to make sure 
the name and address on the bills match the addresses people are 
giving us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Larry Williamson of the state Department of Safety has processed  
applications for more than 100 driver's licenses over several days 
in a room at the First Baptist Church in Moore, which has been used 
as a service center for storm victims. 
</P>
<P>
	People have been offering everything from fishing licenses to  
American Association of Retired Persons membership cards to prove 
their identity. 
</P>
<P>
	``I took a guy awhile ago who had his entire criminal booking  
record with his name and address on it,'' Williamson said. ``He got 
his license.'' 
</P>
<P>
	To guard against fraud, Williamson calls up driving histories  
and quizzes applicants about speeding tickets, maiden names or how 
long they have been driving. 
</P>
<P>
	Everyone is asked to give a thumbprint, which scares away the  
criminals and gives state investigators some key evidence if the 
license is used to commit fraud, Williamson said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have had some people come into the exam stations who change  
their stories or don't know all the answers,'' he said. ``They 
leave pretty quickly.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kent and Kellie Taylor, married a decade ago, were among the  
lucky ones. Taylor had his driver's license in his pocket when he 
took cover in a closet with his children, ages 18 months and 9 
years, as the tornado ripped away the roof of their three-bedroom 
home. 
</P>
<P>
	He should be able to quickly replace his marriage license and  
his children's birth certificates. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know I'm still married to him and I'm not going to let him  
forget that,'' Mrs. Taylor joked Tuesday, as the couple drove 
through the rubble that once was their neighborhood. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 16:53:31 </DATE_TIME>
