<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bond Prices Fall After Weak Auction / Bonds  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Bond prices fell after a weak showing of demand  
for 5-year notes at an auction Tuesday, pushing the yield on the 
long Treasury bond to the highest level in nearly a year. 
</P>
<P>
	The price of the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond fell 19/32  
point, or $5.94 per $1,000 in face value. Its yield, which moves in 
the opposite direction, rose to 5.83 from 5.79 percent late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Treasury sold $15 billion of five-year notes at 5.367  
percent, an 11-month high, in the first leg of a two-day auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The news sent the price of the long bond, which was already down  
for the day, even lower. The resulting yield of 5.83 hasn't been 
seen since last May 27, when it reached 5.84. 
</P>
<P>
	With bond yields more competitive with stocks, equities prices  
also fell. The Dow Jones industrial average ended 18.90 higher at 
11,026.15, well off its highs of the day when it crossed the 11,100 
level. 
</P>
<P>
	In the broader market, prices of short-term Treasury securities  
fell between 1/16 point and 1/8 point. Intermediate maturities fell 
3/16 to 11/32 point, reported Bridge Telerate, a financial 
information service. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields on three-month Treasury bills were 4.60 percent as the  
discount was unchanged from Monday's auction price at 4.48 percent. 
Six-month yields were 4.69 percent, as the discount rose 0.01 
percentage point from Monday's auction price to 4.52 percent. 
One-year yields were 4.76 percent as the discount rose by 0.02 
percentage point from late Monday to 4.54 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Yields are the interest bonds pay by maturity, while the  
discount is the interest at which they are sold. 
</P>
<P>
	The federal funds rate, the interest on overnight loans between  
banks, remained unchanged at 4.69 percent from late Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In the tax-exempt market, the Bond Buyer index of 40 actively  
traded municipal bonds fell to 122 7/16 from 122 11/16 Monday. The 
average yield to maturity rose to 5.35 percent from 5.33 late 
Monday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
