<DOCNO> APW19990511.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 18:12:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> No Water Alarm on Sunken Tour Boat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- The operator of a tourist boat that  
sank in a minute, taking 13 people down with it, said at a hearing 
Tuesday that there was virtually no sign of trouble before the 
disaster. 
</P>
<P>
	Elizabeth Helmbrecht told the Coast Guard Marine Safety Board of  
Investigation that nothing appeared wrong until shortly before the 
Miss Majestic sank May 1. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she went down with the Miss Majestic and was near the  
bottom of Lake Hamilton before she managed to escape. 
</P>
<P>
	``You couldn't see anything, then water started coming in my  
nose and then I saw some light finally,'' said Helmbrecht, one of 
eight survivors. ``Then I saw only a few people kicking their feet 
and when I got up, there was only a few of them there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She began sobbing and was helped from the stand.  
</P>
<P>
	The accident happened two days after Helmbrecht had taken her  
boat to mechanics and complained that its bilge pump was switching 
on and off erratically. She said she was assured the repairs had 
been made and was confident that the boat was seaworthy. 
</P>
<P>
	Helmbrecht said the Miss Majestic tilted slightly left about  
five minutes after entering the water during the tour. She asked a 
passenger to move, thinking he could help balance the boat. But 
then, she said, water poured in from the rear and the bottom of the 
boat. 
</P>
<P>
	She said she yelled at passengers to get out and had no time to  
grab a life jacket. She said she tried to save a young boy as the 
boat went down, grabbing his hand and leading him toward an opening 
under the boat's canopy. He was jerked away from her, apparently by 
the force of the water, she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Helmbrecht said she had instructed passengers on how to use the  
boat's life preservers before it set out, as required by the boat's 
owner, Land and Lake Tours Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	But Robert Powers of Little Rock, one of the accident's  
survivors, said in an interview with The Associated Press last week 
that Helmbrecht gave no safety instructions. 
</P>
<P>
	In her testimony, Helmbrecht said she did not hear an alarm  
alerting occupants that water was coming into the boat, which was 
mandated by the Coast Guard after a Feb. 23 inspection. The 
company's lawyer said Monday it appeared the alarm had not been 
installed despite a March 11 deadline. 
</P>
<P>
	Other survivors are expected to testify at the weeklong Coast  
Guard hearing into the cause of the accident. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0039 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 09:35:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Unintended Victims at a Glance </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Since the bombing of Yugoslavia began on March 24, more than 100  
people have been reported killed by NATO's mistaken attacks on a 
refugee convoy, a passenger train, a market and hospital complex, 
residential neighborhoods and the Chinese Embassy. 
</P>
<P>
	Mistakes in warfare or times of high military tension are not  
new. Some examples from recent history: 
</P>
<P>
	April 1994: Two U.S. Air Force F-15s shoot down two U.S. Army  
helicopters on a diplomatic mission over Iraq, mistaking them for 
hostile aircraft in the ``no-fly zone,'' killing 26 people. No one 
was found criminally responsible. 
</P>
<P>
	February 1991: The United States bombs a shelter in Baghdad  
during the Persian Gulf War, killing more than 300 people. U.S. 
officials said it was an Iraqi military center and they did not 
know civilians were inside. U.S. public support for the war 
remained high despite the bombing. 
</P>
<P>
	January 1991: Seven U.S. Marines are killed when a missile fired  
by a U.S. Air Force A-10 attack aircraft hits their armored vehicle 
during a battle with the Iraqis. In all, more than 30 U.S. and nine 
British service members were killed by ``friendly fire'' during the 
war. 
</P>
<P>
	July 1988: U.S. warship Vincennes shoots down an Iranian  
passenger plane over the Persian Gulf, mistaking it for a 
threatening warplane, during the war between Iraq and Iran. All 290 
people aboard are killed. United States paid over $130 million in a 
1996 settlement that included compensation for families of the 
victims. 
</P>
<P>
	April 1986: U.S. bombing in Libya damages French Embassy but no  
one is hurt. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0040 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 05:25:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Cezanne Sells for $60.5 Million </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A Cezanne still life sold Monday for $60.5  
million, the fourth-highest price ever for a work of art sold at 
auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The painting, ``Still Life With Curtain, Pitcher and Bowl of  
Fruit,'' is ``as close to perfection as I have ever witnessed a 
work of art,'' Charles S. Moffett, a specialist in Impressionist 
and modern art for Sotheby's auction house, said after the sale. 
</P>
<P>
	In the painting, executed in 1893-1894, fruit spills across a  
simple table, balanced by a gray earthenware jug. 
</P>
<P>
	The price far exceeded Sotheby's estimate of $35 million. The  
previous record for a Cezanne sold at auction was $28.6 million at 
Sotheby's in 1993. 
</P>
<P>
	The Cezanne led a strong sale of artworks from the collection of  
socialite Betsey Cushing Whitney and her husband, John Hay ``Jock'' 
Whitney, a financier, collector and ambassador to Great Britain. 
</P>
<P>
	All buyers were anonymous.  
</P>
<P>
	The highest price ever paid for a painting at auction was $82.5  
million for van Gogh's ``Portrait of Dr. Gachet,'' sold by 
Christie's during the height of the art boom in 1990. 
</P>
<P>
	The second-highest was $78.1 million for Renoir's ``At the  
Moulin de la Galette,'' also in 1990, followed by $71.5 million for 
a van Gogh self-portrait that sold last fall. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
