<HEADLINE> `The Mummy' Takes In $44 Million / Box Office  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- ``The Mummy,'' a remake of the 1932 Boris  
Karloff classic, survived mixed reviews to set a record for the 
biggest movie opening ever outside summer, grossing $43.4 million 
over Mother's Day weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	The opening ranked 9th among the top 10 all-time weekends,  
according to final figures released Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Universal Studios President Ron Meyer said he had expected a  
debut closer to $30 million for the horror and special-effects film 
starring Brendan Fraser. The remake was Universal's third-largest 
opening, exceeded only by ``The Lost World: Jurassic Park'' ($90.2 
million) and ``Jurassic Park'' ($47 million). 
</P>
<P>
	Other top films in North America over the Mother's Day weekend  
included ``Entrapment,'' the Sean Connery cat-burglar adventure, 
dropping to No. 2 with a take of $12.3 million in its second 
weekend of release. The Keanu Reeves sci-fi movie ``The Matrix'' 
was third with $5.9 million in its sixth weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``Election,'' starring Reese Witherspoon and Matthew Broderick,  
was fourth with $3.2 million, followed by ``Never Been Kissed'' at 
$3 million and ``Analyze This'' $1.7 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Matrix'' leads 1999 films with $138.5 million, and  
``Analyze This'' with Robert DeNiro and Billy Crystal passed the 
$100 million mark after 10 weeks in theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	The top 20 movies at North American theaters Friday through  
Sunday, followed by distributing studio, gross, number of theater 
locations, average receipts per location, total gross and number of 
weeks in release, as compiled by Exhibitor Relations Co. Inc. and 
ACNielsen EDI Inc.: 
