<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Reporter Fired for Cancer Tales </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OWENSBORO, Ky. (AP) -- In frank and wrenching words, Kim Stacy  
told her rural Kentucky readers that her death was fast 
approaching. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm going to die! I'm going to die!'' she wrote recently in a  
series of columns in the Owensboro Messenger-Inquirer. ``I have 
terminal brain cancer. I was told I had about 10 months to a year 
to live.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But Ms. Stacy now admits she lied. The 33-year-old reporter  
isn't a victim of cancer, though she said she's been battling 
another illness for four years -- AIDS. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm terribly sorry. I didn't think about what I was doing,''  
she said Monday after being fired from the newspaper. ``I betrayed 
a lot of people and misled a lot of people including my own friends 
and family.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Stacy said she lied because of the stigma attached to AIDS.  
</P>
<P>
	``I grew up in a small-town atmosphere where you are crucified  
for having AIDS or being gay,'' said Ms. Stacy, who is a lesbian. 
``Nobody knew until this weekend that I have AIDS.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The newspaper's publisher, Ed Riney, said he feels compassion  
for Ms. Stacy's situation but also an obligation toward his 
readers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are victims and party to a hoax,'' he said. ``The news  
business is about checking the facts. We let our hearts overrun our 
reasoning in Kim's case.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Five of Ms. Stacy's columns were published in the  
Messenger-Inquirer, one of which was distributed in Kentucky by The 
Associated Press. A sixth was scheduled to run Sunday. 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Stacy said she decided to tell her editors that the columns  
were fabrications after being confronted by suspicious employees 
from the Appalachian News-Express in Pikeville, where she worked 
until March 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	News-Express publisher Marty Backus said Ms. Stacy told the  
newspaper staff four years ago she had terminal stomach cancer, but 
a later examination revealed the cancer had disappeared. 
</P>
<P>
	``Everybody was tickled,'' Backus said. ``We had her on prayer  
lists. We thought our prayers had been an answered.'' 
</P>
<P>
	When the News-Express published a special section about cancer  
survivors, Ms. Stacy's photo was put on the cover, Backus said. 
</P>
<P>
	A few months after joining the Messenger-Inquirer, Ms. Stacy  
told her co-workers her cancer had returned, the newspaper reported 
today. Later, she said it had been cured. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, she again told co-workers the cancer had  
returned. 
</P>
<P>
	Last year, two columnists resigned from The Boston Globe after  
allegations they falsified facts and invented people in their 
columns, and The New Republic fired a reporter for fabricating all 
or part of 27 magazine articles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0045 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:45:29 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Gun Shop Pulls Cheap Handguns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MILWAUKEE (AP) -- A gun store reportedly cited as leading the  
nation in sales of weapons later linked to crimes pulled cheap, 
so-called ``Saturday night special'' handguns from its shelves, at 
least temporarily. 
</P>
<P>
	``If people felt that was a problem, we decided to take them off  
the shelf,'' said Curtis Beatovic, one of the three owners of 
Badger Guns &AMP; Ammo in West Milwaukee. Guns that had been on sale at 
the store last week for $99.99 were gone Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	He said the handguns would be shipped back to manufacturers and  
declined to comment further. When asked about criticism over the 
sales of cheap handguns, he replied: ``A gun is a gun is a gun.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Federal tracing information complied by the U.S. Bureau of  
Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms showed Badger sold 1,060 guns between 
1996 and 1998 that later were recovered by authorities as linked 
with crimes. 
</P>
<P>
	The ATF has not announced full statistics on the survey but the  
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel reported Sunday that the Badger store 
ranked first nationwide among 80,000 federally licensed firearms 
dealers last year in crime-gun tracings. 
</P>
<P>
	James Fendry, leader of the Wisconsin Pro-Gun Movement, said  
Badger's move was temporary. 
</P>
<P>
	The gun store owners ``were concerned there might be some people  
who would come down and protest,'' Fendry said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were also concerned because they got a hailstorm of calls  
from people who wanted to come down and buy the cheaper handguns.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0046 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:33:41 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blazers Seek Sweep in 1st Round </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PHOENIX (AP) -- If the Portland Trail Blazers are going to move  
on and up in the playoffs, they're going to have to win on the 
road. A victory Wednesday night over Phoenix, and the resulting 
first-round sweep of the Suns, would be a great place to start. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blazers would not have the homecourt advantage against  
either Utah or San Antonio in a future playoff series. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got to play well on the road to be successful,'' Damon  
Stoudamire said. ``One way or another, we're going to have to start 
winning games on the road if we're ultimately going to get to the 
goal that we've wanted from the beginning of the season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Two victories in Portland left the Blazers on the brink of their  
first opening-round series triumph since Clyde Drexler and Terry 
Porter led them to the NBA Finals in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	The natural tendency is to ease up for Game 3. After all, the  
Blazers need just one victory in the next three games to win the 
best-of-5 series. But Portland coach Mike Dunleavy said title 
contenders shouldn't think that way. 
</P>
<P>
	``You've got to come in here with that urgency,'' Dunleavy said  
before the Blazers worked out at America West Arena on Tuesday. 
``It can't be the idea that we'll win one out of three. That is not 
the mindset of a team that's going very far. Our mindset has got to 
be that we've got to get it done in three, and anything less than 
three is not successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In an effort to resolve the matchup nightmare his team faces  
against Portland, Suns coach Danny Ainge kept Rex Chapman and Luc 
Longley on the bench most of Game 2 Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	After shooting just 3-for-12 and getting dominated by the  
Blazers' Isaiah Rider in Game 1, Chapman played just seven minutes 
in Game 2. Ainge played Randy Livingston, signed just before the 
last regular-season game, instead of Chapman in the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	``I have not lost confidence in Rex,'' Ainge said. ``I needed to  
make a change and it was a defensive change. I knew Rex would not 
be happy with it. That's what I love about Rex Chapman. That sucker 
loves to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Chapman shrugged off the situation, the latest setback in what  
has been a season of injuries and erratic shooting. 
</P>
<P>
	``I've just got to keep plugging away,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	Even Jason Kidd has struggled. He's shooting just .387 from the  
field (12-for-31), 3-for-12 from 3-point range. He has 19 
hard-earned assists but only six rebounds, half his season average. 
He was 5-for-16 from the field Monday night, 0-for-8 in the second 
half. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's been a very physical series,'' Kidd said. ``They've put  
three or four different guys on me. We knew going into the series 
that they were going to try to wear me down. I've done everything I 
could do, trying to get the ball to the right guy, running the 
team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	George McCloud said the Suns must get tough and quit letting the  
Blazers push them around. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our label anyway is that we're a finesse, soft team,'' McCloud  
said. ``We definitely need to be more aggressive, more physical. 
When they come to the hole to dunk, you've got to put them down. 
You've got to give him a hard foul. He may score but you've got to 
let him know he's got to pay the price.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Amen, Ainge said.  
</P>
<P>
	``I don't care how many fouls you've got, no layups,'' Ainge  
said. ``We've got to have more guys play that way.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stoudamire said Kidd suffers from his own reputation and his  
huge role on the team. 
</P>
<P>
	``Jason has so much responsibility for that team and he does so  
many things for that team,'' Stoudamire said. ``Even when it looks 
like he's not playing as well as he should, he's still playing 
well. I just think that's what the expectations have become for 
Jason Kidd.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The only bright spot for Phoenix has been its bench. The Suns  
reserves have outscored the deep and talented Portland bench 98-53 
in the first two games, 62-26 on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	But that is misleading because Portland's starters outscored the  
Suns starters 84-37 in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our starters have had such good games,'' Blazers reserve point  
guard Greg Anthony said. ``The strength of our team is that we ride 
the hot hand. J.R. (Rider) has a big game in Game 1. In Game 2, 
Damon has a big game. I'm the first to say `Hey, let them keep 
going.' When you're going good, you've got to ride it.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
