<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dollar Rallies Vs. Euro, Others </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The dollar rallied against most major currencies  
Tuesday after rising against the euro, which was hit again by 
lowered expectations of peace in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	The euro was quoted at $1.0715 in late trading in New York, down  
from $1.0782 late Monday. The dollar rose to 120.97 Japanese yen 
from 120.50 yen. 
</P>
<P>
	Traders have tied the euro's fortunes in recent weeks to the  
bombing in Kosovo, which begain in late March. Europe, with a 
stagnant economy, is expected to bear the brunt of the cost of 
rebuilding after the airstrikes end. 
</P>
<P>
	When Yugoslavia announced Monday that it was making a partial  
withdrawal of troops from Kosovo, the euro rose above $1.8000 for 
the first time in weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	But U.S. and NATO officials later said they saw no evidence of a  
withdrawal and continued heavy bombing on Tuesday. Traders dropped 
the euro and other currencies while buying dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	``The prospects for the war ending in Kovoso immediately have  
faded,'' said Anjum Sayyed, chief currency trader at the Buffalo, 
N.Y., office of Manufacturers &AMP; Traders Trust Co. ``That's given 
the dollar a boost and hurt the euro.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Also, the Dow Jones industrial average rose 94 points before  
falling and closing down about 4 points even as U.S. Treasury bond 
prices fell sharply, sending the benchmark 30-year Treasury bond 
yield up to 5.85 percent, a level not seen since last June. 
</P>
<P>
	Sayyed was optimistic about the dollar's performance after U.S.  
stocks failed to tank along with bond prices. 
</P>
<P>
	``The fact that the U.S. equity market has held up in the face  
of a weak bond market is giving (foreign) investors confidence that 
they can keep their assets invested in the U.S. equity market,'' 
Sayyed said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other trading Monday, the dollar was quoted at 1.5016 Swiss  
francs, up from 1.4899; and 1.4530 Canadian dollars, down from 
1.4613. 
</P>
<P>
	The British pound fell to $1.6234 from $1.6253.  
</P>
<P>
	Currencies of the 11 countries participating in the euro are no  
longer traded separately and are tied to the euro by a fixed rate. 
</P>
<P>
	Based on the euro's rate, the dollar was worth: 1.8255 German  
marks, up from 1.8139; 6.1237 French francs, up from 6.0827; and 
1,808.32 Italian lire, up from 1,795.33. 
</P>
</TEXT>
