<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Patriots Stadium Bill Is Introduced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- A bill allocating $70 million for a New England  
Patriots stadium was introduced Tuesday by Massachusetts House and 
Senate leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Gov. Paul Cellucci, House Speaker Thomas Finneran and Senate  
President Thomas Birmingham announced the filing of the bill at a 
Statehouse news conference. The bill would provide $70 million for 
such items as roads, sewers and other utilities. 
</P>
<P>
	The leaders said the bill could be the subject of a public  
hearing by Monday and then be passed by the House and Senate on 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It seems as if the end zone is in reasonable sight,'' Finneran  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Patriots owner Robert Kraft was absent from the news conference.  
And the elected leaders said they had had no input from Kraft while 
working on the bill. 
</P>
<P>
	But the leaders said they worked closely with the NFL on the  
bill and were assuming that meant it would be acceptable to Kraft. 
They also said that parts of the bill were the same as a bill that 
Kraft had supported last year. 
</P>
<P>
	``The NFL, I'm sure, has been in contact with Mr. Kraft,''  
Cellucci said. ``I'm sure they didn't have two of their top guys 
sitting down with us ... for the fun of it. There's a reason why 
those people were there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NFL issued a statement, saying the bill filing was ``an  
important step toward preserving the Patriots in Massachusetts.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We will study the impact of the proposed legislation and look  
forward to working closely with state officials to resolve any 
remaining issues promptly and cooperatively,'' the statement said. 
</P>
<P>
	The stadium is expected to cost $225 million and seat about  
68,000 fans. 
</P>
<P>
	The state will receive $1.4 million per year to help offset the  
cost of the infrastructure improvements: $400,000 from off-site 
parking operators located within three miles of the stadium and $1 
million from the team. 
</P>
</TEXT>
