<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0054 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 12:35:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ariz. Gov. Hull Addresses GOP Women </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Arizona's female governor urged a group of  
prominent Republican women to help further the rise of women in 
American politics by moving from ``slogans to substance.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The remarkable rise of women to political prominence in Arizona  
is one that could be repeated elsewhere in the country, Gov. Jane 
Hull told the Republican Women Leaders Forum, an organization of 
about 800 political and business leaders from 45 states. 
</P>
<P>
	Hull and four other women hold the top elected positions in  
Arizona, and are referred to as the ``Fab Five.'' Their power, Hull 
said, should be derived not merely from platitudes and slogans but 
from focusing on substantive issues and party unity. 
</P>
<P>
	``The way we do that is by sticking to the Republican agenda,''  
said Hull. ``That is how we will reach a point where electing 
women, especially Republican women, is commonplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She stressed that women can move beyond ``women's' issues'' and  
win elections by focusing on Republican ideals. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most significant thing we can do,'' Hull said, ``is to  
continue the transition from symbolism to substance in American 
politics.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
