<HEADLINE> Knoblauch Back in Yanks' Lineup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Chuck Knoblauch returned to the New York  
Yankees' lineup Tuesday night, five days after bruising his lower 
left leg while trying to turn a double play. 
</P>
<P>
	Knoblauch batted leadoff and played second base against Anaheim.  
He came back in time to face a tough pitcher for him -- he was only 
1-for-13 in his career against Angels starter Steve Sparks. 
</P>
<P>
	Knoblauch was injured when Minnesota's Corey Koskie rolled into  
him last Thursday at the Metrodome. Koskie was called out for 
interference while Knoblauch writhed on the ground. 
</P>
<P>
	Luis Sojo started at second base during a weekend series against  
Seattle and Chad Curtis batted leadoff. Yankees interim manager Don 
Zimmer was glad to see his All-Star able to play again. 
</P>
<P>
	``As long as he didn't break nothing. It could have been a  
disaster,'' Zimmer said before Tuesday night's game. ``So here he 
is playing tonight.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Roger Clemens, however, will remain on the disabled list at  
least until the weekend because of a bad left hamstring. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens is eligible to come off the DL on Thursday. But Zimmer  
said the pitcher will not be activated until Saturday ``at the 
earliest.'' The Yankees play the Chicago White Sox this weekend. 
</P>
<P>
	``If he feels anything, we don't want him to pitch,'' Zimmer  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemens is 2-0 despite a 5.47 ERA in five starts. He has won 17  
straight decisions since last season, tying the AL record. 
</P>
<P>
	With Clemens still out, Hideki Irabu was scheduled to start  
Thursday night and Orlando ``El Duque'' Hernandez was to pitch 
Friday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Ramiro Mendoza, meanwhile, will go back to the bullpen as a long  
reliever. He missed Sunday's start because of a viral infection. 
</P>
<P>
	``He hasn't pitched a bad game,'' Zimmer said. ``If Hideki can  
pitch well enough to stay in the rotation, we're a better team with 
Mendoza in the bullpen.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
