<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Finish Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices finished lower Tuesday as  
investors locked in profits following recent rapid advances. The 
U.S. dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 233.83  
points, or 1.38 percent, closing at 16,743.18. On Monday, the 
average gained 30.49 points, or 0.18 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.62 yen at mid-afternoon, down 0.24 yen  
from late Monday in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 
120.50 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, investors took profits after the Nikkei  
index surged to close at 17,300.61 points on Thursday -- its highest 
finish since Oct. 24, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Nikkei's 17,000 level prompts selling, but the downside is  
seen solid,'' said Hiroichi Nishi, deputy general manager at Nikko 
Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese blue chips were mixed following the sluggish  
performance of their U.S. counterparts overnight on Wall Street and 
the yen's rise against the dollar Monday, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen tends to make Japanese exports more expensive and  
thus less competitive abroad, while making imports cheaper in 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 18.04 points, or 1.31 percent, to 1,355.82 
points. The TOPIX closed up 5.44 points, or 0.40 percent, Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar slipped on news late Monday  
that the Yugoslav army had announced a partial withdrawal of 
military and police forces in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	But trades remained in a narrow range in the absence of fresh  
incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market today had no energy and was completely lifeless,''  
said Kenichi Hayashi, manager of the international treasury 
department at the Industrial Bank of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	There was little follow-through dollar selling Tuesday in the  
wake of the latest development in Kosovo, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.08 yen, up from  
129.38 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.340 percent from Monday's close of 1.335 percent, 
driving its price down to 104.08 yen from 104.13 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
