<DOCNO> APW19990511.0064 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 05:15:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Law Officer Deaths Drop in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Sixty-one law enforcement officers were  
murdered on duty in the United States during 1998, a decline of 
almost 13 percent from the previous year, the FBI reported Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	Releasing preliminary figures for 1998, the FBI said nine fewer  
officers were slain at work last year than the 70 killed in 1997. 
The drop is consistent with a nationwide decline in all types of 
crime since the mid-1990s. 
</P>
<P>
	Firearms continued to be the most frequent weapon for killing  
officers, with handguns accounting for 40 of the murders in 1998, 
rifles for 17 and a shotgun for 1. The other three were attributed 
to a vehicle, a blunt instrument and a bomb. 
</P>
<P>
	Arrest situations produced 16 of the murders: seven officers on  
drug-related investigations, six serving arrest warrants and three 
attempting to prevent robberies or catch robbers. Another 16 
officers were killed while answering disturbance calls. 
</P>
<P>
	An additional 10 murders were ambushes, nine came while  
enforcing traffic laws, six while investigating suspicious persons 
or circumstances and 4 while guarding prisoners. 
</P>
<P>
	Southern states saw the largest number of murders, 29, followed  
by Western states with 14, Midwestern states with 10, Northeastern 
states with three and Puerto Rico with five. 
</P>
<P>
	Thirty-four of the officers were wearing body armor when they  
died. Six were slain with their own weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	The 61 murders occurred in 55 separate incidents, and arrests  
have been made in 51 of them. Five suspects remain at large. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, accidental deaths of officers on duty rose by 15,  
from 62 in 1997 to 77 in 1998. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
