<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> 91-Year-Old Sentenced in Shooting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SPRINGFIELD, Mass. (AP) -- Despite a plea from the victim, a  
judge refused to jail a 91-year-old man who shot his 85-year-old 
neighbor at a senior citizens complex because he thought the man 
was annoying. 
</P>
<P>
	Leodore P. Menard, who pleaded guilty in the June 1998 shooting,  
told authorities he shot Robert H. Bell in the knee to get him back 
for being annoying. 
</P>
<P>
	At Monday's sentencing, Bell urged the judge to jail Menard,  
saying Menard would surely be jailed if he were younger. 
</P>
<P>
	Judge Thomas Curley agreed that a young adult would probably be  
headed to state prison, but the judge placed Menard on five years 
probation because of concerns about his health. Menard had not 
violated a law since 1925. 
</P>
<P>
	Menard, who had faced 10 years in prison on the conviction of  
assault and battery with a dangerous weapon on a person over the 
age of 65, can no longer care for himself and is confined to a 
nursing home, his lawyer said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
