<HEADLINE> AP Top News at Midnight EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Ambassador Leaves Embassy  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- U.S. Ambassador James Sasser left his battered  
embassy compound Wednesday morning as four days of protests 
subsided and China mournfully brought home the remains of three 
journalists killed in the NATO bombing of its embassy in 
Yugoslavia. The remains were returned hours after protests ebbed 
and state television for the first time aired U.S. and NATO 
apologies. Vice President Hu Jintao greeted the relatives of 
victims as they stepped on to the airport tarmac carrying urns and 
photographs. The more than 20 diplomats and embassy staff members 
wounded in the bombing also arrived and ambulances whisked them to 
hospitals. 

</P>
<P>
	NATO Airstrikes Continue  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO continued its airstrikes on  
Yugoslavia on Tuesday, saying it does not believe Serb forces are 
being withdrawn from Kosovo. At least seven people were killed in 
the attacks, Serb media said. NATO said there was no evidence 
Yugoslavia had withdrawn any of the estimated 40,000 troops and 
special police from the province. In Washington, Defense Secretary 
William Cohen said NATO will accept nothing less than a total 
withdrawal of forces from Kosovo as part of its conditions to halt 
the air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	White House Site Temporarily Down  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The White House Web site was taken off line  
after hackers reportedly angered by the NATO bombing of the Chinese 
Embassy in Belgrade, Yugoslavia, broke into the system. White House 
spokesman Barry Toiv confirmed that the site was shut down Monday 
evening for at least 24 hours after ``an attempt was made ... to 
break into the system that operates the White House Web page.'' NBC 
News reported that the hackers were based in Hong Kong and that 
they left behind cyber graffitti critical of the ongoing NATO 
operation in Kosovo. 

</P>
<P>
	Scottish Parties Fail on Coalition  
</P>
<P>
	EDINBURGH, Scotland (AP) -- Scotland's biggest parties failed  
again to reach an agreement on a coalition government Tuesday, as 
the country prepared for the opening of its first Parliament in 300 
years. After a marathon session of bargaining, the Labor and 
Liberal Democrat parties departed with key issues unresolved, 
including the Liberal Democrats' commitment to abolish university 
tuition fees. Coalition talks will resume Wednesday, after the 
Parliament officially opens with a swearing-in ceremony and 
presiding-officer elections. 

</P>
<P>
	WHO: World Faces New Disease Burden  
</P>
<P>
	GENEVA (AP) -- Ailments linked to an aging population and habits  
such as smoking will place added strain on developing countries, 
even as they struggle against AIDS, the World Health Organization 
said Tuesday. Noncommunicable diseases such as the world's top 
three killers -- heart disease, strokes and respiratory infections -- 
are expected to account for almost 75 percent of world illness by 
2020, up from 43 percent last year, according to the agency's 
annual World Health Report. The study also found that AIDS has 
displaced tuberculosis as the world's deadliest infectious disease. 

</P>
<P>
	Dominion To Buy CNG for $6.4B  
</P>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Columbia Energy Group on Tuesday withdrew  
its offer to buy Consolidated Natural Gas Co. after the 
Pittsburgh-based company accepted a revised $6.4 billion offer from 
Dominion Resources Inc. The merger between Dominion and CNG will 
create the nation's fourth-largest electric and natural gas 
utility. On April 18, Columbia Energy offered $6.68 billion in cash 
and stock for CNG despite a ``definitive merger agreement'' 
announced in February between CNG and Richmond, Va.-based Dominion 
Resources. 

</P>
<P>
	Tokyo Stocks Up at Midday  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Japanese stocks rose sharply Wednesday morning,  
following an advance on Wall Street. The dollar was slightly higher 
against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The Nikkei Stock Average climbed 361.31 points to finish the  
morning session at 17,104.49. 

</P>
<P>
	Avalanche Beat Red Wings 5-3  
</P>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Bill Ranford, the backup Detroit goaltender, ran  
out of luck and the Colorado Avalanche continued their winning ways 
on the road, snapping the Red Wings' playoff unbeaten streak with a 
5-3 victory tonight. The Avalanche got goals from Claude Lemieux, 
Theoren Fleury, Dale Hunter, Chris Drury and Aaron Miller. Steve 
Yzerman, Tomas Holmstrom and Vyacheslav Kozlov scored for the Red 
Wings. Detroit, seeking its third-straight Stanley Cup 
championship, has a 2-1 lead in the best-of-7 second-round series. 

</P>
<P>
	Timberwolves Even Series With Spurs  
</P>
<P>
	SAN ANTONIO (AP) -- Kevin Garnett scored 10 of his 23 points in  
the fourth quarter Tuesday night to lead Minnesota past the San 
Antonio Spurs 80-71 and even their Western Conference playoff 
series 1-1. With the victory, the eighth-seeded Timberwolves 
grabbed the homecourt advantage from the No. 1-seeded Spurs in the 
best-of-5 series. Game 3 is Thursday in Minnesota. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

