<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AOL Considers Net TV Possibilities </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- America Online Inc. took preliminary steps  
Tuesday toward bringing its service to TV sets, announcing 
partnerships with companies to develop equipment that would allow 
access to the Internet through televisions. 
</P>
<P>
	AOL will join DirectTV, Hughes Network Systems, Philips  
Electronics and Network Computer Inc., to develop set-top boxes to 
connect televisions to the Internet by using satellite dishes, 
high-speed digital subscriber lines and 56K modems. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Schuler, president of America Online's Interactive  
Services Group, said the proposed system would also allow viewers 
to watch TV while surfing the Internet. 
</P>
<P>
	The targeted audience, he said, are the 17 million AOL  
subscribers who already access the service through personal 
computers. While the computer will still be the main device used to 
access the servcice, he said, AOL would like to expand onto other 
appliances in the home. 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that this is a natural evolution of what is  
happening in the marketplace,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	Investors welcomed the news, sending AOL's stock sharply higher  
Tuesday. AOL shares gained $13.12 1/2 or 10.2 percent to $141.43 3/4 as 
the most active issue Tuesday on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Industry analysts saw the deals as a good first step toward  
AOL's goal of reaching viewers through other means besides the PC. 
</P>
<P>
	``They've pretty well maxed out the number of people signing up  
using computers,'' said Gerry Kaufhold, a multimedia and digital 
television analyst for Cahners In-Stat Group, a market research 
company for emerging technology in Boston. ``They have to expand 
their reach with a non-computer based solution before they get 
scooped by the broadband cable systems.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Kaufhold said AOL is getting pinched by AT&AMP;T, which is moving  
aggressively to provide high-speed hookups to the Internet using 
recently acquired cable systems. 
</P>
<P>
	``AOL is in a footrace,'' he said. ``It expands their turf from  
the 14-inch monitor in your den to the 36-inch TV in your living 
room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	If AOL succeeds in drawing in more viewers, it could increase  
their advertiser base and revenues. 
</P>
<P>
	The boxes are scheduled to be available some time in 2000, but  
the price would be announced later, said Schuler. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
