<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Family and Medical Leave Has Limits </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Q: Can anyone take time off for personal reasons under the  
Family and Medical Leave Act? 

</P>
<P>
	A: The 1993 Family and Medical Leave Act has helped an estimated  
20 million Americans get time off from work to care for a sick 
family member or new baby, or during their own serious illness. But 
the law has restrictions, and it's not open to all. 
</P>
<P>
	Generally, you can take up to 12 weeks off -- all at once or  
intermittently -- during a year if you work for a company that 
employs 50 or more people. You have to work a minimum of 1,250 
hours a year, which is the equivalent of at least 25 hours a week 
for 50 weeks, in the year before your leave. Vacation time doesn't 
count. 
</P>
<P>
	Teachers and top executives, however, aren't as free as others  
to take the time whenever they like. 
</P>
<P>
	School districts may ask teachers to coordinate their returns in  
a way that doesn't disrupt classrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	Executives in the top 10 percent of a company's pay scale may  
not have their jobs guaranteed if their leave harms the firm. But 
the company has the burden of proof. 
</P>
<P>
	You also can't take this kind of leave to care for your third  
cousin-once-removed. If you, your parent, spouse or your child is 
seriously ill or you have or adopt a new baby, you can apply. But 
if your mother-in-law is ill, your spouse must take the leave. 
</P>
<P>
	Not all sicknesses fit the bill, either. The law mandates time  
off for people with ``serious health conditions.'' That means 
anyone who is hospitalized, but it also means people who need 
continuing medical treatment. You may be able to leave if you have 
severe morning sickness or a back problem, and you can take leave 
to drive your father to physical therapy after his stroke. 
</P>
<P>
	The law may seem a bit confusing, but it's a blessing for people  
who need time off. 
</P>
<P>
	If you need help figuring it out, check with your human  
resources department or the National Partnership for Women &AMP; 
Families, a nonprofit group that helped draft the law. The 
Partnership Web site (www.nationalpartnership.org) has a wealth of 
information on the law. 
</P>
<P>
	If you think your rights have been violated, find an employment  
lawyer or call the Labor Department's Wage and Hour Department 
information line at 1-800-959-FMLA. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0079 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 12:25:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Energy Dept. Upgrades Security Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Stung by an espionage scandal, Energy  
Secretary Bill Richardson said Tuesday he will halt the 
administration's aggressive declassification of Cold War-era 
nuclear documents. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's critical that we guard our secrets more thoroughly,'' he  
said in an interview, and there has been some concern that the 
declassification program was moving too fast. 
</P>
<P>
	Richardson also said he will consolidate the department's $800  
million widely dispersed security operation under a single 
``security czar,'' who will report directly to him, and will impose 
new restrictions on access to the most secure computer systems at 
the national nuclear laboratories. 
</P>
<P>
	Criticism has been widespread in Congress about security  
problems at the government's nuclear weapons research labs and 
reports of theft of nuclear secrets -- in the 1980s and possibly as 
late as 1995 -- at the Los Alamos lab in New Mexico. 
</P>
<P>
	Intelligence specialists have argued that part of the security  
problems stems from the wide array of declassified weapons-related 
data that is exchanged among scientists. Growing alarm about theft 
as well as access to information on the Internet has sparked 
re-examination of the rush to declassify. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's some concern that we're moving too fast,'' said  
Richardson. 
</P>
<P>
	He said there will be an 18-month moratorium on the aggressive  
declassification efforts involving defense-related documents that 
were ordered by former Energy Secretary Hazel O'Leary during 
President Clinton's first term. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're reversing that. We believe it's critical that we guard  
our secrets more thoroughly,'' Richardson said. He said the program 
would be reviewed over the next 18 months with plans ``to slow down 
some of the declassification.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Energy Department has been criticized in the past for its  
secretiveness. When O'Leary became secretary in 1993, she overruled 
reservations from some of the DOE's defense and security experts 
and began an aggressive move toward more openness. Declassification 
efforts were stepped up further after the disclosure in 1993 of 
improper radiation experiments on people in the early days of the 
Cold War. 
</P>
<P>
	Now, 10 congressional committees are looking into Energy  
Department security lapses and the administration's handling of the 
Los Alamos espionage case, which has focused on alleged activities 
dating back to the 1980s of a Taiwan-born scientist. The scientist, 
Wen Ho Lee, was fired March 8 for security violations but has not 
been charged with a crime. He has denied he ever provided secrets 
to China or anyone else. 
</P>
<P>
	A voluminous still-secret congressional report detailing  
widespread security problems at the labs -- including details about 
the Lee investigation -- is expected to be made public next week. 
</P>
<P>
	Trying to blunt some of the attacks, Richardson said Tuesday he  
is streamlining the department's security efforts under one office, 
headed by a ``security czar'' who will have ``juice and clout'' and 
report directly to him. No one has been named, but Richardson said 
he wants ``a three-star general with extensive security 
background.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a dramatic change because it consolidates all the  
security empires at the DOE that have not coordinated with each 
other into one single unit accountable to me,'' Richardson said. 
The counterintelligence office would remain separate, also 
reporting directly to the secretary. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody's been willing to tackle these very thorny security  
problems. The time has come,'' Richardson said. 
</P>
<P>
	The new security office also will consolidate computer security  
programs that currently are split between two offices, one 
responsible for classified systems and the other for unclassified 
systems. 
</P>
<P>
	Investigators recently found at Los Alamos that more than 1,000  
files of top-secret nuclear weapons codes were found in an 
unsecured computer belonging to Lee, the scientist dismissed on 
March 8. It is believed the consolidation of security offices might 
reduce the risks of such transfers in the future. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier this year, Richardson reinforced the department's  
counterintelligence office and directed that it report directly to 
him. To head the office, he hired Ed Curran, a former CIA official 
and still one of the FBI's top counterintelligence experts. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
