<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Golf Notes  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	IRVING, Texas (AP) -- International Management Group wants him.  
So do three or four other individual agents. Carlos Franco has an 
answer for them all. 
</P>
<P>
	Gracias, but no.  
</P>
<P>
	Franco, who became only the second player from South America --  
and the first from Paraguay -- to win on the PGA Tour, prefers to 
cut his own deals. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm my own boss,'' he said Tuesday at the GTE Byron Nelson  
Classic. 
</P>
<P>
	That means not being tied down to corporate outings or feeling  
pressure to play certain events. Franco can take three weeks off if 
he wants and answer to nobody. His caddie, Doc Docherty of 
Vancouver, takes care of tournament commitments. 
</P>
<P>
	Franco takes care of the money.  
</P>
<P>
	He had a Japanese manager, who helped him sign his deal with  
Callaway Golf. But even with the potential to blossom into a star, 
Franco would rather go it alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``I would have to take a cut,'' he said. ``I don't want to do  
that. I have one contract written in English and one in Spanish, so 
it's no problem. What's important is the money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	For a guy who grew up barefooted in a shack in Paraguay, Franco  
is doing quite nicely in his first year on the tour. He got 
$468,000 for winning the Compaq Classic in New Orleans, moving him 
up to 12th on the money list with $814,520. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of that money will go toward his new house at Doral Resort  
in Miami, which is only an eight-hour flight from Paraguay. 
</P>
<P>
	``They speak Spanish there,'' Franco said. ``And my wife doesn't  
speak English.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The best perk for winning on tour was a limousine ride to the  
Hilton that tournament officials in New Orleans lined up. 
</P>
<P>
	``That was my first time in a limo,'' he said. ``We had  
champagne, but no women. Just five Colombians, a Puerto Rican and a 
Mexican.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Next up for Franco is trying to get into the U.S. Open without  
having to go through the final stage of qualifying at Colonial 
Country Club in Memphis, Tenn. Franco could gain an exemption by 
either winning another tournament or moving into the top 10 on the 
money list by the end of the Kemper Open. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *WHOA, NELLIE:* With Tiger Woods, Ernie Els and several top  
players taking appearance money to play the Deutsche Bank Open in 
Germany next week, the Colonial Invitational was believed to have 
the weaker of the two fields during the swing through the 
Dallas-Fort Worth area. 
</P>
<P>
	That may not be the case any longer.  
</P>
<P>
	Els and Vijay Singh decided not to play the Nelson Classic, and  
David Duval also decided last month that he would take the week off 
and play Colonial instead. On Monday, Payne Stewart backed out 
because he felt he needed a break, and Ben Crenshaw withdrew when 
his father died. 
</P>
<P>
	That leaves only Woods among the top seven on the money list  
playing in Dallas. A year ago, the Nelson had seven of the top 10 
money-leaders. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Woods remains the biggest draw on tour, and the Nelson  
is a sellout for the third consecutive year. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *BEER BLAST:* Kelly Gibson of New Orleans was so distraught over  
the 9 he made on No. 15 at English Turn in the third round of the 
Compaq Classic that he decided to make it up to the friends who 
were following him. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson promised to buy them a beer on Sunday for every birdie he  
made. He wound up with four birdies in the final round, and his 
three brothers bought 18 beers. 
</P>
<P>
	``I played early, so it was probably too soon for a lot of  
people to drink beer,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The beer cost Gibson about $63, but the 15th hole turned out to  
be even more expensive. 
</P>
<P>
	Gibson made a quadruple bogey and a bogey on the par-5 in the  
last two rounds. Had he made par on the hole both days, he would 
have finished in a tie for 12th instead of 51st. 
</P>
<P>
	The difference? About $40,000.  
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SHELL SCHEDULE:* In what could be a preview for next year on  
the senior tour, Tom Watson will play Hale Irwin in the last of 
five matches on Shell's Wonderful World of Golf. 
</P>
<P>
	The 1999 series will begin in South Africa with Nick Price  
playing Ernie Els at Leopard Creek. Two of the straightest hitters 
in the game, Jim Furyk and Colin Montgomerie, will play the Paris 
Golf Club in France. 
</P>
<P>
	Shell also is including the women. Karrie Webb, already a  
four-time winner this year on the LPGA Tour, is scheduled to play 
Dinah Shore champion Dottie Pepper. The other match will feature 
Fred Couples against John Daly at Crosswater Golf Club in Oregon. 
</P>
<P>
	The matches, which will be shown at 8:30 p.m. on ESPN, start  
Sept. 21. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *SENIOR STABLEFORD:* The Royal Caribbean Classic in Key  
Biscayne, Fla., will become the first Senior PGA Tour event to play 
under the Stableford scoring system. 
</P>
<P>
	The Royal Caribbean, the first full-field tournament on the  
Senior tour, joins the Sprint International in Castle Rock, Colo., 
as the only PGA-sanctioned events to use the Stableford. 
</P>
<P>
	Tournament director John Marovich said the change will ``set  
ourselves apart from the other Senior PGA Tour events.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Players earn two points for birdies, five points for eagles and  
eight points for double eagles. They lose one point for a bogey and 
three points for a double bogey or worse. 
</P>
<P>
	``When we asked the players their opinion, the response was  
overwhelming,'' he said. ``It will be a fun way for them to begin 
their season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Changes to the course to make sure the risk-reward opportunities  
exist include the 18th hole being changed from a par-4 to a par-5. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *DIVOTS:* Steve Flesch has now finished second in his last three  
tournaments in Louisiana -- the last two PGA Tour events in New 
Orleans, and a Nike Tour stop in Lafayette. .... Chip Beck tied for 
31st in New Orleans, his best finish since the Buick Open in 1996. 
... Peter Dawson has been named to replace Michael Bonallack as 
secretary of the Royal &AMP; Ancient Golf Club. Dawson, a Scotsman, 
will join the R&AMP;A on June 1 and work with Bonallack until he 
officially steps down Sept. 14. ... Along with playing his first 
PGA Tour event as a professional, 19-year-old Sergio Garcia is 
studying for his driver's license exam. 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *STAT OF THE WEEK:* Carlos Franco became the fifth player from  
the International team in the Presidents Cup to win on the PGA Tour 
this year. The others are Ernie Els (Nissan) Steve Elkington 
(Doral), Vijay Singh (Honda), Ernie Els (Los Angeles) and Stuart 
Appleby (Houston). 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	 *FINAL WORD:* ``I'm better known than Bill Clinton.'' -- Carlos  
Franco, on his popularity in Paraguay. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
