<DOCNO> APW19990511.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:18:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Journalists' Remains Arrive in China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- The remains of three Chinese killed in NATO's  
bombing of China's embassy in Yugoslavia were returned to Beijing 
early Wednesday, hours after protests ebbed and state television 
for the first time aired U.S. and NATO apologies for the attack. 
</P>
<P>
	Vice President Hu Jintao greeted the relatives of those killed  
as they stepped on to the Beijing airport tarmac carrying urns and 
photographs. The more than 20 diplomats and embassy staff members 
wounded in the bombing also arrived and ambulances quickly whisked 
them to at least three separate hospitals. 
</P>
<P>
	The government bused in 1,000 school children, soldiers, factory  
and office workers and other officials and distributed flowers and 
flags to greet the plane from the Yugoslav capital, Belgrade. 
</P>
<P>
	Flags on government buildings and in Beijing's central Tiananmen  
Square were lowered to half-staff, as were the American flags at 
the U.S. Embassy and consulates. 
</P>
<P>
	A planned live television broadcast of the arrival had been  
expected to heighten emotions over the bombing. But streets were 
quiet outside the U.S. Embassy where angry protesters rallied over 
the past four days. 
</P>
<P>
	Police checked identity papers and turned people away from the  
entrance to the officially sanctioned protest route snaking past 
the U.S. and British embassies. 
</P>
<P>
	In a telephone interview Tuesday from the paint-spattered  
embassy where he remained holed up for a fourth day, U.S. 
Ambassador James Sasser said, ``Tomorrow is a critical day.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Protesters hurled bits of concrete and shouted anti-American  
slogans as they passed by the battered embassy Tuesday, but their 
numbers were in the hundreds, not the thousands who menacingly 
streamed by the previous three days. Police controlled access to 
the marked-off, seven-block protest route, turning some away and 
asking others to discard the projectiles they carried. 
</P>
<P>
	After nightfall, police closed the protest route. Frustrated  
Chinese pushed against the police line but dispersed after a 
scuffle and the apparent arrest of one demonstrator. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Sasser called the new controls ``an enormous  
improvement,'' he was staying put. Violence persisted and police 
had refused to allow back into the embassy staff members who left, 
he said. ``So you run the risk once you leave of not being able to 
get back in.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Angered by Friday's bombing of a symbolic piece of China's  
territory, Chinese have protested in 20 cities nationwide in the 
largest demonstrations since the Communist Party used the military 
to crush the Tiananmen Square democracy movement 10 years ago. 
Protesters have thrown gas and stink bombs at the U.S. Embassy and 
set fire to the U.S. consul's residence in Chengdu. 
</P>
<P>
	Chinese leaders have refused to condemn the violence, abetted by  
party-run organizations and slanted coverage in the exclusively 
state-controlled media. 
</P>
<P>
	In his first direct comments on the protests, President Jiang  
Zemin called NATO's bombing ``a provocation to 1.2 billion Chinese 
people.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``The Chinese people have used protests, meetings, statements  
and all sorts of methods to express their utmost indignation. It 
shows the fervor, will and strength of the great patriotic spirit 
of the Chinese people,'' state media quoted Jiang as telling 
Russian envoy Viktor Chernomyrdin, who was in the Chinese capital 
for talks on the Kosovo crisis. 
</P>
<P>
	Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu Bangzao repeated assurances that  
embassies and diplomatic personnel would be protected. He called 
the protests lawful and did not condemn outright the rock-throwing 
or arson. 
</P>
<P>
	``If those overreactions were seen to be supported by the  
Chinese government, that is a misunderstanding,'' Zhu said, without 
being more specific. 
</P>
<P>
	State media carried reports of President Clinton's Monday  
apology and reported that Secretary of State Madeleine Albright 
went to the Chinese Embassy in Washington on Saturday to apologize 
and promise a full accounting. TV news carried footage of Clinton 
saying he had apologized to Jiang, and NATO Secretary-General 
Javier Solana was shown expressing his regrets. 
</P>
<P>
	The absence of reports on the apologies had helped inflame  
protesters, who called the attack intentional. Tuesday's coverage 
did not mitigate official outrage. The official Xinhua News Agency 
reported late Tuesday that the words of regret ``were not the open 
and just apology demanded by the Chinese government.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While noting the apology, Foreign Ministry spokesman Zhu said  
China was waiting for more and reiterated demands for a complete 
investigation and criminal punishment of those responsible. He 
dismissed NATO explanations that the bombing resulted from 
misinformation by CIA target planners. 
</P>
<P>
	``How could the joint intelligence source of the most powerful  
military alliance in the world mistakenly identify the location of 
a large diplomatic mission with a big courtyard, a plate on the 
front door and flying the national flag?'' Zhu told reporters at a 
routine briefing. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials continued Tuesday to express deep  
regrets over the bombing, but the apologies were mixed with concern 
over rising anti-American sentiment and demonstrations in China. 
</P>
<P>
	In Washington, Secretary of Defense William Cohen suggested  
Beijing was overreacting and not giving the Chinese people an 
accurate enough account of what had actually taken place. 
</P>
<P>
	It ``defies all logic'' for anyone to suggest the attack was  
deliberate, Cohen told a Senate committee. 
</P>
<P>
	Jiang met with Chernomyrdin, the Russian envoy, who is trying to  
persuade China not to block a U.N. Security Council resolution that 
Russia and the seven major industrialized powers agreed to last 
week. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Chernomyrdin told reporters that he and Jiang had agreed  
the bombing in Yugoslavia must stop before peace talks can be held. 
But he also said it was necessary to go ahead with the G-8 plan to 
withdraw Yugoslav forces from Kosovo and deploy an international 
security force. 
</P>
<P>
	On the heels of suspending military, arms control and human  
rights contacts with the United States, China canceled a planned 
visit next week by Gen. Charles Krulak, commandant of the Marine 
Corps, U.S. defense officials said. They added that Cohen's planned 
trip to China in June now appears unlikely. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambassador Sasser said ``one of the great tragedies'' of the  
embassy bombing was the harm it did to U.S.-China relations so soon 
after Premier Zhu Rongji's visit to the United States last month. 
</P>
<P>
	Sasser hoped that ``once everyone has vented their feeling of  
anger and frustration that wiser heads will prevail and we'll move 
back in the direction of trying to establish a productive and 
stable relationship between our two countries.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials continued to express deep regrets over  
the bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade, but the apologies 
were mixed with concern over rising anti-American sentiment and 
demonstrations in China. 
</P>
<P>
	Cohen, in his Senate testimony, suggested Beijing was  
overreacting and not giving the Chinese people an accurate enough 
account of what had actually taken place. 
</P>
<P>
	He said it ``defies all logic'' for anyone to suggest the attack  
was deliberate. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
