<DOCNO> APW19990511.0090 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 12:25:17 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ark. Boat Apparently Missing Alarm </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HOT SPRINGS, Ark. (AP) -- The owner of a tour boat that sank  
earlier this month, killing 13 people, had apparently not followed 
a Coast Guard order to install an alarm that warns when a vessel is 
taking on water, the owner's lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors said the Miss Majestic took on water quickly May 1 and  
sank in less than a minute. The operator of the boat has told 
investigators that she did not believe the bilge pump activated and 
that she had no warning before the vessel went down in about 60 
feet of water. 
</P>
<P>
	At a Coast Guard investigative hearing Tuesday, a Coast  
Guardsman who inspected the amphibious tour boat about two months 
before it sank in Lake Hamilton said he declared the vessel fit 
despite a number of problems he found. 
</P>
<P>
	Among nine items that Chief Warrant Officer Troy Collins wanted  
dealt with were installation of an alarm to indicate the boat was 
taking on water. 
</P>
<P>
	``Even with these items here, I still considered the vessel  
fit,'' Collins said of his Feb. 23 inspection. 
</P>
<P>
	Lt. Robert Bowen, supervisor for marine inspections at the Coast  
Guard station in Memphis, Tenn., told the investigation board 
Monday that the boat's approval came with the condition that the 
bilge alarm and a device for detecting flammable vapors be 
installed, in accordance with new Coast Guard regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	The boat's owner had until March 11 to install the equipment,  
but Bowen could not say whether the Coast Guard checked to see that 
the deadline was met. 
</P>
<P>
	Q. Byrum Hurst Jr., a lawyer for boat owner Don Bridges, said  
that the vapor detection device may have been installed but that he 
did not believe the vessel had a bilge alarm when it went down. 
</P>
<P>
	Collins testified that he had not inspected a duck boat -- which  
operates on land and in water -- in five years when he inspected 
four such craft belonging to Land and Lake Tours Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked to look over several photographs of the boat after it was  
raised from the bottom fo the lake, Collins pointed out several 
possible violations of Coast Guard regulations. 
</P>
<P>
	One was the attachment of a life preserver to the boat with what  
appeared to be a bicycle chain. He also said four child's life 
preservers appeared to be obstructed and may not have been easily 
accessible in an emergency. 
</P>
<P>
	Under questioning, Collins said he would not have certified the  
boat as seaworthy had he seen a life preserver secured by a chain. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coast Guard panel's esponsibility is to determine what  
caused the accident and make recommendations on preventing such 
tragedies. The hearing is expected to take a week. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
