<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> FBI Sets Up Internet Fraud Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LAKE BUENA VISTA, Fla. (AP) -- It's hard to fight Internet crime  
when you don't even have a solid idea about how much commerce there 
is -- or how much fraud actually occurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Law enforcement officials will be getting some needed  
assistance. The FBI and several anti-fraud groups announced Monday 
they are establishing an Internet Fraud Complaint Center and 
forming the Internet Fraud Council. 
</P>
<P>
	The center and the council will be modeled after the  
Atlanta-based Centers for Disease Control, which collects health 
data and tracks health trends. 
</P>
<P>
	``The goal is to give law enforcement significant support in  
investigating these cases,'' said Richard Johnston, director of the 
National White Collar Crime Center, which is joining the FBI in 
developing the center in a private-public partnership. 
</P>
<P>
	The Internet crime-fighting effort was announced at the Economic  
Crime Summit conference at Walt Disney World. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet crimes range from credit card fraud to pyramid scams to  
securities fraud. Authorities said they have no idea how much 
Internet commerce takes place -- estimates range from $9 billion to 
$108 billion -- and even less of a clue how much Internet fraud 
occurs. 
</P>
<P>
	Part of the mission of the Internet Fraud Council will be to  
give law enforcement a picture of how big Internet crime really is. 
The council, supported by the National Fraud Center, the National 
Coalition for the Prevention of Economic Crime and the National 
White Collar Crime Center, will also provide training against 
Internet fraud and create forecasts of fraudulent activity. 
</P>
<P>
	The National Fraud Center is a Horsham, Pa.-based fraud and risk  
management consulting firm. The National White Collar Crime Center 
is a federally funded research and consulting firm based in 
Richmond, Va. The privately financed National Coalition for the 
Prevention of Economic Crime is a research organization that aims 
to educate the private sector about economic fraud. 
</P>
<P>
	The complaint center will take information on its Web site from  
Internet crime victims. The center plans to link its Web site with 
law enforcement sites around the nation so victims can make 
reports. Those reports will allow the FBI to analyze trends and 
notify local law enforcement if action is needed. 
</P>
<P>
	An address for the Web site has yet to be determined. The center  
is scheduled to open in late summer in a yet-to-be-selected 
location in West Virginia and will eventually employ 135 people. 
</P>
<P>
	The popularity of the Internet has changed the face of crime,  
authorities said at the conference. Internet criminals are 
increasingly well-educated and female. 
</P>
<P>
	And they are no longer constrained by borders and boundaries.  
They are as likely to commit crimes over the Internet from Bozeman, 
Mont., as from Manama, Bahrain. 
</P>
<P>
	Because cyber-criminals can move about easily, it is even more  
crucial that law enforcement share information with each other, 
officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Cyber-criminals don't have the financial limits of law  
enforcement and many upgrade their computer equipment and software 
every six months, authorities said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Criminals aren't saddled with taking the lowest bid when  
buying equipment,'' said Florida Department of Law Enforcement 
Commissioner Tim Moore. ``They don't have a lot of albatrosses 
around their neck.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0093 </DOCNO>
