<DOCNO> APW19990511.0096 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 12:25:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Clarifies ACLU Complaints Story </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- An Associated Press story May 9 about  
complaints received by American Civil Liberties Union offices 
around the country gave an incomplete account of one ACLU 
official's position on school safety. 
</P>
<P>
	Eleanor Eisenberg, executive director of the ACLU in Arizona,  
was quoted in the story as saying: ``Schools are saying that school 
safety comes first and students' rights second. That's wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Eisenberg said that when she made the statement she was  
paraphrasing the following quotation from Benjamin Franklin: ``They 
that can give up essential liberty to obtain a little temporary 
safety deserve neither liberty nor safety.'' 
</P>
<P>
	She said denying civil liberties was not a solution to the  
problem of alienation and violence by young people. But she did not 
mean to suggest that the safety of children was less important than 
student rights. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
