<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 5 a.m EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	U.S. Says NATO Demands Must Be Met  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The Clinton administration says that without a  
full Yugoslav agreement to NATO's central demands, bombing will 
continue against its troops and their support structure even if 
President Slobodan Milosevic does as he announced and withdraws 
some of his forces from Kosovo. Entering the 49th day of Operation 
Allied Force today, the Western alliance is insisting that in 
addition to a complete troop withdrawal, Milosevic must agree to 
grant the Serbian province autonomy and allow displaced ethnic 
Albanians to return under the protection of an international 
military force. 

</P>
<P>
	Sasser: US-China Dispute an Aberrration  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Ambassador James Sasser believes the flap over  
the mistaken U.S. bombing of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade is an 
aberration that the two sides will overcome. Sasser said he is 
encouraged by signs of a Chinese willingness for the first time to 
permit the media to publish U.S. expressions of condolences over 
the loss of life in Belgrade and the apologies of President Clinton 
and other senior officials. But Chinese President Jiang Zemin has 
yet to accept a telephone call from Clinton, and other Chinese 
officials are continuing to cast doubt on the American claim that 
last week's bombing was an accident. 

</P>
<P>
	Death sentence for Gandhi Assassins  
</P>
<P>
	NEW DELHI, India (AP) -- India's Supreme Court commuted the death  
sentences of 22 defendants today in the 1991 assassination of 
former Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi, but ordered that four others in 
the case must face capital punishment. Three of the defendants were 
given life sentences. Two people were acquitted, and 17 others were 
ordered released after receiving sentences less than the nearly 
eight years they have been held. A court in the southern city of 
Madras had sentenced all 26 to death in January 1998 after a trial 
that lasted six years. 

</P>
<P>
	Clinton Seeks To Bolster US Markets  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying American businesses must invest in  
markets at home as they do abroad, President Clinton is appealing 
to the nation's chief executives to join the effort to breathe new 
life into cities and rural areas missing out on the current 
economic boom. The president was convening a meeting today at the 
White House with 15 business leaders to discuss ways to bolster 
private investment in economically distressed communities. 
Afterward, Clinton was traveling to Atlanta for more discussions 
with CEOs and a tour of the Sweet Auburn Market, located near the 
Martin Luther King Jr. historic district, to see an example of the 
type of economic development he hopes to generate in other areas. 

</P>
<P>
	UN Council Still Far Apart on Iraq  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- Despite weeks of negotiations and warnings  
that inaction will only make matters worse, the Security Council 
appears to have made little headway in forging an agreement on a 
new policy towards Iraq. Sporadic bombing of targets in Iraq has 
continued and Baghdad's goal of getting the council to lift the 
economic sanctions imposed after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait is 
still a long way off. While some council members regularly express 
concern that Iraq's weapons programs are not being monitored -- and 
U.N. weapons inspectors are barred from returning to Baghdad -- 
major differences remain on how to resume oversight of Iraq's 
disarmament. 

</P>
<P>
	Japan Auto Import Sales Fall  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Hurt by the continuing recession, sales of imported  
cars, trucks and buses in Japan slipped 0.6 percent on year in 
April, an industry group reported today. Total import sales in 
April amounted to 19,962 vehicles, down from 20,084 the same month 
a year ago -- the second straight monthly drop, the Japan Automobile 
Importers Association said. 

</P>
<P>
	Japanese Stock Prices Finish Lower  
</P>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices finished lower today. The Nikkei  
dropped 233.83 points to close at 16,743.18. 

</P>
<P>
	Dodgers 4, Cubs 3  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Raul Mondesi hit a pair of two-run homers off  
Steve Trachsel, and Ismael Valdes pitched six effective innings 
despite constant trouble last night as the Los Angeles Dodgers beat 
the Chicago Cubs 4-3. Mondesi, who has 11 home runs this season, is 
12-for-34 with seven homers against Trachsel in his career. Mondesi 
homered to right-center with one out in the fourth, and hit another 
to left-center with one out in the sixth for the 10th multihomer 
game of his career. 

</P>
<P>
	Padres 7, Marlins 5  
</P>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- Reggie Sanders hit a two-run homer in the  
eighth inning last night, lifting the San Diego Padres over the 
Florida Marlins 7-5. Dan Miceli struck out the only two batters. 
The Marlins lost for the eighth time in 10 games. Padres center 
fielder Ruben Rivera was carried off the field on a stretcher with 
a back injury. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by VINCENT K. WILLIS  
</P>
</TEXT>
