<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dominion To Buy CNG for $6.4B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	RICHMOND, Va. (AP) -- Spurning Columbia Energy Group,  
Consolidated Natural Gas Co. chose to accept Dominion Resources 
Inc.'s revised $6.4 billion acquisition offer, paving the way for 
the creation of the nation's fourth-largest electric and natural 
gas utility. 
</P>
<P>
	On April 18, Columbia Energy offered $6.68 billion in cash and  
stock for CNG. The offer came despite a ``definitive merger 
agreement'' announced in February between CNG and Richmond, 
Va.-based Dominion Resources. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are disappointed in the CNG board's decision,'' said Oliver  
G. Richard III, chairman, president and chief executive officer of 
Columbia Energy, adding that the Herndon, Va.-based company was 
withdrawing its offer for CNG. 
</P>
<P>
	The revised deal with Dominion Resources will give CNG  
shareholders a combination of cash and Dominion stock worth $66.60 
for each CNG share. The original deal had been an all-stock offer, 
but Dominion Resources sweetened the offer by guaranteeing its cash 
value. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy had offered $70 a share for CNG stock -- $45.50  
in cash and $24.50 in stock. 
</P>
<P>
	CNG said Tuesday night that the new Dominion Resources offer was  
better ``due to its certainty and timing, the strategic benefits of 
a gas and electric combination, and the upside potential to 
shareholders of an investment in the combined CNG-Dominion.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We believe that a combination of CNG and Dominion best serves  
our shareholders because it makes strategic sense and has a 
straightforward road map to completion,'' said George A. Davidson 
Jr., chairman and CEO of CNG. ``Together we will have the scale, 
scope and skills to be successful in the competitive energy 
marketplace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This reaffirms and sustains our plans to create the nation's  
premier energy company,'' said Thos. E. Capps, chairman, president 
and CEO of Dominion Resources. ``Our amended offer -- an offer that 
was, and is, valued fairly -- protects and promotes the long-term 
interests of shareholders at both companies.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia Energy is a major energy services company with roles in  
natural gas exploration and production, transmission, distribution 
and storage. Its 1998 revenues were nearly $6.6 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Dominion Resources, the parent company of electricity supplier  
Virginia Power, had $6 billion in revenues last year. 
</P>
<P>
	CNG, which had $2.8 billion in revenues last year, supplies  
natural gas to 1.9 million customers in Ohio, Pennsylvania, 
Virginia and West Virginia and owns 7,600 miles of gas pipelines in 
New York, Pennsylvania, Ohio, Virginia, West Virginia and Maryland. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
