<DOCNO> APW19990511.0104 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 10:39:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Horse Renamed After Colo. Shootings </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LEXINGTON, Ky. (AP) -- In a rare move, the owner of a 3-year-old  
filly named Columbine Is Sad was allowed to change the horse's name 
in deference to the shooting victims in Littleton, Colo. 
</P>
<P>
	The horse, owned by John Ed Anthony of Arkansas's Shortleaf  
Stable, will now run under the name Dake. The Jockey Club in 
Lexington, which registers thoroughbred names, accepted the change 
last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Anthony originally named Columbine Is Sad after a song of that  
name. 
</P>
<P>
	Fifteen people died in the shootings at Columbine High School on  
April 20, counting the two gunmen who committed suicide. 
</P>
<P>
	Jockey Club registrar E.A. ``Buddy'' Bishop said Monday he knew  
of only three or four cases in the last decade in which a name had 
been changed once a horse had raced. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's strictly an integrity issue,'' he said. ``If people keep  
changing horse's names after workouts and races, it gets so after a 
while you can't keep up with them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In this case, however, ``It was pretty obvious why it was the  
right thing to do,'' Bishop said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bishop said he got a call from Anthony shortly after the  
Colorado shootings. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was even thinking of retiring the filly,'' Bishop said.  
``He figured every time he ran the filly, it would just bring it up 
again.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Running as Columbine Is Sad, Dake has finished in the money  
seven times in 12 lifetime starts and has won three times, earning 
$87,640. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0105 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:06:04 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Ex-POW Stone Attends Hockey Game </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- A day after a parade was held in his honor in  
Capac, Army Staff Sgt. Christopher Stone attended the Detroit Red 
Wings playoff game against the Colorado Avalanche on Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, wearing his Army uniform, was introduced to the crowd  
with 12:18 left in the first period. The crowd applauded as he 
waved from a luxury box and then held up a Red Wings shirt with the 
No. 1 and the name ``Stone'' on it. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't say I feel like a hero. I just feel like I did my best  
and the homecoming I'm receiving is what everybody should get when 
they come home from something like that,'' Stone said during an 
interview on WKBD-TV during the second period. 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, bruised and battered during 32 days in captivity in  
Yugoslavia, said what kept him strong was: ``Faith in God, hope and 
a belief in my country and all the people I knew were supporting 
me.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stone, who is from Smiths Creek in St. Clair County, was  
captured along with two soldiers under his command, Spc. Steven M. 
Gonzales, 22, and Staff Sgt. Andrew A. Ramirez, 25, along the 
Macedonia-Yugoslavia border on March 31. They were released May 2, 
when Yugoslav authorities handed the soldiers over to the Rev. 
Jesse Jackson, who had negotiated their release. 
</P>
<P>
	When Stone's father flew to Germany last week to see him for the  
first time since his release, he brought with him a Red Wings shirt 
with Brendan Shanahan's No. 14. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0106 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 10:37:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lawn Device Picks Up After Dog </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EDINA, Minn. (AP) -- Mike Miller is building a  
multi-million-dollar business on things other people don't want to 
touch. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller's Hound Dog Products is the company behind the Poop  
Hound, a long-handled scooper with a raking arm that sweeps doggie 
droppings from the lawn into a plastic bag that can be released 
into the trash. 
</P>
<P>
	No bending. No touching.  
</P>
<P>
	Just mention dog poop and Miller's eyes shine as he thinks about  
the business potential. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are 53 million dogs in America and I'll bet you dollars  
to doughnuts every one of those dogs poops,'' Miller said. ``What's 
a bigger nuisance in the back yard than dog poop?'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hound Products makes four other products for the lawn and  
garden. 
</P>
<P>
	Its first, the Weed Hound, was introduced in 1995. About 900,000  
of the long-handled weeders have been sold through U.S. retailers 
such as Coast to Coast, Eagle Hardware &AMP; Garden, Home Depot, 
Target, True Value, Wal-Mart and lawn and garden centers. Hound Dog 
products also are sold in Canada, Japan, France, Belgium, Germany 
and the United Kingdom. 
</P>
<P>
	The company also makes the Bulb Hound, a standup planter with  
movable spades that release soil like a post digger; the Turf 
Hound, a lawn aerating tool that removes 4-inch plugs of soil from 
lawns to break up thatch, and the Edge Hound, used to remove grass 
encroaching on sidewalks and to install vinyl lawn and garden 
edging. 
</P>
<P>
	Each of the tools has a suggested retail price of $25.  
</P>
<P>
	Hound Dog, which has seven employees, expects sales of more than  
$6 million this year and $10 million in 2000. Miller hopes to grow 
revenues to $50 million by 2005 by adding new products each year. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is developing a garden cultivator; a compact Poop  
Hound for taking on walks with the dog; and an ice chopper. 
</P>
<P>
	All Hound Dog products are designed with two customers in mind --  
Emma, a hypothetical 60- to 70-year-old woman with limited grip 
strength, and Bubba, an imagined 300-pound customer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We build it for Emma and make sure that Bubba can't break  
it,'' Miller said. 
</P>
<P>
	The company is based in this Minneapolis suburb, and its  
products are made by robots at a plant in Watertown, about 30 miles 
west of Minneapolis. During peak production months, 23,000 tools 
are produced each week. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller started in business as a sales representative for Procter  
&AMP; Gamble and later worked for Pillsbury and ConAgra. When he turned 
30, he started looking for a business of his own and took out a 
newspaper ad seeking a venture. 
</P>
<P>
	One man who answered wanted a partner in a real estate deal.  
When Miller wasn't interested, the man said he had an invention in 
the garage to show Miller. After being injured in a construction 
accident, he had built the tool to help with his yard work. 
</P>
<P>
	``He called it the 'green machine.' My eyes widened and I said  
we should test it,'' Miller recalled. He took three-dozen of the 
tools to a local garden store, they sold out and the store ordered 
another hundred. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, with his stepfather as a minority shareholder, signed a  
license agreement with the inventor and has worldwide rights to the 
tool, which was refined to become the Weed Hound. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller thinks there is potential to sell 4 million Weed Hounds,  
but he thinks the Poop Hound will be his best-seller. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think we can sell 5 to 6 million Poop Hounds,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The idea behind the Poop Hound came from a bank Miller had as a  
child. 
</P>
<P>
	``A hand would come out and grab the penny. That's what the Poop  
Hound does,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Poop Hound was introduced in January after extensive  
testing. For the skeptics who might wonder if it really works, ``We 
tested it with mashed potatoes,'' Miller said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0107 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:06:04 </DATE_TIME>
