<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Landslide Reminds of Hawaii Dangers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	HAUULA, Hawaii (AP) -- From its volcanic peaks to its  
crystal-blue waters, Hawaii is a place of both beauty and danger. 
</P>
<P>
	Several tourists die each year during their dream vacations.  
They have been battered by pounding winter surf, attacked by 
man-eating tiger sharks, steamed to death in a volcano or buried 
under giant rocks -- which happened to dozens of visitors Sunday at 
Sacred Falls State Park. 
</P>
<P>
	Eight people are confirmed dead from the landslide, another is  
missing and presumed dead and 12 more remain hospitalized. 
Boulders, some the size of compact cars, rained down on visitors 
swimming in a pool beneath a 90-foot waterfall. 
</P>
<P>
	Ten people have died at Sacred Falls from landslides and flash  
floods since 1970, yet it remains one of the island's most popular 
tourist attractions with 56,000 annual visitors. 
</P>
<P>
	``They come here to fulfill their fantasies,'' said Capt. Ken  
Rust of Honolulu's water safety division. ``But they are unaware of 
the hazards.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Or they ignore them.  
</P>
<P>
	For example, Sandy Beach in eastern Honolulu injures more  
swimmers than any beach in the state, despite 30 warning signs 
fixed in the sand and ocean-conditions signs placed there daily by 
lifeguards. Waves there break close to the shoreline, driving body 
surfers into the ocean floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``People think it won't happen to them,'' Rust said.  
</P>
<P>
	Hawaii visitors, military personnel and locals often  
underestimate the dangers of adventure outings to snorkel, surf, 
Jet Ski, kayak, hike and bike the islands. And those dangers can be 
glossed over by tour companies fighting for survival. 
</P>
<P>
	With more than 6 million annual visitors to the islands, tourism  
is Hawaii's No. 1 industry. Tourists spend about $11 billion a year 
in the Aloha State, generating a quarter of its tax revenues and a 
third of its jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	Consequently, tourist deaths in Hawaii are not uncommon. Just  
recently: 
</P>
<P>
	--A 29-year-old Californian was killed by a shark off Maui while  
kayaking with her husband. He accused the kayak rental company of 
not warning them enough about the dangers of ocean paddling. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 31-year-old man from Washington state drowned while swimming  
in waters off Kauai with his fiancee. 
</P>
<P>
	--A 44-year-old Japanese woman was killed when her Jet Ski was  
broadsided by another. The accident prompted state officials to 
consider changes in safety rules. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is not Disneyland,'' said Janet Babb, who offers tours of  
Hawaii Volcanoes National Park on the Big Island. ``It's hard to 
convince people that this is Mother Nature and we can't control 
it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ms. Babb's tours explore the wonders of Kilauea Volcano, which  
has been erupting almost constantly since January 1983. 
</P>
<P>
	Since then, five people have died in the park, including a local  
man who fell into 2,000-degree lava and a Colorado woman who became 
trapped in a steam vent near the volcano's crater. Park ranger 
Mardi Lane said they both had disregarded signs indicating the area 
was closed. 
</P>
<P>
	``The overwhelming majority of people who visit the park take  
our warnings seriously,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Ms. Babb stopped taking people to see the lava flow  
entering the ocean because of the dangers to them -- from molten 
rock, poisonous sulphuric acid or an earthquake -- and potential 
liability to her. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
