</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0111 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 16:32:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> ValuJet Crash Memorial Dedicated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	EVERGLADES NATIONAL PARK, Fla. (AP) -- A memorial with 110  
concrete columns topped by pyramids was dedicated Tuesday to the 
people who died three years ago when a ValuJet plane plunged into a 
swamp. 
</P>
<P>
	About 150 people from as far away as Italy attended the  
ceremony, held near the crash site. Many had images of the 110 
victims pinned to their lapels, printed on T-shirts or held in 
picture frames. 
</P>
<P>
	``You never get over it,'' said Richard Kessler, whose wife,  
Kathleen, died while returning home to Atlanta after attending 
their daughter's graduation at the University of Miami. ``The old 
myth is time heals and you get on with your life. But as we all 
know, you carry this pain the rest of your life.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Volunteers designed and built the monument, which rests on a  
grassy knoll a few yards from a levee. The concrete block columns, 
topped by four-sided pyramids, are set apart equally in rows. 
</P>
<P>
	The columns rest on a triangular platform that points toward the  
crash site. A center aisle divides the rows, widening as the 
structure rises. 
</P>
<P>
	``For me the design is an allegory, the rise of the victim's  
souls and the fall of the fateful plane,'' said Lee Sawyer, a 
teacher whose parents died in the crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Chemical oxygen generators ignited in the cargo hold of ValuJet  
Flight 592, sending flames tearing through the floor of the 
passenger cabin. The plane nose-dived into the swamp at 460 mph 
minutes after it took off from Miami for Atlanta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
