<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Latin American Briefs /  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LIMA, Peru (AP) -- Thieves crawled through a hole they drilled in  
a Peruvian monastery's front door, punched in a second glass door 
and stole 13 religious paintings, authorities said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The thieves cut 13 of 42 Cuzco School religious paintings out of  
their frames with knives Sunday in the Santa Rosa Monastery in 
Arequipa, said Luis Sardon, director of Peru's National Culture 
Institute. Arequipa is 465 miles southeast of Lima. 
</P>
<P>
	The 17th century paintings depicted the prophet Tobiah and the  
Virgin Mary, among other themes. Cuzco School paintings feature 
Catholic themes painted by Indian artists for Spanish conquerors, 
who used them to decorate churches in Latin America. 
</P>
<P>
	It was the sixth church or monastery in Arequipa robbed of its  
art this year. Thieves target Cuzco School paintings, which are 
sold to local collectors or smuggled abroad. Some are worth as much 
as $30,000. 
</P>
<P>
	---	 
</P>
<P>
	BUENOS AIRES, Argentina (AP) -- President Carlos Menem has  
launched a $600 million plan to create or preserve 1.2 million 
jobs, the Labor Ministry said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Double-digit joblessness is a leading concern in Argentina. The  
government last reported in October 1998 that nationwide 
unemployment stood at 12.4 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan calls for reducing payroll taxes to encourage employers  
to create jobs, offering temporary wage compensation for newly 
hired employees and giving small businesses better access to 
credit. 
</P>
<P>
	---	 
</P>
<P>
	MEXICO CITY (AP) -- Mexico's ruling party has promised to crack  
down on excessive or improper spending amid a costly media campaign 
for the presidential nomination, newspapers reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	President Ernesto Zedillo has promised to prevent the use of  
public funds by presidential hopefuls from his Institutional 
Revolutionary Party, party chairman Jose Antonio Gonzalez Fernandez 
was quoted as saying by Mexico City dailies. 
</P>
<P>
	The sharpest criticism has been aimed at Roberto Madrazo,  
governor of the Gulf Coast state of Tabasco, who has boasted of his 
accomplishments in a series of slick, state-financed television 
commercials. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts say those commercials have helped Madrazo join the  
front-runners in polls for the nomination of the ruling party, or 
PRI. 
</P>
<P>
	---	 
</P>
<P>
	SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) -- One woman was killed by  
a shotgun blast Tuesday during protests in the northern Dominican 
Republic to demand more government services. 
</P>
<P>
	Sobeida Garcia was killed during a protest by students demanding  
repairs to their high school in Santiago, 70 miles northwest of 
Santo Domingo. 
</P>
<P>
	Police would not say who fired the shot, and Garcia's age was  
not released. Witnesses said she was not participating in the 
protest. 
</P>
<P>
	Protests also took place Tuesday in the resort town of Puerto  
Plata, where demonstrators called for road repairs and more public 
works projects. The People's Organizations Collective -- a coalition 
of labor leaders, truckers, taxi drivers and farmers -- has called 
for a general strike on May 18-19. 
</P>
</TEXT>
