<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Heat, Knicks Head to New York Tied  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PURCHASE, N.Y. (AP) -- Somewhere in the wide zone between  
delighted and dismayed sat the New York Knicks on Tuesday, their 
minds eased by the memory of Game 1 but their confidence shaken by 
what happened in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	The key in Wednesday night's Game 3 will be which Knicks team  
shows up -- the aggressive, efficient team on display in the series 
opener or the selfish, shooting-impaired bunch from Monday night's 
loss at Miami. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our goal was to win two games, and that's what we went down  
there to do,'' Allan Houston said. ``What's disappointing is that 
we played a lot differently in Game 2, and in the playoffs you 
can't afford to do so. This isn't the regular season.'' 
</P>
<P>
	There was no panic in the air as the Knicks watched film and  
went through an easy practice in preparation for Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Patrick Ewing was his usual post-practice self, blowing past  
reporters without so much as a word. And Jeff Van Gundy had a laugh 
at his own expense, noting that he was using many of the same 
phrases, like ``playing with passion,'' that he had dismissed just 
last week as meaningless. 
</P>
<P>
	``Sometimes I use those same cliches to my advantage,'' Van  
Gundy said 
</P>
<P>
	Neither game has gone down to the finish, the Knicks winning the  
first one by 20 points after withstanding Miami's final run in the 
third quarter, and the Heat winning by 10 Monday night by turning 
back New York's final surge midway through the fourth quarter. 
</P>
<P>
	To a man, the Knicks pointed out that they need to pass the ball  
better and create easier shots to overcome the type of tough 
defense that the Heat played in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``We weren't really passing the ball to each other. We only had  
11 assists for the game, and Tim Hardaway had 11 assists alone,'' 
Marcus Camby said. 
</P>
<P>
	On the defensive end, the Knicks know they need to reinject some  
of the franchise's old toughness. 
</P>
<P>
	``Alonzo (Mourning) had seven layups or dunks, and Mash (Jamal  
Mashburn) came down the lane and had a finger roll with no contact 
at all. In games like this, you have to send them to the line,'' 
Camby said. 
</P>
<P>
	None of the Knicks is shooting either terribly well or terribly  
poorly, but the team has had to adjust to shrinking offensive 
production from Ewing, who is hampered by Achilles tendinitis. 
Latrell Sprewell is the Knicks' leading scorer, averaging 18.5, and 
New York needs more point production from at least one of its 
starters -- be it Houston, Kurt Thomas or Charlie Ward -- to 
duplicate the success of Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Miami found a way to win Game 2 while getting just one basket  
from Hardaway, their main offensive threat after Mourning. Terry 
Porter and Mashburn had 11 points each, while P.J. Brown had 12. 
</P>
<P>
	The main factor was defense, with the Heat not allowing the  
number of uncontested shots -- in fact, they hardly allowed any -- 
that they did in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Defense is our crutch, something we take great pride in,''  
Mourning said. ``We're not a team that can outscore you. That's not 
our strategy. For the most part we rely on our defense. It 
definitely made a difference (in Game 2). We don't want to get into 
a scoring battle with them.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
