<DOCNO> APW19990511.0120 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:08:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japanese Stock Prices Finish Lower / Japanese Stocks  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Tokyo stock prices finished lower Tuesday as  
investors locked in profits following recent rapid advances. The 
U.S. dollar fell against the yen. 
</P>
<P>
	The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average dropped 233.83  
points, or 1.38 percent, closing at 16,743.18. On Monday, the 
average gained 30.49 points, or 0.18 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The dollar bought 120.62 yen at mid-afternoon, down 0.24 yen  
from late Monday in Tokyo but above its late New York level of 
120.50 yen overnight. 
</P>
<P>
	On the stock market, investors took profits after the Nikkei  
index surged to close at 17,300.61 points on Thursday -- its highest 
finish since Oct. 24, 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Nikkei's 17,000 level prompts selling, but the downside is  
seen solid,'' said Hiroichi Nishi, deputy general manager at Nikko 
Securities Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Japanese blue chips were mixed following the sluggish  
performance of their U.S. counterparts overnight on Wall Street and 
the yen's rise against the dollar Monday, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	A strong yen tends to make Japanese exports more expensive and  
thus less competitive abroad, while making imports cheaper in 
Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the  
first section was down 18.04 points, or 1.31 percent, to 1,355.82 
points. The TOPIX closed up 5.44 points, or 0.40 percent, Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In currency dealings, the dollar slipped on news late Monday  
that the Yugoslav army had announced a partial withdrawal of 
military and police forces in Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	But trades remained in a narrow range in the absence of fresh  
incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	``The market today had no energy and was completely lifeless,''  
said Kenichi Hayashi, manager of the international treasury 
department at the Industrial Bank of Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	There was little follow-through dollar selling Tuesday in the  
wake of the latest development in Kosovo, traders said. 
</P>
<P>
	In other currencies, the euro was traded at 130.08 yen, up from  
129.38 yen late Monday in Tokyo. 
</P>
<P>
	The yield on the benchmark No. 212 10-year Japanese government  
bond rose to 1.340 percent from Monday's close of 1.335 percent, 
driving its price down to 104.08 yen from 104.13 yen. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0121 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 07:55:13 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coelho Named Gore Campaign Chairman </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Former Rep. Tony Coelho, a prominent  
Democratic strategist and architect of the party's failed 1994 
midterm election strategy, will be general chairman of Al Gore's 
presidential effort, the campaign announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	He takes over a political operation that stumbled out of the  
gates, but has shown signs of rebounding in recent weeks. Gore is 
the early front-runner for the Democratic nomination. 
</P>
<P>
	``His political and private-sector experience, his tireless  
energy and his devotion to public service will make a strong 
campaign even stronger,'' Gore said in a statement. ``I am thrilled 
he is joining our team.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho responded: ``It is because I believe in Al Gore, the  
strength of his leadership, the power of his ideas and the values 
he brings to public life that I am going to do everything I can to 
help him become our next president.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, said  
Coelho main task will be to give direction to a troika of interests 
inside the Gore team: The campaign staff, Gore's White House staff 
and his outside consultants. Gore aides and Democratic operatives 
have complained that the three interests do not always work well 
together -- and often are at odds. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore leads his only Democratic rival, former New Jersey Sen.  
Bill Bradley, by at least 20 percentage points in most public 
opinion polls. More sure-footed in recent days, Gore's poll numbers 
have improved. But he has been prone to gaffes, and slow to respond 
to the miscues, as Bradley has threatened to close the gap. 
</P>
<P>
	Polls also show Gore trailing early GOP favorite George W. Bush  
in head-to-head match-ups. 
</P>
<P>
	The hiring of a campaign chairman is not a surprise, though the  
Coelho's name had not been mentioned in public before Monday. 
Officials said the move does not undercut Gore's consultants or top 
aides at the campaign and White House. 
</P>
<P>
	One of the advisers compared it to President Clinton's 1992  
campaign, when California lawyer Mickey Kantor was brought in to 
calm turf wars between the campaign staff and Clinton's political 
team in Arkansas. 
</P>
<P>
	Kantor became U.S. trade representative and commerce secretary  
under Clinton. 
</P>
<P>
	Campaign manager Craig Smith will continue to supervise the  
campaign staff and its budget. And the vice president's schedule 
and day-to-day operation will still be controlled by his White 
House chief of staff, Ron Klain. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho, a former House majority whip, quit Congress in 1989 amid  
an investigation into his personal finances. The campaign says 
Coelho, an investment banker, was cleared by the Justice Department 
of what was a technical violation of House reporting rules. 
</P>
<P>
	While in Congress, Coelho was perhaps the most adroit political  
operator among the House Democrats. In the early 1980s, he 
transformed the Democratic Congressional Campaign Committee into a 
modern and powerful organization. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho headed the Democratic election effort in 1994, when  
Republicans won control of both houses of Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0122 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 05:25:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Calvin Klein Loses Perfume Suit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A judge Monday rejected Calvin Klein's claim  
that something doesn't smell right about Ralph Lauren's new women's 
perfume being marketed in a similar-looking bottle. 
</P>
<P>
	U.S. District Judge John E. Sprizzo issued a preliminary ruling  
saying he did not find enough similarities between Lauren's Romance 
and Klein's Eternity to rule in Klein's favor. 
</P>
<P>
	He noted the Eternity bottle is tall and thin with a curved  
T-shaped silver cap while the Romance bottle is short and squat 
with a flat and square silver cap. He also said the walls of 
Lauren's bottle, though slightly curved, are not like Klein's 
bottle, whose walls are straight. 
</P>
<P>
	Besides the dissimilarities though, the judge said the  
``likelihood of consumer confusion is also minimized by the 
differing marketing techniques employed by the parties and the 
prominent inclusion of the ``Romance'' name on the bottle cap and 
box.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Klein brought the case to federal court in Manhattan in June  
when it learned that the Ralph Lauren was bringing the new 
fragrance to market. 
</P>
<P>
	Ira Jay Levy, a lawyer for Ralph Lauren, said the product has  
sold well since it was introduced last summer. 
</P>
<P>
	Calvin Klein said the lawsuit had already brought about  
improvements because Ralph Lauren changed its bottle to include a 
label with the product's name around the collar of the bottle's 
cap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0123 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 08:45:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Microsoft, Konami To Share Games </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	REDMOND, Wash. (AP) -- Microsoft Corp. and Japan's Konami Co.  
have agreed to publish each other's games on other systems, marking 
the first time both companies have strayed outside their core game 
markets. 
</P>
<P>
	Konami, a large video game publisher based in Tokyo, will  
publish Microsoft's games on systems such as Nintendo 64, Sony 
PlayStation and the Sega Dreamcast, Dow Jones News Service reported 
Tuesday. Microsoft, meanwhile, will adapt Konami titles for the 
personal computer. The first titles resulting from the deal will be 
announced this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Traditionally, Microsoft has published its game titles only on  
the PC, though it has licensed individual titles on occasion for 
the Sony PlayStation and Nintendo 64. But the new deal will allow 
Konami to choose any of Microsoft's titles and publish them for 
other platforms, and vice versa. 
</P>
<P>
	Ed Fries, general manager of the Microsoft games business, said  
the deal will help Microsoft develop new sources of revenue for the 
titles already selling on the PC. Microsoft still will aim its 
games first for the PC. But Fries said more game players are 
switching between systems, so the deal makes sense. 
</P>
<P>
	Tim Dunley, vice president of marketing at Konami of America in  
San Mateo, Calif., said more of his company's games such as the 
multimillion seller ``Metal Gear Solid'' are aimed at adult 
audiences, making it more sensible to adapt the titles to the PC, 
which tends to draw older players. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies also noted that the alliance was a strategy to  
deal with growing consolidation in the games business. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0124 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:39:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  New Offer May Seek To Move Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Pittsburgh inched closer Tuesday to joining  
Hartford, Winnipeg, Quebec and other cities that lost NHL teams 
with a new buyer's offer of $85 million to move the Pittsburgh 
Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	NHL attorney Jeffrey Levitan revealed the offer during a hearing  
on the league's request for quick work on the fate of the team, 
which is in U.S. Bankruptcy Court proceedings for the second time 
in 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The buyer is believed to be Paul Allen, the Seattle billionaire  
who also owns the NFL's Seattle Seahawks and NBA's Portland Trail 
Blazers. The Penguins would provide another wintertime tenant for 
the Rose Garden in Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	NHL commissioner Gary Bettman would not confirm Allen's bid  
during a news conference minutes before the Maple Leafs-Penguins 
playoff game Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not finalized or signed a deal with anyone,'' Bettman  
said. ``If there's speculation that's a done deal, I think people 
are getting ahead of themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trail Blazers officials, who act as Allen's public-relations arm  
and fielded calls Tuesday about the rumors, denied that Allen had 
made an offer for the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	``Nobody has bid on the Penguins,'' said Melinda Gable, the  
Blazers' director of corporate and community affairs. But Allen's 
enterprise will continue to evaluate NHL teams for possible 
relocation to Portland, the team said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Bettman said the NHL remains firmly behind Hall of Famer Mario  
Lemieux's reorganization plan, but time is growing tight as 
planning already is underway for the 1999-2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are fully supportive of Mario's plan, but there are a  
variety of conditions that must be satisfied first,'' Bettman said, 
citing a renegotiated arena lease as the first priority. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG, which operates the Civic Arena, is not to blame for the  
Penguins' financial mess, Bettman said, but he cautioned that the 
Lemieux plan will not go through unless SMG renegotiates. The 
Penguins currently pay $5 million-$6 million a year to play in the 
38-year-old Civic Arena, the oldest in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	``This club is not viable in Pittsburgh without a new lease,''  
Bettman said. ``We would like to have the Pens reorganized in 
Pittsburgh, but if it (the Lemieux plan) fails, we have to look at 
alternatives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL also could liquidate the Penguins and disperse its  
players in a draft among the other league teams. But Bettman said 
that will occur only if the alternative owner decides he doesn't 
have enough time to market the Penguins in a new city for next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The new bid represents $35 million more than Lemieux's $50  
million cash bid endorsed by the NHL, so the team's 200 creditors 
stand to earn more from it. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Chuck Greenberg, Lemieux's attorney, said the  
assumption of debt by the Lemieux group will eventually make his 
bid more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not surprised that another party is interested in the  
team. There were a number of bidders who emerged the last time the 
league expanded,'' Greenberg said. ``We are not going to concern 
ourselves with what might happen if our bid is not confirmed. We 
want to put all our energies into making this a viable franchise in 
Pittsburgh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offer mentioned by Levitan is $30 million less than the  
recent reported price for the Tampa Bay Lightning, who finished at 
19-54-9 and unlike the Penguins missed this year's playoffs. But 
the Lightning plays in a nearly new arena, the Ice Palace, that is 
controlled by the team's new ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial trouble and uncertainty about the looming season have  
reduced the Penguins' value, said William Daly, the league's vice 
president for legal affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are not ideal conditions under which to be selling a  
sports franchise,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A court and creditors' review of the NHL's plan to dissolve the  
Penguins has been scheduled for 11 a.m. May 19. 
</P>
<P>
	That is 12 days before the NHL's deadline for resolving Penguins  
ownership and the same day as Game 7, if necessary, in the current 
playoff series with Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly said the league wants to begin scheduling for next season  
and needs to know how many teams it will have and whether they will 
travel to Pittsburgh or another city for games. 
</P>
<P>
	The league is using the prospect of losing the team to push the  
Penguins toward Lemieux and his investors, although the tone of 
court proceedings has become more grave as the deadline nears. 
</P>
<P>
	``The longer it goes, the harder it is for the league,'' Bettman  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Las Vegas and Kansas City are among the other U.S. cities that  
have been trying to get hockey teams. Roger Marino, one of the 
Penguins' three owners along with Howard Baldwin and Morris 
Belzberg, traveled there and elsewhere to pitch the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	At the May 19 hearing, Judge Bernard Markovitz could schedule  
votes by creditors on the NHL's plan and the Lemieux bid, perhaps 
simultaneously. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want our alternative plan put on the same track as the  
Lemieux plan,'' Bettman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest creditors, the Penguins' banks and insurers, and the  
NHL want the votes to happen at the same time. But other creditors 
object, saying that could be confusing. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge faulted the NHL for waiting so long to prepare its  
plan. Levitan said the league held back at first because it did not 
want to upset negotiations with prospective buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, who is owed $26.2 million in deferred salary and is the  
Penguins' biggest unsecured creditor, is courting Broadcast.com 
founder Mark Cuban, a native of suburban Pittsburgh, as a potential 
investor. They met again on Tuesday afternoon, Greenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins' banks, insurers, equipment suppliers, bond  
holders, former players and other creditors are owed $125 million. 
The team lost $10 million last year and did not sell out recent 
home playoff games with New Jersey, though its first two home games 
against Toronto are sellouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's troubles stem from long-term deals that Baldwin,  
strapped for cash after losing $25 million during the 1994-95 
lockout season, signed with Fox Sports and SMG. He received money 
upfront that kept the team in business. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0125 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:39:09 </DATE_TIME>
