<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks Move Higher; Dow Up 46.10 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Prices opened higher on Wall Street today,  
pushed up by retailers' strong earnings reports and buying in 
technology shares. 
</P>
<P>
	At 10 a.m. on Wall Street, the Dow Jones industrial average was  
up 46.10 at 11,053.35. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, the Dow average fell 24.34 to 11,007.25.  
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators were higher. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500  
index was up 9.91 at 1,350.21, and the Nasdaq composite index was 
up 26.15 at 2,552.54. 
</P>
<P>
	Retail shares were led higher by Wal-Mart, up 1 3/4 at 46 15/16,  
after the company released an earnings report that beat Wall 
Street's profit forecast. Home Depot was up 3 1/8 at 59 1/2. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were also higher in continued buying of  
Internet-related shares. AOL was up 9 5/8 at 137 15/16 in leading 
volume on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	Concerns about higher interest rates were still prominent ahead  
of two big refundings by the Treasury today and Wednesday. The 
30-year Treasury bond yield was trading at 5.79 percent, even with 
Monday's close. Despite the interest rate concerns, banking stocks 
were higher with Citigroup up 1 1/16 at 72 3/8. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by near 3 to 2 on the  
NYSE, where volume came to 111.24 million shares, up from Monday's 
pace. 
</P>
<P>
	Overseas, Japan's Nikkei stock average fell 1.38 percent. In  
afternoon trading, Germany's DAX index was up 1.3 percent, 
Britain's FT-SE 100 was up 0.08 percent, and France's CAC-40 was up 
0.4 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
