<DOCNO> APW19990511.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 17:14:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Cisco 3Q Profits Rise 33 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Quarterly profits rose 33 percent at Cisco  
Systems as the frenzied growth of Internet activity fueled a 44 
percent jump in revenues for the networking technology company. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco earned $646 million, or 38 cents per share, in the three  
months ended May 1, the third quarter of the company's fiscal year. 
</P>
<P>
	In the same period last year, Cisco earned $484 million, or 30  
cents per share, excluding a one-time charge of $419 million to 
cover acquisition-related expenses. 
</P>
<P>
	The latest results, released after financial markets closed on  
Tuesday, edged the 37 cents per share that Wall Street was 
expecting, according to a survey of analysts by First Call. 
</P>
<P>
	In advance of the report, Cisco's shares rose $2.62 1/2, or 2.4  
percent, to $111.87 1/2 on the Nasdaq Stock Market. But in late 
trading on other markets, the shares rose as high as $117. 
</P>
<P>
	Revenues for the past three months totaled $3.15 billion, up  
sharply from $2.18 billion in year-ago period, thanks to robust 
growth in most business sectors and regions. 
</P>
<P>
	Equipment orders for cable TV systems and digital subscriber  
line networks -- the broadband connections that can combine 
Internet, telephone and TV service -- both improved more than 40 
percent in the latest quarter compared with to the year-ago period. 
</P>
<P>
	Broadband is shaping up as a heated battlefield in the scramble  
for Internet market share, with AT&AMP;T assembling a national cable 
network and DSL prices falling as rival phone companies hurry to 
roll out that service. Last week, AT&AMP;T agreed to acquire MediaOne, 
the fourth largest cable company, and formed a partnership with No. 
3 Comcast. 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco's quarterly report also announced a stock split in which  
investors will receive two shares for every common share held on 
May 24. The split, the eighth since Cisco went public in 1990, will 
take effect on June 21. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Internet Economy continues to create unprecedented growth  
opportunities for people, companies, and countries on a global 
basis,'' said John Chambers, president and chief executive of 
Cisco. ``The new world of integrated data, voice, and video 
communications is at the center of these opportunities.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Cisco, based in San Jose, Calif., makes equipment for the  
Internet and other computer networks. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0146 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 05:35:02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Kosovo Spending Eats at Surplus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Congress is about to take another bite out of  
the federal surplus, this time to pay for the conflict with 
Yugoslavia. With proposals mounting for other spending ideas, many 
Republicans worry that their image as a tightfisted party is in 
jeopardy. 
</P>
<P>
	As early as this week, congressional leaders hope to send  
President Clinton a bill financing the confrontation over Kosovo, a 
package expected to cost about $10 billion. Virtually all of it is 
sure to come from this year's federal surplus, which the 
Congressional Budget Office estimates will be a record $111 
billion. 
</P>
<P>
	The problem for Republicans is that all of that surplus will  
come from Social Security, which is collecting more money than it 
spends each year to prepare for the baby boomers' coming 
retirement. Republicans have pledged repeatedly to leave that money 
alone, in hopes of establishing themselves as protectors of the 
popular pension program. 
</P>
<P>
	But with Congress considering the Kosovo funds and a long list  
of other proposals -- such as beefing up spending for the Pentagon 
and schools -- the GOP is finding it increasingly tough to abide by 
its Social Security promise, blurring that message. 
</P>
<P>
	``Politically, the Republican Congress is creating a track  
record that can be used against them,'' warned Ron Utt, a senior 
fellow at the conservative Heritage Foundation. 
</P>
<P>
	Some lawmakers want to add $1 billion to the Kosovo package for  
school safety and up to $4.3 billion for farmers. And that bill 
seems likely to be attached to another measure providing help for 
Central America for damage from last autumn's Hurricane Mitch and 
for U.S. farmers, to which senators have added hundreds of millions 
of dollars to aid the oil, hard-rock mining and steel industries. 
</P>
<P>
	By the end of the year, lawmakers and Clinton may dip even  
deeper into surpluses for 1999 and beyond. 
</P>
<P>
	Both parties say they want to spend more to improve education,  
fortify the military and boost troops' pay. Democrats want to add 
prescription coverage to Medicare, and some want to roll back 
Medicare savings imposed two years ago on hospitals and other 
health-care providers. Republicans want a tax cut of about $800 
billion over the next decade, although they say none of it would be 
paid for from Social Security. 
</P>
<P>
	In fact, the Kosovo spending measure is not even the first chunk  
lawmakers have taken from the surplus. 
</P>
<P>
	When Congress and Clinton enacted a big package of ``emergency''  
spending last fall, it was financed through the surplus, and the 
nonpartisan CBO estimates it will trim this year's black ink by $17 
billion. Without it, the latest projection for the 1999 surplus 
would have been $128 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	That spending spree, however, upset many conservative voters,  
which Republicans say helped cause their poor showing in the 
November congressional elections. In reaction, many GOP leaders 
want to sharpen the party's conservative image by holding such 
raids on the surplus to a minimum. 
</P>
<P>
	A group of conservative senators led by Senate Majority Whip Don  
Nickles, R-Okla., have been pushing to keep the Kosovo package 
close to the $6 billion Clinton requested. Their worry is that the 
more money Congress adds to it, the less credibility their promise 
to protect Social Security has. 
</P>
<P>
	That was underlined when conservative Rep. Tom Coburn, R-Okla.,  
proposed paying for the Kosovo measure last week by cutting 
domestic programs across the board. He was defeated, 322-101, but 
not before highlighting his party's sensitivity to eroding Social 
Security's surpluses just weeks after Congress approved a 
GOP-written budget pledging to leave that money alone. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is morally right to support our troops'' but not ``to take  
money from the Social Security system, to take money out of the 
very future that we say is our highest priority,'' Coburn said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Coburn proposal aimed a spotlight on a schism within the  
GOP, as more than half of the House Republicans voted against his 
amendment. 
</P>
<P>
	That split illustrated how little taste many Republicans have  
for the domestic spending cuts Coburn proposed, plus their belief 
that since Clinton also proposed paying for the fighting with the 
surplus, there would be scant political price to pay for doing just 
that. 
</P>
<P>
	``We can blame this one on Clinton without blinking hard,'' said  
Rich Galen, executive director of the Republican political action 
committee GOPAC. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
