<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Necco Wins Bid To Make Clark Bar </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- The country's oldest candy maker and producer  
of Necco Wafers is the new owner of Pittsburgh's signature Clark 
Bar and plans to move production of the candy to Massachusetts. 
</P>
<P>
	New England Confectionery Co., beating out a handful of other  
bidders, agreed in U.S. Bankruptcy Court on Tuesday to pay $4.1 
million for the peanut butter crunch Clark Bar. The production line 
will be moved to Cambridge in the next month or so, leaving more 
than 100 people without jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clark trademark has a good reputation with consumers, Necco  
president Domenic M. Antonellis said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Clark Bar will have its own place,'' Antonellis said.  
``Unfortunately, we're not going to keep it in Pittsburgh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 152-year-old candy maker, the oldest in the United States  
and also maker of Stark candies, also purchased Clark's recipe for 
Slim Fast diet candy bars and some inventory. 
</P>
<P>
	The Clark Bar will keep company with Necco's Sweethearts  
Conversation Hearts and its wafers, which are stamped out by 
century-old machines. Conversation Hearts -- those little pastel 
candies with messages like ``Be Mine'' -- were developed by Necco in 
1902. The company makes about 85 percent of those purchased each 
Valentine's Day, Antonellis said. 
</P>
<P>
	Irish immigrant D.L. Clark founded the Clark Bar in 1886, but in  
recent years the company has fallen on hard times, dwarfed by large 
national brands such as Mars and Hershey. The company has been 
operating under protection from its creditors since March and owes 
$6.6 million. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
