<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Seeks New Markets in U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Saying American businesses must invest in  
markets at home as they do abroad, President Clinton is appealing 
to the nation's chief executives to join the effort to breathe new 
life into cities and rural areas missing out on the current 
economic boom. 
</P>
<P>
	The president was convening a meeting today at the White House  
with 15 business leaders to discuss ways to bolster private 
investment in economically distressed communities. 
</P>
<P>
	Afterward, Clinton was traveling to Atlanta for more discussions  
with CEOs and a tour of the Sweet Auburn Market, located near the 
Martin Luther King Jr. historic district, to see an example of the 
type of economic development he hopes to generate in other areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton was to tout again his New Markets Initiative, a package  
of proposed tax incentives and loan guarantees designed to attract 
venture capital to areas in need of economic stimulus, such as 
Gary, Ind., the Los Angeles barrios and Appalachian hamlets. 
</P>
<P>
	He also was announcing plans to lead a delegation of CEOs and  
members of Congress on a tour of ``untapped markets'' the week of 
July 5. The White House said the trip was to be patterned after 
trade missions that Cabinet secretaries make overseas to identify 
markets where new jobs and development can be created. 
</P>
<P>
	``The president has been concerned, has spent a good bit of time  
over the last three years trying to come to grips with the 
problem,'' White House spokesman Joe Lockhart said Monday. ``Even 
though we have an economy that we haven't seen in a lifetime, if 
ever, in our country, there still are some areas of the country 
that haven't fully participated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The president's New Markets plan was developed by an  
administration task force that consulted with investment advisers, 
members of Congress and pioneers in community development. Clinton 
first unveiled it in January at Jesse Jackson's Wall Street 
Project, a coalition of executives seeking to expand business 
opportunities for minorities and women, and included it as part of 
his fiscal 2000 budget proposal. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Jackson's group played a prominent role in developing  
the proposal, Jackson himself was absent from today's events. 
</P>
<P>
	He was not listed among those meeting with Clinton at the White  
House, and was not invited to accompany the president to Atlanta. 
The head of the Wall Street Project, Sloan Financial Group CEO 
Maceo Sloan, was attending the White House meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton's proposal includes:  
</P>
<P>
	--A $1 billion tax credit designed to spur $6 billion in new  
equity capital for investment in the targeted markets. The 
administration hopes the 25 percent credit will attract investors, 
who in turn could support small technology companies, inner-city 
shopping centers, manufacturers, retail stores and other 
businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	--Creation of new private investment partnerships to be known as  
America's Private Investment Companies patterned after the Overseas 
Private Investment Corp. APIC would make equity investments in 
larger businesses that expand or relocate to inner cities or rural 
areas. 
</P>
<P>
	--Targeting of the federal Small Business Investment Program to  
low- and moderate-income areas. This program provides equity and 
debt financing to small companies that are looking to grow. America 
Online and Staples are two examples of companies that have 
benefited from this program, but the White House says it has been 
of little benefit to inner cities and rural areas. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
