<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:26:34 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Panel Holds Cop Brutality Hearing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Rep. James Clyburn pledges that the  
Congressional Black Caucus' first hearing on police brutality will 
yield more than a report that will sit on a bookshelf and collect 
dust. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are focused on solutions,'' Clyburn, D-S.C., said Monday.  
``Panels like this often focus only on the horror stories, but we 
are talking solutions. We need to stay focused and achieve some 
meaningful results.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The caucus on Monday hosted the first of a planned national  
series of hearings on police brutality designed to measure whether 
the recent spate of high-profile deaths of young blacks at the 
hands of police are an aberration or a troubling new outgrowth of 
tougher policing policies nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	Early in the five-hour hearing, the panel heard from  
representatives of the civil rights community, including National 
Urban League President Hugh Price and Raul Yzaguirre, president of 
the National Council of La Raza. 
</P>
<P>
	``The problem isn't only excessive use of force but dragnet  
techniques'' that include racial profiling of suspects on traffic 
stops and the random stopping and frisking policies employed by New 
York City police, Price said. 
</P>
<P>
	Later, Bill Lann Lee, acting assistant attorney general for  
civil rights, told the caucus members that although his office is 
limited in its ability to bring federal prosecutions in local 
police jurisdictions, it has reached settlements with the cities of 
Pittsburgh and Steubenville, Ohio, which were judged by the Justice 
Department to discriminate in policing. 
</P>
<P>
	Lee said investigations of the Washington, New York City and New  
Orleans police departments are continuing. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have seen several tragedies in the last few months,'' Lee  
said. ``We have to see how we as a nation as a whole respond, not 
by pointing fingers but by moving forward.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Witnesses like Dorothy Elliott provided tearful testimony of how  
their loved ones died at the hands of police. Mrs. Elliott's son, 
Archie Elliott III, 24, was stopped by Prince George's County, Md., 
police in June 1995 for driving erratically. 
</P>
<P>
	Police said Elliott, with his hands cuffed behind him in a  
police car, pointed a gun at them. The official version of events 
was that after refusing police orders to drop the gun, Elliott was 
shot 14 times and died. 
</P>
<P>
	``You can call it a tragedy, but I call it a murder,'' Mrs.  
Elliott sobbed. ``My son didn't resist arrest. My son's life had 
value.'' The shooting was ruled justified by authorities. 
</P>
<P>
	Seated next to her was Saiko Diallo, whose son Amadou, a street  
vendor from Guinea, was killed Feb. 4 outside his apartment in the 
New York City borough of the Bronx when four white police officers 
fired 41 shots, striking him 19 times and making the young 
immigrant a national symbol of police abuse. 
</P>
<P>
	``The police officers have been indicted for (second-degree)  
murder,'' Diallo said in halting tones. ``But they are still 
working full time with a full salary. This is unfair. This is not 
right.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clyburn said additional hearings are planned for New York, Los  
Angeles, Houston, Chicago and Atlanta. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0154 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 21:14:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Wars Tickets Available </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For Javier Sanchez, it was fate as much as  
the Force that led him to the long line of devotees camping outside 
Mann's Chinese Theatre to get tickets to ``Star Wars: Episode I -- 
The Phantom Menace.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A week ago, the 15-year-old Hollywood High School student and  
longtime ``Star Wars'' enthusiast happened to see the cluster of 
diehard fans outside the famous movie house. 
</P>
<P>
	``I decided I wanted to be out here with them,'' said Sanchez,  
whose love of ``Star Wars'' began at age 9 ``when I heard about 
Darth Vader getting his hand chopped off by Luke Skywalker.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Sanchez and others who have been trading shifts outside the  
theater will get their chance to buy tickets today when advance 
sales for ``Phantom Menace'' begin at 3 p.m. EDT. 
</P>
<P>
	Theater operators and independent ticket sellers were gearing up  
for an expected onslaught of thousands of fans seeking tickets at 
theater box offices, over the Internet and by telephone. 
</P>
<P>
	MovieFone, the company that sells tickets over the telephone and  
Internet, boosted its Web capacity to enable 10 times more people 
than usual to use the service. The company also increased its 
telephone capacity by 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this case, everyone's going to start coming after tickets  
at the same point in time,'' said Andrew Jarecki, chief executive 
officer of MovieFone. ``That presents a challenge to us, but it's 
one we think we can handle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loews, Mann Theatres and Edwards Cinemas were among the theater  
operators planning to sell in advance by telephone or at the box 
office at most theaters. They and other operators were updating 
their Web sites and information lines to advise customers where and 
when tickets would be available. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbus, Ga.-based Carmike Cinemas Inc., unlike other big  
chains, elected to stick with its policy of not selling tickets in 
advance and even had to shoo away one fan who set up camp outside a 
theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Carmike was hoping the film would generate strong  
ticket sales to offset lackluster earnings in recent months, said 
Philip Smitley, a spokesman for the company that as of March 31 
operated 2,653 screens at 463 locations in 36 states. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be one of the fastest-grossing movies of all  
time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Phantom Menace'' doesn't actually open until May 19. But  
diehard fans have been camping outside Southern California theaters 
for weeks with friends to ensure they're among the first to see the 
long-awaited prequel to George Lucas' ``Star Wars'' trilogy. 
</P>
<P>
	Regal Cinemas, the world's largest movie chain, reported people  
lined up Tuesday outside theaters in San Antonio, Las Vegas, 
Cleveland, Philadelphia and Portland, Ore. Regal is showing Star 
Wars at 260 of its 411 theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Phil Zacharetti, a vice president of the chain based in  
Knoxville, Tenn,. said he's seen nothing to compare with this. Not 
even ``Titanic'' had this level of expectation. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has not been anything with the built-in fan base,'' he  
said. ``Most films don't have the hype until after they open. But 
this has a 22-year history'' since the ``Star Wars'' original. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is basically part of our culture now.''  
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's sale won't end the vigil for some. Sanchez plans to  
stay in line as part of a promotion by Countingdown.com, a Web site 
dedicated to big movie openings. If he accumulates enough hours, he 
can win good seats inside Mann's. 
</P>
<P>
	Late Tuesday afternoon, the line holding hundreds of fans  
stretched half a block down Hollywood Boulevard and continued up 
Orange Street. 
</P>
<P>
	``'Star Wars' has changed my life,'' said Lance Swartout, 19,  
who had been pulling shifts with friends outside Mann's since April 
9. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever since I was a kid I wanted to have the 'Star Wars' toys  
and make them, so I'm going to school to learn to make them,'' said 
Swartout, a toy design major at Otis College of Art and Design. 
``That's my dream. This makes it more fun. It's worth it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Some theater operators were standing in line, too. Studio  
executives on Tuesday still were negotiating sales with some 
chains, said Tom Sherak, head of 20th Century's domestic film 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue for most, Sherak said, were stipulations that the movie  
remain in theaters for a set period of time, ranging from two weeks 
to 12 weeks, depending on the location and time of opening. 
</P>
<P>
	Sherak expected ``Star Wars'' to open initially on 2,800 to  
3,000 screens nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole difference in this movie is who has control of the  
movie playing at the theater,'' he said. ``The good news is I don't 
know of one exhibitor who doesn't want to play this movie and it's 
always easier when they want to play the movie.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
