<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:25:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Star Wars Tickets Available Wed. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- You can buy the toys, hear the music,  
speculate about the plot, download the trailer, and starting 
Wednesday, you can even buy tickets for ``Star Wars: Episode I -- 
The Phantom Menace,'' a movie premiere still a week away. 
</P>
<P>
	For fans, distributor 20th Century Fox and theater operators,  
the start of advance ticket sales at 3 p.m. EDT Wednesday is an 
event nearly as big as the movie itself. 
</P>
<P>
	``'Star Wars' has changed my life,'' said Lance Swartout, 19,  
who has been pulling shifts outside Mann's Chinese Theatre in 
Hollywood since April 9. 
</P>
<P>
	``Ever since I was a kid I wanted to have the 'Star Wars' toys  
and make them, so I'm going to school to learn to make them,'' said 
Swartout, a toy design major at Otis College of Art and Design. 
``That's my dream. This makes it more fun. It's worth it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ticket sellers were gearing up for the onslaught by adding staff  
and equipment. MovieFone, the company that sells tickets over the 
telephone and Internet, boosted its Web capacity to enable 10 times 
more people than usual to use the service. The company also 
increased its telephone capacity by 30 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``In this case, everyone's going to start coming after tickets  
at the same point in time,'' said Andrew Jarecki, chief executive 
officer of MovieFone. ``That presents a challenge to us, but it's 
one we think we can handle.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Loews, Mann Theatres and Edwards Cinemas were among the theater  
operators planning to sell in advance by telephone or at the box 
office at most theaters. They and other operators were updating 
their Web sites and information lines to advise customers where and 
when tickets would be available. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbus, Ga.-based Carmike Cinemas Inc., unlike other big  
chains, elected to stick with its policy of not selling tickets in 
advance and even had to shoo away one fan who set up camp outside a 
theater. 
</P>
<P>
	Even so, Carmike was hoping the film would generate strong  
ticket sales to offset lackluster earnings in recent months, said 
Philip Smitley, a spokesman for the company that as of March 31 
operated 2,653 screens at 463 locations in 36 states. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's going to be one of the fastest-grossing movies of all  
time,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``Phantom Menace'' doesn't actually open until May 19. But  
die-hard fans like Swartout have been camping outside Southern 
California theaters for weeks with friends to ensure they're among 
the first to see the long-awaited prequel to George Lucas' ``Star 
Wars'' trilogy. 
</P>
<P>
	Regal Cinemas, the world's largest movie chain, reported people  
lined up Tuesday outside theaters in San Antonio, Las Vegas, 
Cleveland, Philadelphia and Portland, Ore. Regal is showing Star 
Wars at 260 of its 411 theaters. 
</P>
<P>
	Phil Zacharetti, a vice president of the chain based in  
Knoxville, Tenn,. said he's seen nothing to compare with this. Not 
even ``Titanic'' had this level of expectation. 
</P>
<P>
	``There has not been anything with the built-in fan base,'' he  
said. ``Most films don't have the hype until after they open. But 
this has a 22-year history'' since the ``Star Wars'' original. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is basically part of our culture now.''  
</P>
<P>
	Wednesday's sale won't end the vigil for some. Swartout said he  
has put in about 300 hours in shifts so far. As part of a promotion 
by Countingdown.com, a Web site dedicated to big movie openings, he 
plans to continue taking shifts with friends in the hope of winning 
good seats. 
</P>
<P>
	Some theater operators were standing in line, too. Studio  
executives on Tuesday still were negotiating sales with some 
chains, said Tom Sherak, head of 20th Century's domestic film 
group. 
</P>
<P>
	At issue for most, Sherak said, were stipulations that the movie  
remain in theaters for a set period of time, ranging from two weeks 
to 12 weeks, depending on the location and time of opening. 
</P>
<P>
	Sherak expected ``Star Wars'' to open initially on 2,800 to  
3,000 screens nationwide. 
</P>
<P>
	``The whole difference in this movie is who has control of the  
movie playing at the theater,'' he said. ``The good news is I don't 
know of one exhibitor who doesn't want to play this movie and it's 
always easier when they want to play the movie.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Jarecki declined to predict how many tickets would sell on  
Wednesday, but said he expected most showings on May 19 to sell out 
within 15 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	Weeks of hype and buildup can only carry a film for a few days.  
</P>
<P>
	Once it opens, Sherak said ``Phantom Menace'' will have to  
convince viewers it is worth the price of a ticket. 
</P>
<P>
	Early reviews of the movie have been mixed. Critics generally  
have praised the film for its visually stunning creation of a new 
universe of characters and creatures. Some have been less 
enthusiastic about the dialogue and story line, however. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have all the confidence in the world in the movie. The  
bottom line in any movie is the movie. It's what the public does,'' 
Sherak said. ``They're going to tell us how good that movie is and 
whether they're going to like it or not.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
