<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Airlines Gets Help </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MANILA, Philippines (AP) -- Germany's Lufthansa Airlines and a  
Middle Eastern aviation company have agreed to help rehabilitate 
ailing Philippine Airlines, President Joseph Estrada said today. 
</P>
<P>
	The airline's majority stockholder Lucio Tan has been  
negotiating with Lufthansa officials in Germany principally to help 
manage the Philippine flag carrier. 
</P>
<P>
	Philippine officials said an aviation company in the Middle East  
and an investment group in Singapore have also expressed interest 
in providing some of the $200 million in new capital that PAL 
needs. 
</P>
<P>
	Estrada said he was informed by Tan, who is to return from  
Germany later this week, that Lufthansa and the Middle Eastern 
company have agreed in principle to help PAL recover. Estrada did 
not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	In Frankfurt, Germany, Lufthansa said late today it won't take  
an equity stake in PAL, but will offer consulting services. 
</P>
<P>
	The $200 million capital infusion is a key element of a PAL  
rehabilitation plan that also calls for reducing the airline's 
fleet of 54 aircraft to 22 and its 8,000-member workforce to about 
3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL's debt was largely incurred by an ambitious but ill-timed  
fleet modernization program. The carrier became unable to service 
its loans as a result of Asia's economic crisis and a debilitating 
pilots' strike. 
</P>
<P>
	Manila's corporate regulator, the Securities and Exchange  
Commission, set a June 4 deadline for the capital infusion. 
</P>
<P>
	PAL's recovery plan has been conditionally accepted by European  
credit agencies owed around 40 percent of the carrier's $2.2 
billion debt. It has also gotten support from a consortium of 11 
Philippine banks, owed around 10 percent of the total debt, and a 
number of smaller local and foreign creditors. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan is likely to be approved later this month despite the  
objections of the U.S. Export-Import Bank, PAL's second-biggest 
creditor with 16 percent of its debt, SEC Chairman Perfecto Yasay 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The U.S. Ex-Im bank withdrew its support for the plan last week  
after Tan reassumed direct management control. 
</P>
<P>
	Tan stepped aside only a few months earlier under pressure from  
creditors who wanted PAL run by professional managers. 
</P>
<P>
	Although Philippine law doesn't require the SEC to get the  
consent of creditors for the rehabilitation plan, Yasay said this 
was necessary to ensure its success. 
</P>
<P>
	The backing of the U.S. Ex-Im Bank is also important because it  
recently began moves to seize all four of PAL's Boeing 747-400 
jets, which are used for its long-distance flights to the United 
States. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
