<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Hasek Is Key to Sabres Hopes / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BUFFALO, N.Y. (AP) -- The Buffalo Sabres and Boston Bruins are  
talking about hitting in their best-of-7 Eastern Conference 
semifinal series. 
</P>
<P>
	But it's really about goaltending.  
</P>
<P>
	Boston's Byron Dafoe is tough. Buffalo's Dominik Hasek, the  
NHL's two-time defending MVP, is still the man to beat. 
</P>
<P>
	The quarreling rivals switch to Buffalo for Games 3 and 4  
Wednesday and Friday. No matter how much his Buffalo teammates and 
their Boston foes might quarrel on and off the ice, Hasek stays 
focused on one thing -- stopping the puck. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't want to get into a fight, but I want the referee to  
see that I'm really upset if somebody takes a cheap shot at me, 
especially after the whistle,'' Hasek said. ``I just make a couple 
steps and let my teammates do their job.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Sabres took good care of Hasek for most of Game 2, pestering  
the Boston forwards in much the same way Buffalo captain Michael 
Peca and forward Vaclav Varada had rendered Ottawa superstar Alexei 
Yashin scoreless in the first round. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think Boston hasn't played their best game yet,'' Hasek  
said. ``They'll be sharp in the next game. If we want to win, we'll 
have to be sharp, too.'' 
</P>
<P>
	This year Hasek overcame a nagging groin injury, a sagging  
Buffalo offense and a trade rumor that flew into town just in time 
for the second round of the playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The 34-year-old goaltender had a career-best 1.87 goals-against  
average. He led the NHL for the sixth straight year in save 
percentage at .937 and is one playoff shutout away from a team 
record. 
</P>
<P>
	In the playoffs' first round, Hasek shut Ottawa down. He  
preserved a 2-0 lead late in the second period of Game 2 against 
Boston by turning back a flurry of shots during a Bruins' 5-on-3 
advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Players on both teams talk about a big hit Sabres defenseman  
Alexei Zhitnik made on Bruins captain Ray Bourque in Buffalo's 3-1 
victory in Game 2. That led to more talk about possible 
repercussions against Hasek, Buffalo's equivalent of Bourque. 
</P>
<P>
	``There isn't a whole lot you can do about someone running over  
Dom,'' Sabres defenseman Jason Woolley said. ``If they're trying to 
pick a superstar to go after, he's the only one. We know where 
they're going if that's their game plan, but I don't think we're 
worried about that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hasek worries a lot more about the puck than the talk. ``I don't  
think about becoming a target of Boston players,'' he said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	The world's best goaltender also knows that while he's watching  
out for shots, someone is watching his back. 
</P>
<P>
	``My defense does a good job in front of me and they will take  
care of the players who take runs at me,'' Hasek said. 
</P>
<P>
	Boston will try to distract Hasek and aim high. In Game 1, Hasek  
allowed three goals on 21 shots after a lengthy layoff following 
Buffalo's sweep of favored Ottawa. 
</P>
<P>
	``Of course we have to be ready for traffic in front,'' said  
Hasek, whose unorthodox style has him flopping around, throwing 
down his stick and frequently skating out of the crease. 
</P>
<P>
	``I expect there will be a couple of times when I won't see the  
puck, but it doesn't mean I can't stop the puck,'' Hasek said. 
``They talk about creating traffic in front of me and shooting 
high; it doesn't change my style.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
