<DOCNO> APW19990511.0161 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:25:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Stocks End Higher; Dow Up 18.90 / Wall Street Report  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- A disappointing Treasury auction undercut a  
powerful rally in blue-chip stocks Tuesday, leaving them only 
modestly higher. But the broader market advanced unscathed on the 
strength of Internet stocks. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow Jones industrial average ended 18.90 higher at  
11,026.15, just shy of its record high close of 11,031.59 last 
Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	Broader stock indicators, however, maintained their strength.  
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index rose 15.31 to 1,355.61, and the 
Nasdaq composite index rose 40.29 to 2,566.68. 
</P>
<P>
	The Dow was up 94 points in early afternoon when the Treasury  
announced it had sold $15 billion of five-year notes at 5.367 
percent, an 11-month high, in the first leg of a two-day auction. 
</P>
<P>
	The news sent the 30-year Treasury bond, which was already down  
for the day, even lower. The bond's yield, which moves opposite the 
price, rose to 5.83 percent from 5.79 percent late Monday, making 
bond yields more competitive with stocks and sending equities 
prices tumbling. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is always the clear and present danger of the stock  
market,'' said Larry Wachtel, market analyst at Prudential 
Securities. ``Once bonds become an alternative form of investment, 
you set up a transfer from stocks to bonds.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Big-company stocks, which are expensive relative to their  
projected earnings, are especially sensitive to inflation and 
higher rates. Either could cut into future earnings and send the 
stocks lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Smaller stocks, on the other hand, are cheap relative to future  
earnings. They can sustain a decline in the earnings projections 
without losing their price advantage. 
</P>
<P>
	Blue chips are particularly vulnerable now because they have  
risen so far so fast, Wachtel said. ``We're up 1,200 (Dow) points 
in five weeks. If you breathe heavily, this whole thing topples 
over.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Stocks could get hit again Wednesday when the Treasury auctions  
another $12 billion of securities, this time of 10-year notes, and 
again on Thursday and Friday, when the government releases 
wholesale and consumer price data. 
</P>
<P>
	Joseph Battipaglia, market strategist at Gruntal &AMP; Co., said he  
thought bond traders, not stock traders, were overdoing the 
selling. ``The data says that there's no inflation and the economy 
remains strong,'' Battipaglia said. ``Therefore, the bond market is 
wrong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Retail stocks were led higher by Wal-Mart, up 2 1/8 at 47 5/16,  
after the company released an earnings report that beat Wall Street 
forecasts. Home Depot was up up 2 7/8 at 59 1/4. Prudential Securities 
upgraded the stock after the company announced expansion plans. 
</P>
<P>
	Technology stocks were also higher in continued buying of  
Internet-related issues. 
</P>
<P>
	America Online was up 13 1/8 at 141 7/16 and was the most active  
stock on the New York Stock Exchange after the company struck 
alliances with four television companies. 
</P>
<P>
	Morgan Stanley analyst Mary Meeker upgraded AOL stock, saying  
the company should be able to stake out a leadership in the new 
multi-channel, high-speed communications arena while still find 
plenty of support for its traditional dial-up Internet service over 
the next several years. 
</P>
<P>
	Internet stocks were also boosted by a very strong inaugural for  
The Street.com, an Internet news service whose stock soared to 60 
1/16 from an original price of 19 in its first day of trading in 
the Nasdaq stock market. 
</P>
<P>
	The stock and bond markets for the most part ignored a  
government report that the nation's productivity, a key gauge of 
future prosperity, shot up at an annual rate of 4 percent in the 
first three months of this year. 
</P>
<P>
	Advancing issues outnumbered decliners by a 4-to-3 margin on the  
New York Stock Exchange. Consolidated volume totaled 1.02 billion 
shares, up from Monday's pace. 
</P>
<P>
	The NYSE composite index rose 6.43 to 645.77, and the American  
Stock Exchange composite index rose 2.21 to 789.29. The Russell 
2000 index of smaller companies rose 4.96 to 446.81. 
</P>
<P>
	In foreign stock markets, the Nikkei average in Tokyo declined  
1.38 percent. In Europe, the DAX in Frankfurt rose 0.83 percent, 
the CAC in Paris gained 0.07 percent, and the FT-SE 100 index in 
London rose 0.46 percent. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0162 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:33:33 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Netanyahu Campaign Targets Arafat </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	JERUSALEM (AP) -- Slipping in the polls as a divisive electoral  
campaign enters its final days, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin 
Netanyahu has been taking his toughest shots at a man who isn't in 
the race: Yasser Arafat. 
</P>
<P>
	By casting the Palestinian leader as chief villain in the  
campaign drama, Netanyahu hopes to tar left-leaning opponent Ehud 
Barak by association, and build up support among his own hard-line 
constituency in advance of Monday's national elections. 
</P>
<P>
	From early political ads that personally targeted Arafat to a  
bid this week to shut down the PLO's Jerusalem headquarters, the 
prime minister has kept the Palestinian leader squarely in his 
sights throughout the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's running against Arafat -- he's using Arafat 24 hours a  
day,'' said Palestinian analyst Mahdi Abdel-Hadi, who heads a 
Jerusalem think tank. 
</P>
<P>
	Even those in the prime minister's camp acknowledge he has  
little to lose by letting friction with the Palestinians come into 
play. 
</P>
<P>
	``It can be said that the fact that Arafat is against Netanyahu  
can work for Netanyahu, because not everybody here is enamored'' of 
the Palestinian leader, said top Netanyahu aide David Bar-Illan. 
</P>
<P>
	Like much else about Israeli politics, the anti-Arafat strategy  
is far from subtle. 
</P>
<P>
	Netanyahu's first round of campaign ads portrayed a shadowy,  
sinister figure in the Palestinian leader's trademark kaffiyeh 
headdress counting down the days to a Barak victory. Another ad 
showed a fiery Arafat declaring that anyone who doesn't like the 
idea of a Palestinian state can go and ``drink from the sea off 
Gaza.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Last week, the prime minister hammered away at the theme that  
only his unyielding stance toward the Palestinians had prevented 
Arafat from declaring Palestinian statehood May 4, upon the 
expiration of interim peace accords. Palestinian leaders said the 
key consideration in the delay was a wish to avoid playing into 
Netanyahu's hands. 
</P>
<P>
	The Palestinians' prominence as a campaign theme has been  
something of a paradox. The five-month race has been virtually 
devoid of thoughtful discourse among the candidates about what 
would seem to be the overriding question facing Israel: terms of 
eventual Palestinian statehood. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead, Netanyahu has seized on issues with maximum visceral  
appeal. This week, he moved to close several Palestinian offices in 
the east Jerusalem compound known as Orient House. For the past 
eight years, Orient House has served as the Palestinians' de facto 
headquarters in the contested city. 
</P>
<P>
	Israel's Supreme Court on Tuesday stayed the closure order until  
after next week's vote, but the prime minister had already made his 
point: trumpeting Israel's claim to sovereignty over all Jerusalem, 
including the traditionally Arab eastern sector where Palestinians 
want to establish the capital of their future state. 
</P>
<P>
	So widespread is the perception that Netanyahu is deliberately  
courting confrontation with the Palestinians -- on the theory that 
heightened Israeli security fears would translate into votes for 
him -- that it was featured in a biting skit this week by the 
popular Israeli satirical puppet show Hartsufim. The show depicted 
the prime minister all but begging Arafat to give the green light 
to a suicide attack by Islamic militants. 
</P>
<P>
	That's only satire, but Netanyahu's own ads have harkened back  
to a series of grisly bus bombings in Israeli cities weeks before 
the 1996 vote in order to suggest that a dovish government means a 
vulnerable Israel. While the ads have been ridiculed in some 
circles as heavy-handed, the 1996 attacks were generally viewed as 
having propelled Netanyahu to his razor-thin victory in that race. 
</P>
<P>
	So far, Arafat has managed to stay out of the fray, steadfastly  
describing the elections as an internal Israeli affair. And he has 
been able to keep a lid on building street pressure in the West 
Bank and Gaza Strip. 
</P>
<P>
	Palestinians are furious over a burst of Jewish settlement  
activity in recent weeks. Almost daily, settlers move new trailers 
onto rocky West Bank hilltops, seeking to expand existing 
settlements. 
</P>
<P>
	Settler leaders frankly acknowledge they are making a  
pre-election drive to establish ``facts on the ground'' -- populate 
more territory in order to make it harder for the Israeli 
government to cede it to the Palestinians later. 
</P>
<P>
	Such expansions, which Palestinians condemn as land grabs, would  
normally set off angry protests and clashes with Israeli troops. 
Instead, the West Bank and Gaza have been remarkably quiet in 
recent weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	Arafat does have one strong direct link to the Israeli vote: he  
exercises considerable influence over Israel's 1 million Arab 
citizens. 
</P>
<P>
	While he meticulously avoids any public electioneering among the  
Israeli Arabs, the Palestinian leadership has reportedly been 
deeply involved in back-channel discussions over whether the first 
Arab candidate for Israeli prime minister, Azmi Bishara, should 
drop out to improve Barak's chances for a first-round victory over 
Netanyahu. 
</P>
<P>
	Both Arafat and Bishara, who says he will make a decision on  
leaving the race by Saturday, deny such contacts. 
</P>
<P>
	Ordinary Palestinians, who follow the Israeli campaign with  
close attention -- and considerable sophistication -- say the most 
important thing they can do in coming days is to avoid responding 
to any Israeli provocations with violence. 
</P>
<P>
	In the dusty West Bank town of Bethlehem, storekeeper Omar Boja,  
seated among crates of fresh-laid eggs and boxes of yellow onions, 
said it was also crucial that Palestinians refrain from any 
appearance of wanting to influence the outcome. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to see the man who wants peace elected,'' Boja said,  
avoiding even mentioning Barak's name. ``But it's their election, 
their choice.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0163 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:33:33 </DATE_TIME>
