<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 15:24:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Coelho Brings Stature to Gore Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Tony Coelho will add stature, discipline and  
political firepower to Al Gore's slow-starting presidential effort, 
said Democratic officials, who dismissed questions about the new 
campaign chairman's fund-raising tactics and personal finances in 
the 1980s. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho, appointed to the post Tuesday, is an adroit political  
operator who served 10 years in Congress before leaving under a 
cloud of controversy in 1989. 
</P>
<P>
	He will oversee Gore's campaign staff, his White House political  
shop and various outside consultants. The three factions did not 
always work well together, slowing down the decisionmaking process 
and exposing the team to internal strife. 
</P>
<P>
	``His political and private sector experience, his tireless  
energy and his devotion to public service will make a strong 
campaign even stronger,'' Gore said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	Party officials said signs of weakness had begun to show in the  
Democratic front-runner's campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	``With three factions, you'll get petty jealousies and  
confusion. You've got to have a strong figure in the middle. He's a 
good choice,'' said Democratic consultant Ray Strother. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore leads his only Democratic rival, former Sen. Bill Bradley  
of New Jersey, by at least 20 percentage points in most public 
opinion polls. Bradley added three senior advisers to his campaign 
Tuesday: pollster Diane Feldman, consultant Jacques DeGraff and 
field director Robert Richman. 
</P>
<P>
	Gore has been prone to gaffes, and slow to respond to the  
miscues, as Bradley threatens to close the gap. Though more 
sure-footed in recent days, the vice president still trails GOP 
front-runner George W. Bush in head-to-head surveys. 
</P>
<P>
	Implied in the praise for Coelho's appointment were suggestions  
that Gore's team had lacked discipline and leadership. 
</P>
<P>
	House Minority Leader Dick Gephardt said it's important for the  
campaign to ``have focus and direction. I think Tony is very well 
equipped to do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Rahm Emanuel, a former Clinton aide and longtime Coelho booster,  
said the Californian brings ``stature and savvy'' to the campaign. 
</P>
<P>
	Mickey Kantor, a former Clinton Cabinet member who served as  
Clinton-Gore campaign chairman in 1992, called Coelho's appointment 
``a very positive step. Tony is extremely disciplined and 
focused.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Unlike Coelho, Kantor joined the 1992 Clinton campaign at its  
beginning. And unlike Kantor, Coelho insists he will not join the 
administration if his candidate wins the presidency. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm just doing this out of loyalty for Al,'' the 56-year-old  
investment banker said in a telephone interview. 
</P>
<P>
	He brings some political baggage to the job.  
</P>
<P>
	--Coelho quit Congress amid an investigation into his personal  
finances. The Justice Department later closed the case without 
taking criminal action. No indictment means no wrongdoing, 
supporters say. ``Nothing was shown to be wrong,'' Gephardt said. 
</P>
<P>
	--In the early 1980s, he transformed the Democratic House  
campaign committee into a modern and powerful organization. He 
expanded the contributions of business political action committees 
and was the first committee chairman to accept ``soft money'' -- 
unregulated donations from unions, corporations and individuals 
that do not fall under federal limits. 
</P>
<P>
	Critics say Coelho's record will be a constant reminder of  
Gore's aggressive fund-raising practices in 1996, which came under 
scrutiny and are a potential campaign issue in 2000. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would seem that naming somebody your campaign chairman who  
has been the subject of those same kinds of questions and 
criticisms would emphasize a weakness rather than erase it,'' said 
Paul Hendrie of the Center for Responsive Politics in Washington. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho and his backers said he was simply keeping up with GOP  
tactics. ``We just took a page out of their political playbook,'' 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	--Coelho headed the Democratic election effort in 1994, when  
Republicans won control of both houses of Congress. Supporters say 
he can't be blamed. 
</P>
<P>
	``You could have been the world's greatest magician and that  
would not have changed the essential facts of 1994,'' Kantor said. 
</P>
<P>
	Coelho said he plans no changes in the campaign staff headed by  
Craig Smith, a longtime Clinton aide. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think some folks ... are talking about campaign problems. I  
don't agree with that,'' he said. ``I think this campaign is right 
where it should be.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He said Smith headed the first phase of the campaign, building a  
national organization and hiring campaign staff. Hiring a general 
chairman is the traditional second step of a presidential campaign, 
he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a good team,'' said Coelho, who won't get paid. ``They  
just need a general coordinator.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Married for 32 years and the father of two adult daughters,  
Coelho has become a staunch advocate for disabled Americans. He has 
epilepsy. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 10:15:03 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Wynton Marsalis Plays Ellington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- ``Duke Ellington loved life. And he wanted you  
to love it, too. He was going to help you love it. That's the main 
thing about his music, I guess.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Wynton Marsalis, artistic director of Jazz at Lincoln Center, is  
at home, talking about ``Swingin' with Duke,'' a 90-minute show 
airing Wednesday at 9 p.m. EDT as part of the ``Great 
Performances'' series on PBS. 
</P>
<P>
	Ellington -- pianist, band leader and America's most prolific  
composer, with some 2,000 titles -- died in 1974 at 75. April 29 was 
the 100th anniversary of his birth. He is being celebrated with 
performances all year by the Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra, which 
is led by 37-year-old Marsalis. 
</P>
<P>
	On the TV show, the Lincoln Center musicians play 16 pieces,  
including ``Sophisticated Lady,'' ``Mood Indigo,'' ``Black and Tan 
Fantasy'' and ``Portrait of Louis Armstrong'' from ``New Orleans 
Suite,'' with trumpeter Marsalis soloing. 
</P>
<P>
	Film clips show Ellington being interviewed, working and playing  
the charming showman on-stage. Ella Fitzgerald is seen singing with 
the Ellington Band. Guests of the Lincoln Center orchestra include 
singer Dianne Reeves, saxophonist Illinois Jacquet and more than a 
dozen dancers capable of doing the lindy-hop, one of the popular 
dances of Ellington's heyday. 
</P>
<P>
	The Lincoln Center Jazz Orchestra uses Ellington arrangements.  
``Unless we had somebody who could arrange better than him, we 
wouldn't change them,'' Marsalis says. 
</P>
<P>
	``Some people say, `To play the music of Duke Ellington is to  
step back in time.' That's not right. You go forward in Duke 
Ellington's music; you don't go back to it,'' Marsalis says. ``Duke 
used to say music is neither new nor old. It sounds contemporary 
today.'' 
</P>
<P>
	During the show Marsalis says, ``We're trying to be in the  
spirit of Duke. We're not trying to recreate what he did. You can't 
do that. We try to bring ourselves to it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not trying to keep this music alive. It is alive,'' he  
says. 
</P>
<P>
	On the show Marsalis is seen instructing high school jazz band  
directors about performing Ellington. 
</P>
<P>
	``They're easy to work with,'' Marsalis says during the  
interview in his apartment near Lincoln Center. ``When I traveled 
around the country doing workshops at high schools these last 15 or 
16 years, I didn't want to step on the band leader's authority. 
They always said, `Man, tell them. Don't worry about me. Help my 
kids.''' 
</P>
<P>
	This year's fourth annual ``Jazz at Lincoln Center Ellington  
High School Band Competition and Festival'' sent the sheet music 
for six Ellington tunes to 1,307 bands in 50 states. Of those, 169 
bands sent in tapes of them playing that music. Twenty bands were 
brought to New York for three days and competed on May 1. Bands 
from New York City, West Hartford, Conn., and Houston took the top 
three places. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsalis says he and the Lincoln Center ensemble try to play  
better than the Ellington Band. ``Chances of that are very slim,'' 
he says. ``But that's what we try to do. We don't walk around 
viewing the old recordings like the Holy Grail. Music has a 
functional purpose -- that is, to be played. I'm sure that's how 
Duke felt about music. I think he would have liked what we're 
playing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Marsalis feels he knows Ellington through his compositions. On  
the show, he says Ellington put the discrimination he felt against 
black people into his music. ``It represents affirmation in the 
face of adversity; let's look up, let's not look down.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He also calls Ellington a champion flirter and charmer of women.  
``It's part of the sweetness of life. He was the master,'' Marsalis 
says. 
</P>
<P>
	Marsalis himself is releasing 14 CDs this year. ``It was my idea  
to do so many,'' he says. The purpose: ``Just to get the creativity 
out.'' 
</P>
<P>
                             	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Elsewhere in television ...  
</P>
<P>
	AWARENESS OF RAINN: ``Beverly Hills, 90210'' star Jennie Garth  
will feature in a public-service announcement supporting RAINN 
(Rape, Abuse &AMP; Incest National Network) to air immediately 
following Wednesday's ``Agony'' episode of ``90210,'' which reveals 
that Kelly Taylor (Garth) has been raped. Kelly bravely tries to 
carry on after the assault. She calls the RAINN hot line at the 
suggestion of a nurse at the hospital where she is being treated. 
``90210'' airs at 8 p.m. EDT on Fox. 
</P>
</TEXT>
