<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Yzerman Wary of Colorado Road Record </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DETROIT (AP) -- Steve Yzerman leads by example, which might be  
why the Detroit Red Wings have yet to lose in the NHL playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's captain is leading the league with eight postseason  
goals, tying a personal best, while the Red Wings have yet to lose 
in six games. 
</P>
<P>
	They take a 2-0 series lead into tonight's game with Colorado.  
Game 4 of the best-of-7 series with the Avalanche is set for 
Thursday night at Joe Louis Arena. Still, Yzerman sounded a note of 
caution. 
</P>
<P>
	``Remember, the Avalanche have a great road record, better than  
at home,'' Yzerman said. ``They have an experienced team. We by no 
means can relax and feel good about everything. 
</P>
<P>
	``They could get back into this one if we aren't careful.''  
</P>
<P>
	Colorado is 1-4 at home, but 3-0 on the road in the playoffs.  
</P>
<P>
	``Look at our road record,'' Avalanche coach Bob Hartley said.  
``I have lots of faith in my players.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He'd feel better, however, if the Avalanche would play just a  
little bit smarter. Hartley asked the players not to take bad 
penalties. 
</P>
<P>
	Yet, in Game 1, the Red Wings -- seeking their third straight  
Stanley Cup championship -- were handed seven power plays and scored 
on two of them. Detroit won that game 3-2 in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	In the second game, Colorado put the Red Wings on the power play  
seven more times and, again, they converted two into scores on 
their way to a 4-0 victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``Loss of discipline comes from frustration,'' Hartley said,  
``and that's one thing we have to learn to control.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Discipline also can come from leadership and the Red Wings, as  
they did in the 1998 playoffs, are getting plenty of that from 
Yzerman. 
</P>
<P>
	``Steve usually gets scoring chances,'' Detroit coach Scotty  
Bowman said. ``I don't worry about his scoring. When he steps up 
and scores, everybody feels that's what he can do and it just sort 
of feeds the other guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Avalanche, on the other hand, haven't had much production  
from their two main leaders -- captain Joe Sakic and center Peter 
Forsberg. They have just one point between them in the series, an 
assist by Forsberg in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Forsberg has been having a bad series in other ways. He put his  
team in a deep hole by drawing a boarding penalty and a game 
misconduct midway through Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	Did he learn his lesson?  
</P>
<P>
	Apparently not. Forsberg was called for boarding Chris Chelios  
in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've got so much skill there shouldn't be six guys in this  
whole league that could stop us,'' Avalanche defenseman Aaron 
Miller said. ``But we've got to play as a team. Twenty great 
players running around isn't going to win anything.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The victory in Game 2 was the 200th playoff win for Detroit  
coach Scotty Bowman, extending his NHL record. He's already 77 
ahead of runnerup Al Arbour. 
</P>
<P>
	The Red Wings have won 11 straight playoff games, including five  
last season. The NHL record is 14 by the Pittsburgh Penguins in 
1992-93. None other than Bowman was coaching the Penguins in those 
days. 
</P>
<P>
	``I didn't really think about it,'' Bowman said. ``Somebody told  
me before the playoffs, but that's the only time I thought about 
it. I worry more about the 111 losses.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
