<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Shipbuilding Takeover Talks OK'd </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW ORLEANS (AP) -- Avondale Industries' board agreed Tuesday to  
open discussions with Litton Industries Inc. about its takeover 
bid, saying it might be superior to Avondale's previous agreement 
to merge with Newport News Shipbuilding Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	The Woodland Hills, Calif.-based Litton has offered to buy both  
Avondale and Newport News for a total of $1.76 billion. The offer 
for Avondale was for $38 a share, or $504 million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Avondale and Newport News had previously agreed to merge in a  
$470 million deal and has already received approval from the 
Pentagon. 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News's board hasn't taken a public position on the  
Litton offer and could not be immediately reached for comment 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	But in a statement issued the day the buyout proposal was  
disclosed, chairman and CEO William P. Fricks said the board would 
conduct ``preliminary discussions'' with Litton ``to fully evaluate 
the terms of the offer.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Newport News, Va.-based Newport News Shipbuilding builds all the  
Navy's aircraft carriers and many of its submarines, and it repairs 
and performs maintenance on various types of Navy ships. 
</P>
<P>
	New Orleans-based Avondale designs, builds and overhauls Navy  
surface ships as well as commercial vessels. 
</P>
<P>
	The Litton offer came three weeks after the Pentagon rejected a  
merger between defense giants General Dynamics Corp. and Newport 
News Shipbuilding on grounds the proposed $2 billion deal would 
have created a single shipbuilder for all nuclear submarines and 
would have reduced competition in other sectors of military 
shipbuilding. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
