<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Counselors in Demand After Storms </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	OKLAHOMA CITY (AP) -- Tornadoes that ripped across central  
Oklahoma left more than a mere physical reminder of the federal 
building bombing that killed 168 people and stunned this city. 
</P>
<P>
	Counselors say survivors, rescue workers and others involved in  
the 1995 explosion are now grappling with the same kind of 
emotional repercussions as a result of the twisters. 
</P>
<P>
	``The majority of folks we're seeing are those who have been  
doubly impacted,'' Project Heartland director Gwen Allen said 
Monday. Her program's four counselors ``have been run off our 
feet'' by demands for assistance. 
</P>
<P>
	Project Heartland, created with a federal grant to help the  
community deal with the trauma of the bombing, is trying to 
determine how many more counselors are needed to provide emotional 
aid to tornado victims, Ms. Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	Counselors predict that storm victims, like those who survived  
the bombing, may suffer feelings of fear, anxiety, depression and 
agitation. The additional loss of homes could create other worries, 
Allen said. 
</P>
<P>
	The May 3 tornado tore a path through the Oklahoma City suburbs  
and surrounding towns, leaving 41 dead. One 23-year-old woman blown 
from underneath a highway overpass remained missing Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	In Moore, children who were left without homes -- or books or  
pencils -- returned to the waiting arms of their teachers Monday in 
borrowed classrooms. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't have a building. But we've got each other,'' Kelley  
Elementary School Principal Kay Engle told pupils, her voice 
cracking. ``We will build our school back, and it will be better 
than ever.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Engle estimated about 300 of the school's 450 children were back  
in class. Half the students raised their hands when she asked if 
their homes had been destroyed in the storms. 
</P>
<P>
	In a borrowed classroom, Janice West's sixth grade math and  
science class took turns telling their stories of survival. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't remember anything except screaming and praying and  
stuff,'' a girl with long blond hair said, as her classmates stared 
at the floor. ``I got up and looked out of the windows and hardly 
anything was there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The class groaned when Ms. West said she had an assignment for  
them. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a lifelong assignment,'' she said. ``Appreciate each  
person, regardless of your feelings for them. The value of a 
person's life is something we cannot replace.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
