<DOCNO> APW19990511.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:05:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Disney, Katzenberg Spat Nears End </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Walt Disney Co. chairman Michael Eisner was  
driven by principle -- not animosity -- while negotiating a bonus for 
former Disney film boss Jeffrey Katzenberg, an attorney argued 
Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	In closing statements of Katzenberg's breach of contract  
lawsuit, Disney lawyer Lou Meisinger tried to humanize Eisner, who 
has been portrayed by the plaintiff's attorney as being vindictive. 
</P>
<P>
	``If there's any villain in this drama, it's not Mr. Eisner,''  
Meisinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Katzenberg has sued Disney, claiming the company owes him at  
least $250 million in bonuses for work he did as head of its film 
division before he resigned in 1994. Disney says Katzenberg 
forfeited the bonus because he left two years before the end of his 
six-year contract. 
</P>
<P>
	The trial is being arbitrated by retired Superior Court Judge  
Paul Breckenridge in the offices of Katzenberg's attorney, Bert 
Fields. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney and Katzenberg had reached a partial settlement, which  
was sealed by the court but was reportedly $77 million. This phase 
of the case is meant to determine how big of a bonus Katzenberg 
should receive. The judge is expected to make a decision within two 
weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The case has blossomed into a bitter Hollywood feud, but Eisner  
was simply acting like a competent executive when he refused to 
allow Katzenberg to receive a 2 percent bonus on the company's 
future income after resigning, Meisinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisner ``was not driven by animosity but driven by principle,''  
the lawyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Eisner repeatedly tried to negotiate a settlement after  
Katzenberg's lawsuit was filed in 1996, but the company was 
snubbed, Meisinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are not the acts of a man driven by hatred,'' he said.  
</P>
<P>
	The company's position, Meisinger argued, has been hampered by  
the absence of the late Disney president Frank Wells, a key figure 
in the 1988 Katzenberg contract negotiations who was killed in a 
1997 helicopter crash. 
</P>
<P>
	Disney has been forced to piece together letters and memos to  
determine exactly what was owed Katzenberg; Wells' absence 
``permits Mr. Katzenberg to refute whatever statements he wants, 
Meisinger said. 
</P>
<P>
	In his rebuttal, Fields argued that the case boiled down to  
Eisner's animosity of Katzenberg. The lawyer displayed a poster 
board with Eisner's mug shot in the center, surrounded by quotes he 
has made about Katzenberg. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the quotes attributed to Eisner were: ``Jeffrey was my  
retriever,'' and ``He was the end of my pompom. I'm the 
cheerleader.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
