<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tie Admitted to Drug Scandal Figure </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PARIS (AP) -- Two cyclists, one in France and the other in  
Belgium, admitted Tuesday they had received substances supplied by 
a man being investigated in the drug scandal which enveloped the 
sport. 
</P>
<P>
	Richard Virenque, a leading French rider, admitted he used  
products given him by Bertrand Sainz, according to judicial 
officials who spoke on condition their names would not be used. 
</P>
<P>
	In Brussels, Belgium, World Cup circuit leader Frank  
Vandenbrocke said he received injections from Sainz. But, 
Vandenbrocke said he was under the impression he was getting 
homeopathic products. 
</P>
<P>
	Sainz is one of five people being investigated for involvement  
in what is described as a drug-supplying network. 
</P>
<P>
	Virenque, a former Festina cyclist, was at the center of last  
summer's Tour de France scandal. Unlike other prominent Festina 
riders, he has continually denied he knowingly took banned 
substances. 
</P>
<P>
	Sainz is accused of setting up the network along with the  
attorney Betrand Lavelot, who in the past has defended Virenque 
against doping allegations. Lavelot is also under investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	French police have seized documents showing that Sainz exchanged  
information on cyclists' blood tests with Lavelot. Both men deny 
this proves they supplied drugs. 
</P>
<P>
	Despite the scandal, Tour de France president Jean-Marie Leblanc  
insisted that this year's tour will go ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	``There is no reason why the tour shouldn't take place,'' he  
told RTL radio. ``If it wasn't necessary to have the Tour de 
France, then there would be no reason to have the Tour of Italy, 
the Grand Prix of Midi Libre, the Dauphine Libre or the Tour of 
Switzerland.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vandenbroucke said his motive in taking the shots was pure.  
</P>
<P>
	``Maybe I was naive but I did not act in bad faith,'' said  
Vandenbroucke, who has won six races this season as he shot up the 
world rankings. ``I don't think it was doping, but I'm worried 
now.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Vandenbroucke's French team Cofidis said he would be immediately  
fired if products seized by the French police and linked to 
Vandenbroucke turned out to include banned substances. 
</P>
<P>
	The Belgian star said Sainz, who is being held in a French jail  
on charges of illegally practicing medicine, had been treating him 
since early this year. ``He told me these were innocent homeopathic 
products. I trusted him,'' Vandenbroucke told a news conference one 
day after Cofidis suspended him and teammate Philippe Gaumont. 
</P>
<P>
	Vandenbroucke has not been charged in the French doping scandal,  
but he was taken in for interrogation last week. He has passed all 
drug tests on the cycling circuit. 
</P>
<P>
	In Madrid, Spanish teams ONCE and Banesto threatened to skip  
this year's Tour de France, citing concern there will be a repeat 
of the drug searches that marred last year's event, a newspaper 
reported Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	All four Spanish teams taking part in last year's race pulled  
out to protest how French police treated ONCE members when the 
scandal erupted following seizure of performance-enhancing drugs 
from top-ranked Festina. 
</P>
</TEXT>
