<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Nike Signs Chamique Holdsclaw </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) -- Nike Inc. has signed basketball sensation  
Chamique Holdsclaw to a five-year contract that could be the most 
ever paid for a woman athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw, who led the University of Tennessee to three national  
championships in four years, might be the top endorsement prospect 
in this year's crop of incoming college players, man or woman. The 
Washington Mystics of the WNBA made her this year's top draft pick. 
</P>
<P>
	Nike officials would not disclose any financial terms. They did  
say they're thrilled to sign her. 
</P>
<P>
	``We've had our eye on her for quite a while,'' said Sandi  
Bittler, director of women's sports marketing at Nike. The deal 
``underscores our commitment to women's sports.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw's agent, Lon Babby, told reporters the contract is  
``by far'' the most ever paid for a woman athlete. 
</P>
<P>
	Some industry observers predicted that Holdsclaw would be the  
first female athlete to sign a $1 million endorsement contract for 
athletic shoes. But agents close to the situation said Holdsclaw's 
contract, though in the six-figure-a-year range, falls far short of 
$1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Nike convinced Holdsclaw to go with a ``head-to-toe'' deal that  
will require her to wear Nike headwear and apparel in addition to 
basketball shoes. The company intends to build a signature shoe for 
Holdsclaw, a process that will take about a year, Nike officials 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Holdsclaw's availability prompted a heated scramble among the  
country's leading athletic shoe companies. According to industry 
sources, Adidas America, Reebok and Puma also bid for Holdsclaw. 
</P>
<P>
	Adidas had hoped its schoolwide sponsorship of Tennessee would  
give it the inside track with Holdsclaw. ``We're grateful for the 
time we had her, and we wish her luck,'' said Robert Erb, Adidas' 
director of sports marketing. 
</P>
<P>
	But Nike made its interest in Holdsclaw abundantly clear,  
despite her school's Adidas connection. Nike staffers attended 
every Lady Vols game this year. The company also wooed her by 
helping set up meetings with Michael Jordan. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
