<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Smithsonian Opens Discovery Center </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Accepting that stuffed elephants and dinosaur  
bones are no longer enough to teach people about their world, the 
National Museum of Natural History opens its new Discovery Center 
on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``In today's world, a museum cannot be unchanging and passive,''  
said Smithsonian Secretary I. Michael Heyman. ``The Discovery 
Center extends the ways natural history can be brought to museum 
visitors.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The goal of the museum is ``to help people understand the  
natural world and the integral role of humanity in it,'' added 
Robert Fri, director of the Natural History Museum. 
</P>
<P>
	Focus of the center is the S.C. Johnson IMAX theater, the  
Smithsonian Institution's second giant-screen theater. 
</P>
<P>
	More than six-stories high, the theater fills a former courtyard  
in the original 1910 museum building. 
</P>
<P>
	Beneath it is a new museum cafeteria and expanded gift shops,  
and atop the theater is a room planned for future high-technology 
science. 
</P>
<P>
	The theater is named for Samuel C. Johnson, head of the SC  
Johnson consumer products company and a former regent of the 
Smithsonian who donated $1 million toward the project. 
</P>
<P>
	On Tuesday, Johnson also announced that he plans to make a  
donation to the District of Columbia schools to cover the cost of a 
field trip to the museum next year for every sixth-grade student in 
the district. 
</P>
<P>
	Discovery Communications, which operates several cable  
television channels, including the Discovery Channel, the Learning 
Channel and the Travel Channel, also contributed to the project. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
