<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> U S West Cutting Internet Cost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DENVER (AP) -- Caught in a race with cable and telephone  
companies for computer users, U S West Inc. on Tuesday announced 
plans to expand its high-speed Internet access service and cut the 
price by 25 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is a sign that competition is picking up between cable  
and phone industries, which both offer Internet access at speeds at 
least five times faster than a typical computer modem. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West itself was once a player in the cable TV industry, but  
decided to get out in order to focus on the telephone business. The 
cable unit it spun off last year, MediaOne, last week agreed to be 
acquired by AT&AMP;T Corp. as part of a the long-distance carrier's 
goal of delivering phone and other telecommunications services over 
cable TV lines. 
</P>
<P>
	In the competition between cable and phone companies, the key is  
getting the high-speed Internet capability in place at an 
affordable price. 
</P>
<P>
	``Our whole objective is to drive the price down to a consumer  
price level as fast as we can,'' said Joe Zell, president of U S 
West's data networking unit. ``The more that we're able to drive 
the cost of the service down, the more viable it becomes as 
entertainment in the home.'' 
</P>
<P>
	U S West cut its price from $40 a month to $29.95 a month for  
its basic digital subscriber line, which processes data at 256 
kilobits a second, compared with 56 kilobits per second in a 
typical computer modem. 
</P>
<P>
	For example, a large software package that takes about an hour  
to download with a 56K modem can be downloaded in about 10 minutes 
via a digital line, Zell said. 
</P>
<P>
	For the line plus unlimited Internet service, U S West cut the  
price from $60 a month to $47.90 a month, Zell said. 
</P>
<P>
	U S West officials also plan to install the necessary equipment  
for the high-speed data lines in more than 250 offices, making the 
service available in more than 40 cities across its 14-state region 
within one year to 18 months, Zell said. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want to try to drive the market now before the cable  
competitors get a foothold,'' he said in a telephone interview from 
New York. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts said the price cut, similar to those taken recently by  
other Baby Bells, will help make the technology more affordable to 
home and small business computer users. 
</P>
<P>
	``Getting the price down to be competitive with cable is good,''  
said Bruce Kasrel, an industry analyst with Forrester Research. 
</P>
<P>
	``Overall, I would say cable is much more accessible,'' he said.  
``The cable companies are building out for better video and data is 
along for a ride.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Peter Clemente, vice president of online research company Cyber  
Dialog, predicted the U S West cut would trigger an overall price 
reduction by high-speed Internet service providers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We'll absolutely see the other telephone companies following  
suit,'' Clemente said. 
</P>
<P>
	The high-speed access service is offered by phone companies  
through existing lines with new digital equipment to handle the 
data processing. Cable companies offer the service through upgraded 
digital technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Analysts estimated high-speed Internet services offered by cable  
companies have about 800,000 subscribers nationwide who pay from 
$30 a month to $60 a month. 
</P>
<P>
	High-speed Internet services offered by phone companies have  
about 50,000 nationwide, with costs ranging from $40 a month to 
about $200 a month, said Clemente. 
</P>
<P>
	Zell said U S West has about 30,000 of the phone company  
subscribers. 
</P>
<P>
	Clemente said both industries face two significant hurdles:  
getting the technology to households and convincing consumers that 
it is worth their while. 
</P>
<P>
	``High-speed Internet access, with the right market strategy,  
should not be a significant hurdle,'' he said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
