<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Offer May Seek To Move Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Pittsburgh inched closer Tuesday to joining  
Hartford, Winnipeg, Quebec and other cities that lost NHL teams 
with a new buyer's offer of $85 million to move the Pittsburgh 
Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	NHL attorney Jeffrey Levitan revealed the offer during a hearing  
on the league's request for quick work on the fate of the team, 
which is in U.S. Bankruptcy Court proceedings for the second time 
in 25 years. 
</P>
<P>
	The buyer is believed to be Paul Allen, the Seattle billionaire  
who also owns the NFL's Seattle Seahawks and NBA's Portland Trail 
Blazers. The Penguins would provide another wintertime tenant for 
the Rose Garden in Portland. 
</P>
<P>
	NHL commissioner Gary Bettman would not confirm Allen's bid  
during a news conference minutes before the Maple Leafs-Penguins 
playoff game Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``We have not finalized or signed a deal with anyone,'' Bettman  
said. ``If there's speculation that's a done deal, I think people 
are getting ahead of themselves.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Bettman said the NHL remains firmly behind Hall of Famer Mario  
Lemieux's reorganization plan, but time is growing tight as 
planning already is underway for the 1999-2000 season. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are fully supportive of Mario's plan, but there are a  
variety of conditions that must be satisfied first,'' Bettman said, 
citing a renegotiated arena lease as the first priority. 
</P>
<P>
	SMG, which operates the Civic Arena, is not to blame for the  
Penguins' financial mess, Bettman said, but he cautioned that the 
Lemieux plan will not go through unless SMG renegotiates. The 
Penguins currently pay $5 million-$6 million a year to play in the 
38-year-old Civic Arena, the oldest in the NHL. 
</P>
<P>
	``This club is not viable in Pittsburgh without a new lease,''  
Bettman said. ``We would like to have the Pens reorganized in 
Pittsburgh, but if it (the Lemieux plan) fails, we have to look at 
alternatives.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The NHL also could liquidate the Penguins and disperse its  
players in a draft among the other league teams. But Bettman said 
that will occur only if the alternative owner decides he doesn't 
have enough time to market the Penguins in a new city for next 
season. 
</P>
<P>
	The new bid represents $35 million more than Lemieux's $50  
million cash bid endorsed by the NHL, so the team's 200 creditors 
stand to earn more from it. 
</P>
<P>
	However, Chuck Greenberg, Lemieux's attorney, said the  
assumption of debt by the Lemieux group will eventually make his 
bid more attractive. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not surprised that another party is interested in the  
team. There were a number of bidders who emerged the last time the 
league expanded,'' Greenberg said. ``We are not going to concern 
ourselves with what might happen if our bid is not confirmed. We 
want to put all our energies into making this a viable franchise in 
Pittsburgh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The offer mentioned by Levitan is $30 million less than the  
recent reported price for the Tampa Bay Lightning, who finished at 
19-54-9 and unlike the Penguins missed this year's playoffs. But 
the Lightning plays in a nearly new arena, the Ice Palace, that is 
controlled by the team's new ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	Financial trouble and uncertainty about the looming season have  
reduced the Penguins' value, said William Daly, the league's vice 
president for legal affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are not ideal conditions under which to be selling a  
sports franchise,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A court and creditors' review of the NHL's plan to dissolve the  
Penguins has been scheduled for 11 a.m. May 19. 
</P>
<P>
	That is 12 days before the NHL's deadline for resolving Penguins  
ownership and the same day as Game 7, if necessary, in the current 
playoff series with Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly said the league wants to begin scheduling for next season  
and needs to know how many teams it will have and whether they will 
travel to Pittsburgh or another city for games. 
</P>
<P>
	The league is using the prospect of losing the team to push the  
Penguins toward Lemieux and his investors, although the tone of 
court proceedings has become more grave as the deadline nears. 
</P>
<P>
	``The longer it goes, the harder it is for the league,'' Bettman  
said. 
</P>
<P>
	Las Vegas and Kansas City are among the other U.S. cities that  
have been trying to get hockey teams. Roger Marino, one of the 
Penguins' three owners along with Howard Baldwin and Morris 
Belzberg, traveled there and elsewhere to pitch the Penguins. 
</P>
<P>
	At the May 19 hearing, Judge Bernard Markovitz could schedule  
votes by creditors on the NHL's plan and the Lemieux bid, perhaps 
simultaneously. 
</P>
<P>
	``We want our alternative plan put on the same track as the  
Lemieux plan,'' Bettman said. 
</P>
<P>
	The biggest creditors, the Penguins' banks and insurers, and the  
NHL want the votes to happen at the same time. But other creditors 
object, saying that could be confusing. 
</P>
<P>
	The judge faulted the NHL for waiting so long to prepare its  
plan. Levitan said the league held back at first because it did not 
want to upset negotiations with prospective buyers. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux, who is owed $26.2 million in deferred salary and is the  
Penguins' biggest unsecured creditor, is courting Broadcast.com 
founder Mark Cuban, a native of suburban Pittsburgh, as a potential 
investor. They met again on Tuesday afternoon, Greenberg said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins' banks, insurers, equipment suppliers, bond  
holders, former players and other creditors are owed $125 million. 
The team lost $10 million last year and did not sell out recent 
home playoff games with New Jersey, though its first two home games 
against Toronto are sellouts. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's troubles stem from long-term deals that Baldwin,  
strapped for cash after losing $25 million during the 1994-95 
lockout season, signed with Fox Sports and SMG. He received money 
upfront that kept the team in business. 

</P>
</TEXT>
