<DOCNO> APW19990511.0192 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 09:25:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Books and Authors: Robert McNamara </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PROVIDENCE, R.I. (AP) -- Did 58,000 Americans need to die in  
Vietnam? Or did Washington bungle opportunities to halt the sad 
procession of body bags? 
</P>
<P>
	Families of the fallen soldiers may be unsettled by answers  
offered by former U.S. Defense Secretary Robert S. McNamara, a 
principle strategist of the war, in ``Argument Without End: In 
Search of Answers to the Vietnam Tragedy,'' published by Pacific 
Affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	The book argues that leaders in Hanoi and Washington passed up  
many opportunities that could have averted war -- or lessened its 
carnage -- by making bad decisions or failing to communicate. 
</P>
<P>
	``Both Washington and Hanoi could have accomplished their  
purposes without the appalling loss of life,'' writes McNamara, 
defense secretary from 1961 until 1968. 
</P>
<P>
	The American casualties were but a small fraction of 3.8 million  
North and South Vietnamese soldiers and civilians killed in the war 
that lasted from the mid-1960s to 1973. 
</P>
<P>
	``Argument Without End'' is the second book in which McNamara  
seeks to come to terms with what some called ``McNamara's War'' 
because of his dominant role in formulating the Johnson 
administration's strategies in Vietnam. 
</P>
<P>
	In his 1995 memoirs, McNamara admitted that the policies were  
``terribly wrong,'' and that he had reached this conclusion by 
1967. That confession provoked outcry from American veterans, who 
said McNamara was wrong to let the war escalate when he knew U.S. 
policies were flawed. 
</P>
<P>
	Like the first book, the second is something of a McNamara mea  
culpa. It's also an exercise in soul-searching. 
</P>
<P>
	Now age 82, McNamara is in a way a victim of the war he helped  
wage. Many Vietnam vets hate him. But he is like them in one way: 
The war weighs heavily on his mind. 
</P>
<P>
	McNamara says he wrote the new book to identify mistakes made  
during the Vietnam War so similar errors won't be made in the 
future. 
</P>
<P>
	``Wars between great and lesser powers ... are certain to  
occur,'' McNamara writes. ``But can we not reduce their severity by 
learning from history?'' 
</P>
<P>
	McNamara's search for answers led him to initiate a series of  
conferences in Hanoi with his old North Vietnamese foes, including 
Gen. Vo Nguyen Giap. Comments made by McNamara's erstwhile enemies 
in those discussions, held between November 1995 and February 1998, 
are used as pillars for his new book. 
</P>
<P>
	Retired Army Col. Harry Summers, who wrote a book about  
strategies used in the Vietnam War, thinks McNamara's quest for 
answers is actually a quest to find other shoulders on which to 
place blame for American deaths. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's concerned about his legacy. He's trying to absolve  
himself and explain himself away,'' said Summers, who served two 
tours of duty in Vietnam and is editor of Vietnam Magazine. 
</P>
<P>
	``Argument Without End'' is co-authored by McNamara and Thomas  
Biersteker and James Blight of Brown University, Robert K. Brigham 
of Vassar College, and Herbert Schandler, a retired U.S. Army 
colonel who served three tours of duty in Vietnam and is now a 
professor at the National Defense University in Washington, D.C. 
</P>
<P>
	Relying on his own knowledge of the war era and on statements by  
former North Vietnamese officials who attended the 1995-98 
conferences in Hanoi, McNamara offers a litany of ``missed 
opportunities'' which he contends could have averted the war or 
ended it before it spun out of control:. 
</P>
<P>
	--In the late 1940s, Communist leader Ho Chi Minh sent ``many  
signals'' to Washington indicating he wanted peaceful relations, 
McNamara writes. Preoccupied with ending World War II and 
confronting the Soviet threat, McNamara says, Washington never 
responded. 
</P>
<P>
	--Washington wrongly perceived North Vietnam to be a pawn of the  
Soviets or the Chinese, McNamara says. 
</P>
<P>
	--Seeking to reclaim colonies in Indochina, France went to war  
against Ho Chi Minh's guerrillas in 1945. In 1950, the United 
States decided to provide financial support for France's war -- a 
``very, very costly mistake.'' 
</P>
<P>
	--After the French defeat in 1954, an international conference in  
Geneva divided Vietnam into the Communist north and the 
pro-American south, and called for elections to be held in 1956 to 
reunify the country. The United States refused to endorse the 
election, fearing Ho Chi Minh's Communists would win. McNamara 
suggests Washington could have averted war had the elections gone 
ahead. 
</P>
<P>
	--Washington and Hanoi could have agreed on a neutral coalition  
government in Saigon at any time from 1961 to 1964, McNamara 
maintains, but a lack of communication resulted in them failing to 
understand that their goals for Vietnam were compatible. 
</P>
<P>
	--When Communist guerrillas attacked a South Vietnamese Army  
barracks at Pleiku on Feb. 7, 1965, killing eight Americans and 
wounding more than 100 others, the Communists didn't know U.S. 
soldiers were there. Had Washington known that at the time, the 
McNamara book suggests, the United States might have given more 
thought before launching ``Rolling Thunder,'' a massive bombing of 
North Vietnam that was a prelude to the ground war. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of these arguments have been made before. They have been  
countered by some observers who say Cold War pressures made the war 
inevitable, or that the war could have been won had restraints not 
been placed on the U.S. military. 
</P>
<P>
	Daniel Ellsberg, famed leaker of the ``Pentagon Papers,'' said  
McNamara's book manages to overlook a crucial ``missed 
opportunity'': his failure to make a lot of noise in public about 
his own doubts the war could be won. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1967, McNamara wrote memos to President Lyndon Johnson  
voicing displeasure with the conduct of the war. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson disagreed, and McNamara left the Pentagon in 1968, but  
kept his opinions of the war to himself, apparently out of loyalty 
to Johnson. 
</P>
<P>
	``He kept his mouth shut as guys on both sides died year after  
year,'' says Ellsberg. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:05:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Qualcomm-Ericsson Deal Gets Fed OK </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SAN DIEGO (AP) -- The U.S. Justice Department approved a deal to  
resolve a long-running patent dispute between Qualcomm Inc. and 
Swiss-based LM Ericsson Co., company officials said. 
</P>
<P>
	Approval of the deal between the rival telecommunications  
companies was unconditional, Ericsson spokeswoman Kathy Egan said 
Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	That means San Diego-based Qualcomm can sell its money-losing  
infrastructure division to Ericsson in a couple of weeks, Qualcomm 
spokeswoman Christine Trimble said. 
</P>
<P>
	More than 1,200 of the division will transfer to Ericsson. Last  
week, some employees filed a class-action lawsuit claiming that the 
switch would deprive them of unvested stock options that could 
total millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	Options usually are offered as hiring incentives and bonuses.  
They allow workers to buy stock at the current market price and 
then sell it after certain ``vesting'' dates. 
</P>
<P>
	Such arrangements can be extremely lucrative if -- as with  
Qualcomm -- the stock price soars. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, Qualcomm announced that at least 94 percent of the  
1,053 division employees with unvested stock options had agreed to 
accept a bonus instead of joining the lawsuit. 
</P>
<P>
	The signup deadline was last Friday for the bonus, which will  
pay employees a percentage of the value of their unvested stock. 
The company has said workers could get anywhere from $20,000 to 
more than $1 million. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are pleased with the overwhelming acceptance of the  
retention bonus plan,'' Irwin Jacobs, Qualcomm's chief executive, 
said in a statement. 
</P>
<P>
	That still leaves more than 60 workers who could join the suit,  
with potential damages of more than $30 million, said David 
Perkins, the lead attorney for the employees. 
</P>
<P>
	Perkins claimed Qualcomm pressured employees to take the bonus.  
</P>
<P>
	``We're also going to look into the possibility of duress on  
these employees,'' Perkins said. ``If they were pressuring 
employees to sign, then that's not legal.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Trimble said employees were given ample time to decide what they  
what they wanted to do. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not able to comment on speculation but I can tell you  
that they were presented the plan through meetings last month,'' 
she said. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0194 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 13:45:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Coach Silas Gets 4-Yr. Hornets Deal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 *AP Photos    	
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE (AP) -- Paul Silas, who moved gracefully from a backup  
role to transform the Charlotte Hornets into a winning team, signed 
a $6 million contract Tuesday to coach the NBA club for the next 
four seasons. 
</P>
<P>
	Silas, 55, was an assistant when coach Dave Cowens resigned in  
March in a salary dispute. When Silas took over as interim coach, 
the team's record was 4-11. 
</P>
<P>
	Behind Silas, the Hornets put together a 22-13 record, including  
nine straight victories in one stretch, and missed making the NBA 
playoffs by one game. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was thrown into a situation where no one expected much,''  
said Hornets forward Anthony Mason, who has one year remaining on 
his contract. ``We share the same mentality, and we both want to 
win just as much.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A popular choice among the Hornets players, Silas said he was  
surprised when he got a phone call last week from Hornets owner 
George Shinn, who asked to meet with him at the airport. 
</P>
<P>
	``I intended to come in with my best poker face for the  
negotiations,'' Silas said. ``But when I saw the offer, I broke 
into a big grin. I guess I blew it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The contract includes a guaranteed $4.5 million over three  
years, with an optional fourth year, according to media reports. 
The team did not disclose the terms. 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn, who recently ended negotiations to sell half-interest in  
the Hornets to Michael Jordan, said he was thrilled to sign Silas 
to a long-term contract. 
</P>
<P>
	``After Paul Silas took over as coach, something special  
happened to this team,'' he said. ``Of all the coaches that I have 
spoken to and seen work over the years, Paul has impressed me more 
with his desire to develop each player to their highest 
potential.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Shinn left the news conference without taking any questions.  
</P>
<P>
	General manager Bob Bass described Silas as tenacious.  
</P>
<P>
	``Seldom do you meet a man who never gave up,'' he said. ``He  
has had this dream, and he never gave it up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silas, who joined the team as an assistant in 1997, saved most  
of his praise for the players, whom he calls ``my guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``This team has a chance to do some special things next year,''  
he said. ``To me, it was nothing short of a miracle what this team 
did this year, missing the playoffs by an inch.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silas said he hoped to keep the same team together so they could  
become one of the NBA's elite clubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``These guys really gave it to me,'' he said. ``They worked hard  
every night and never dogged it. I look forward to coaching this 
team a long time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silas guided the old San Diego Clippers to a 78-168 mark in  
three seasons as coach immediately after completing a 16-year NBA 
career. Silas also was an assistant with New Jersey, New York and 
Phoenix. 
</P>
<P>
	He acknowledged that it was critical for the front office to  
sign Mason and Eddie Jones, who also could become a free agent 
after next year. Another need is a backup at point guard, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	``They stepped up to the plate for me so I don't see why they  
won't do it for the players,'' Silas said. 
</P>
<P>
	Mason, who missed the entire season with a ruptured biceps  
tendon, wasn't ready to show his hand. Asked if he believed the 
Hornets were willing to spend the money to keep him, he responded: 
``We shall see.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0195 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:08:12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Japan Auto Import Sales Fall </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	TOKYO (AP) -- Hurt by the continuing recession, sales of imported  
cars, trucks and buses in Japan slipped 0.6 percent on year in 
April, an industry group reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	Total import sales in April amounted to 19,962 vehicles, down  
from 20,084 the same month a year ago -- the second straight monthly 
drop, the Japan Automobile Importers Association said. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of imported passenger cars jumped 1.8 percent to 19,382,  
but truck imports plummeted 44.6 percent to 579. One imported bus 
was sold in April, the same as last year. 
</P>
<P>
	Kunihiko Ono, a spokesman for the association, said imported  
vehicle sales were likely to remain weak amid few signs of a 
significant economic recovery in Japan. 
</P>
<P>
	Mercedes-Benz was the leading import brand in April for the  
sixth straight month. Mercedes-Benz had a 21 percent share of the 
import market, followed by Volkswagen with 16 percent and BMW with 
9 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	By country, sales of passenger cars imported from Germany rose  
5.5 percent to 11,065. Mercedes sales increased 40.6 percent to 
3,949, Opel sales grew 3.1 percent to 1,383 and German-made Ford 
sales soared 183.6 percent to 431. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of U.S.-made passenger cars rose 24.2 percent to 4,363,  
with Ford sales rising 2.6 percent to 240 and Honda sales soaring 
371.1 percent to 1,630. 
</P>
<P>
	Ono said Ford's April sales were boosted by demand for its  
recently introduced three-door hatchback, the ``Ka,'' while Honda 
continued to benefit from strong demand for its Inspire and Saber 
luxury sedans. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of other U.S.-made passenger cars fell, however, with  
DaimlerChrysler's sales slumping 39.7 percent, GM's dropping 8.8 
percent and Toyota's plunging 52.5 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	Sales of passenger cars from Britain dropped 15.2 percent.  

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0196 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 13:45:11 </DATE_TIME>
