<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:13:25 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Baffert's Preakness Decision Easy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BALTIMORE (AP) -- Bob Baffert intends to let the luck determine  
whether he runs fillies Silverbulletday and Excellent Meeting in 
the Preakness. 
</P>
<P>
	If Monday's workout means anything, then Baffert's decision on  
Silverbulletday will be an easy one. 
</P>
<P>
	After the filly covered five furlongs in an impressive 59  
seconds at Churchill Downs, Baffert said, ``I figured after she 
worked they'd have to put water on the track to cool it down. 
That's what you want to see coming into a race like the 
Preakness.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Both fillies are entered in Friday's Black-Eyed Susan, where  
Silverbulletday drew the rail and Excellent Meeting received the 
fourth position. If they get anywhere near that kind of placement 
in Wednesday's Preakness draw, Baffert will saddle both for 
Saturday's middle jewel of the Triple Crown. 
</P>
<P>
	``Fate will decide whether we run or not,'' Baffert said.  
``These are two great fillies and I'm not going to waste a (start). 
I want to run to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Silverbulletday has won 10 of 11 career races, including the  
Kentucky Oaks. Excellent Meeting, fifth in the Kentucky Derby, was 
to work out this morning. 
</P>
<P>
	In other news, the trainer of First American pulled his horse  
from the Preakness, citing a pair of injuries. The colt, who took 
16th in the Derby, has been bothered by fluid in his lungs and 
developed a bone chip in his ankle. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm very disappointed. When we decided to make this trip, we  
thought he would be in good shape,'' trainer Eduardo Caramori said. 
``The lung wasn't clear for the Derby and still isn't great, and 
the first sign that the ankle was bothering him came yesterday. 
With that combination, we have to pull out. You can't go into a big 
race at less than 100 percent.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The departure of First American leaves the stakes barn at  
Pimlico near empty. Although most of the entrants plan to arrive 
Wednesday, trainer Nick Zito shipped his two horses, Stephen Got 
Even and Adonis, last Friday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's a lot easier for a trainer and his staff to stay in one  
place and ship in at the last minute,'' Zito conceded. ``I feel 
that if you come here and get used to the racetrack, it should mean 
something.'' 
</P>
<P>
	His strategy worked to perfection in 1996, with upset winner  
Louis Quatorze. Zito is counting on similar results this year, even 
though both of his entrants finished far back in the Kentucky 
Derby. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were right in '96 and hopefully we'll be right in '99,'' he  
said. ``If they do well Saturday, we'll be vindicated.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Zito was among the first arrivals at Pimlico three years ago,  
and his judgment appeared justified when Louis Quatorze charged 
past Skip Away and paid $19 to win. 
</P>
<P>
	If Stephen Got Even or Adonis win Saturday, it was also be  
considered a surprise. Stephen Got Even is coming off a 14th-place 
finish at the Derby, and Adonis took 17th place. 
</P>
<P>
	``They deserved the right to be in the Derby. But they had  
traffic problems and didn't have the best of trips,'' Zito said. 
``Hopefully, they'll have better luck here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0198 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 17:43:21 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Last Cop-Hiring Subsidies Announced </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Announcing grants to reach a goal of putting  
100,000 new police officers on the street, President Clinton 
planned Wednesday to ask Congress to toughen penalties for misuse 
of biological agents that can be used as weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton has made his commitment to put 100,000 more cops on the  
street through federal subsidies a hallmark of his administration. 
Although the actual number of new officers is running behind the 
number funded, administration officials were treating the latest 
round of grants as a milestone. 
</P>
<P>
	As he presents $95 million in grants for the last 1,500  
officers, Clinton planned to push Congress to renew the community 
policing program for five years and embrace his crime package, 
especially its initiatives aimed at cutting juvenile violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton also planned to unveil legislation to toughen penalties  
for unauthorized possession of harmful biological agents like 
anthrax and hold certified handlers of such materials accountable 
for their misuse, an administration officials said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``It essentially bans the possession of these agents for other  
than peaceful purposes and makes the unsafe handling of them a 
crime as well,'' said the official, speaking on condition of 
anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	Among the 526 grants being announced Wednesday, officials said,  
were $2.3 million to hire 30 new officers for the Miami-Dade Public 
Schools police in Florida; $1.5 million to hire 20 new officers in 
Raleigh, N.C.; $1.9 million for 20 new officers in Fairfax, Va., 
and $1.6 million for 21 new officers in Irvington, N.J. A 
half-dozen towns in Puerto Rico were receiving funds for 137 new 
officers. 
</P>
<P>
	Republicans have accused the administration of failing to make  
good on the 100,000 cops pledge. And a recent Justice Department 
Inspector General's report said several state and local police 
agencies had used the grants to supplant -- rather than supplement -- 
state and local funds. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration officials said that there is a lag of up to 18  
months between the time an agency receives the funds and when a new 
trainee is ready to hit the streets, claim Clinton can boast of 
more than 50,000 new officers already on the beat. 
</P>
<P>
	There is also some flexibility for police agencies who want to  
use funds to upgrade communications and other gear in order to free 
up officers for patrols. 
</P>
<P>
	Jose Cerda of the White House domestic policy team said the  
agencies investigated by the Justice Department's inspector general 
represented less than 1 percent of the recipients and were singled 
out for review because of administration suspicions. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every indication from the Justice Department, from surveys  
that they conduct regularly, is that every six months there are 
more cops on the street,'' Cerda said. ``The program is working 
well.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Clinton wants to extend the community policing program. He would  
spend $1.3 billion annually to help local governments to continue 
to hire more police, buy bulletproof vests and improved 
communications gear, hire more prosecutors and engage more closely 
with schools and community leaders. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0199 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 06:24:50 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veto Threatened on Kosovo Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House-Senate negotiators hoping to ship  
President Clinton legislation this week paying for the fight with 
Yugoslavia, aid to Central America and other items are facing a new 
veto threat from the White House. But it seems likely that such a 
confrontation will be avoided. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from the two chambers planned to meet this afternoon  
to begin crafting a compromise, multibillion-dollar package. But 
Monday evening, White House officials threatened for the first time 
to veto it, citing a host of objections. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, the administration had threatened to veto a  
stand-alone aid measure for Central America and U.S. farmers 
because it would cut domestic programs and add environmental and 
other items the White House opposes. They had also complained about 
-- but not threatened to veto -- a separate bill in which the House 
more than doubled Clinton's $6 billion request for the fight over 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, however, White House officials warned that the new,  
blended legislation was in danger of being rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a number of very troubling issues ... and the  
president's senior advisors would continue to recommend that he 
veto this legislation unless the objectionable provisions are 
resolved in a satisfactory manner,'' said a letter to House leaders 
from White House budget chief Jacob Lew. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked specifically about the extra House-approved defense funds,  
Lew said in an interview, ``It's important to scale it back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Members of both parties have said privately that they don't  
think Clinton would veto the Kosovo package as long as it is kept 
at roughly the $13 billion range the House approved last week. 
Congressional bargainers seem likely to pare it back even further, 
perhaps to about $10 billion, said participants who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	These officials say that with American troops in the field and  
with Clinton himself saying the Pentagon needs more money, he would 
be hard-pressed to reject such a measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The extra money the House added was for U.S. military operations  
and installations around the world, and a pay raise for the troops. 
The most likely item to be dropped is $1 billion the House added to 
modernize U.S. bases overseas, aides say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really haven't settled anything yet,'' House Appropriations  
Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 16, Clinton requested nearly $1 billion to help Honduras  
and other Central American nations devastated by last autumn's 
deadly Hurricane Mitch. He later asked for $152 million to help 
U.S. farmers hurt by record-low prices for wheat, corn and other 
farm products. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 23, the Senate approved a $2.5 billion bill for Central  
America and farmers, which included aid they had added for the U.S. 
steel, oil, gas and mining industries. The next day, the House 
approved a $1.3 billion version without the Senate add-ons. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration objections include Senate language that would bar  
the federal government from sharing in the $246 billion settlement 
states have won from the tobacco industry, delay increases in 
royalties oil companies pay for using federal lands and postpone 
stricter requirements for hardrock mining on government property. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House also opposes GOP plans to pay for the Central  
America aid with cuts in food stamps, along with money the United 
States uses to back loans by international lending agencies and 
other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration prefers using this year's expected federal  
surplus. Many aides from both parties, however, believe a 
compromise will be reached on spending reductions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
