<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 9 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Attacks Continue in Yugoslavia  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO continued its airstrikes on  
Yugoslavia today and Serb media said at least seven people were 
killed in the attacks. The strikes continued as NATO said there was 
no evidence Yugoslavia had withdrawn any of the estimated 40,000 
troops and special police from the Kosovo. In Washington, Defense 
Secretary William Cohen said NATO will accept nothing less than a 
total withdrawal of forces from Kosovo as part of its conditions to 
halt the air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	China Drops Demand of U.N. Council  
</P>
<P>
	UNITED NATIONS (AP) -- China dropped its demand Tuesday that the  
Security Council condemn NATO's bombing of its Belgrade embassy, 
but warned again it wouldn't discuss a Kosovo peace plan until the 
alliance stops attacking Yugoslavia. The bombing incident has 
soured U.S.-China relations and threatens to complicate a 
diplomatic solution to the conflict. As a permanent, veto-wielding 
member of the Council, China must support any resolution codifying 
a peace plan. China has said that the chief condition for peace 
talks was an end to the NATO airstrikes. 

</P>
<P>
	CIA Error May Yield Budget Increase  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- The CIA may well see one of its biggest  
blunders turn into a budget boost. On Capitol Hill today, Sen. Ted 
Stevens, R-Alaska, chairman of the Senate Appropriations Committee, 
asked Defense Secretary William Cohen whether the mistaken bombing 
of the Chinese Embassy in Belgrade stemmed from overworked 
intelligence analysts with underfunded information databases. Many 
lawmakers have reacted to the bombing error by talking about 
pumping more money into the U.S. intelligence system. The Clinton 
administration is seeking about $29 billion for intelligence 
programs in the 2000 budget, an increase of about 9 percent. 

</P>
<P>
	Republicans Restate Tax-Cut Pledge  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Republicans used today's symbolic ``Tax  
Freedom Day'' to renew their promise to pass tax relief in Congress 
this year. The Tax Foundation calculates ``Tax Freedom Day'' as the 
time it takes Americans on average to finish paying all federal, 
state and local taxes each year and begin working for themselves. 
This year's date is 131 days into 1999, one day later than last 
year. Republicans are trying to put together a tax relief bill that 
would eventually grow to nearly $800 billion over the next decade. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Welfare Recipients Studied  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most Americans who have been swept from  
welfare rolls have jobs and earn more than they got from the 
government -- but not enough to escape poverty. That's the picture 
painted by 21 state studies that, after much speculation, provide 
the first glimpse of what has happened to the millions who have 
left welfare amid tough new rules and unprecedented economic 
growth. While homelessness and other worst-case scenarios are rare, 
a substantial number of these families face hardships, such as 
trouble paying for food and utility bills, an Associated Press 
review of the studies shows. 

</P>
<P>
	Diller Abandons Pursuit of Lycos  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Media mogul Barry Diller will officially abandon  
his plans tomorrow to buy the top-rated Internet site Lycos, 
according to people close to the situation. Diller had planned to 
create a company worth $22 billion by combining Lycos with his Home 
Shopping Network and Ticketmaster Online-Citysearch Inc., a ticket 
agency and online entertainment directory. But Diller couldn't win 
over small day traders who own a major stake in Lycos. 

</P>
<P>
	Star Wars Tickets To Go On Sale  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- Advance ticket sales for ``Star Wars: Episode  
I -- The Phantom Menace,'' will begin at 3 p.m. EDT tomorrow. Ticket 
sellers were gearing up for the onslaught by adding staff and 
equipment. MovieFone, the company that sells tickets over the 
telephone and Internet, boosted its Web capacity to enable 10 times 
more people than usual to use the service. ``Phantom Menace'' 
doesn't actually open until May 19. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Sees Modest Gains  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 18.90  
at 11,026.15 today. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange 
led decliners 1,717-1,320. The Nasdaq was up 40.27 to 2,566.66. 

</P>
<P>
	Sampras Gets By in 1999 Clay Debut  
</P>
<P>
	ROME (AP) -- Pete Sampras, overcoming rustiness and his dislike  
of playing on clay, struggled to a first-round victory over Bohdan 
Ulihrach today in the Italian Open. Sampras, seeded second, 
committed 49 unforced errors to 11 for the tentative Ulihrach, but 
got past the Czech 3-6, 6-2, 7-6 (7-2). It was the American's first 
singles match since losing to Richard Krajicek at the Lipton 
Championships on March 23, and first outing on clay since he bowed 
out of last year's French Open in the second round. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  
</P>
</TEXT>
