<DOCNO> APW19990511.0205 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 18:31:39 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Columbia/HCA Spinoffs Complete </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) -- Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. completed  
its spinoff of 61 hospitals into two new publicly traded companies 
Tuesday, the latest step in an overhaul prompted by a 2-year-old 
federal fraud investigation. 
</P>
<P>
	The spinoffs netted the nation's biggest hospital chain about  
$900 million, as each of the 61 hospitals paid for the right to be 
spun off. Columbia was left with 236 hospitals, down from a high of 
345 in 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia shareholders on Tuesday received one share in each of  
the two independent companies for every 19 shares of Columbia stock 
held on April 30. 
</P>
<P>
	The new companies are Nashville-based Lifepoint Hospitals Inc.,  
which owns mostly rural hospitals, and Dallas-based Triad Hospitals 
Inc, which will operate mainly in medium-sized urban markets. 
Shares of both companies will begin trading on the Nasdaq stock 
market on Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Even with the spinoffs, Columbia will retain its title as  
nation's biggest hospital chain and have annual revenues of about 
$15 billion. But the spinoffs and other recent sales have left a 
more focused company that will ``get more bang for its buck,'' said 
Kemp Dolliver of SG Cowen Securities Corp. 
</P>
<P>
	The spinoffs ``will allow management to focus more on its core  
operations,'' he said. And the hospitals that were spun off will 
get more attention and resources from their new management, he 
said, while continuing to utilize Columbia's data processing 
services and remaining in its purchasing network. 
</P>
<P>
	``I am absolutely convinced that this is one instance where one  
plus one plus one is equal to a whole lot more than three when the 
dust settles,'' Columbia vice president Vic Campbell said. 
</P>
<P>
	While the spinoff is ``not the final step'' in the company's  
restructuring efforts, ``it is the last major piece,'' Campbell 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	When Columbia was headed by the hard-charging Rick Scott, it  
grew at a staggering rate. Scott was forced out by the Columbia 
board because of his response to the investigation and replaced by 
Dr. Thomas Frist in July 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Frist vowed to concentrate on patient care instead of corporate  
growth and began selling off parts of the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Since Frist took over, the company has sold outright some 60  
hospitals and 40 to 50 surgery centers, as well as most of its home 
health care and benefits management businesses. 
</P>
<P>
	Columbia remains in settlement talks with the U.S. Justice  
Department, which has spent the past two years investigating 
whether Columbia overcharged Medicare, Medicaid and other 
government health programs. Four Columbia middle managers were 
indicted in Florida, and their trial began last week. 
</P>
<P>
	Lifepoint has 22 hospitals in Alabama, Florida, Georgia, Kansas,  
Kentucky, Louisiana, Tennessee, Utah and Wyoming. Triad includes 39 
hospitals and 19 surgery centers in Alabama, Arizona, Arkansas, 
California, Kansas, Louisiana, Missouri, New Mexico, Oklahoma, 
Oregon and Texas. 
</P>
<P>
	Lifepoint plans to sell three of its hospitals, most of which  
are in rural areas. 
</P>
<P>
	Patients won't see much difference from ``the day before to the  
day after'' the spinoffs, Lifepoint CEO Scott Mercy said. ``But 
over the next 12 months, you'll see expanded services, and we've 
got a dedicated effort to recruit more physicians.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Triad plans to sell five of its 39 hospitals by the end of the  
year to reduce its $628 million debt load, said CEO James D. 
``Denny'' Shelton. Most of its hospitals are in urban areas. 
</P>
<P>
	LifePoint would have posted operating losses of $18 million on  
revenue of $498 million if independent last year, while Triad's 
losses would have been $86 million on revenue of $1.6 billion. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
