<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Lycos Shares Rise on USA Report </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Shares of Lycos Inc. soared 17 percent Monday as  
investors cheered reports that USA Networks is expected to abandon 
its plans to buy the Internet portal. 
</P>
<P>
	Barry Diller, chairman and chief executive of USA Networks, has  
been stymied by investor opposition to his plans to combine Lycos 
with his Home Shopping Network and Ticketmaster City-Search Inc. 
</P>
<P>
	Diller, however, hasn't reached a final decision, and still may  
decide to sweeten his bid, according to a report Monday in The Wall 
Street Journal, which cited bankers close to the company. 
</P>
<P>
	Both companies declined to comment on the report.  
</P>
<P>
	Since Diller made his offer for Lycos in February, the company's  
shares plummeted from $127 a share to as low as $73.87 1/2 as many 
investors rejected the prospect of joining with a non-internet 
company like USA Networks. 
</P>
<P>
	Many Lycos shareholders also didn't like the terms of the deal,  
where they would receive a 30 percent stake in the combined company 
and Diller's side would get the rest. 
</P>
<P>
	Lycos' stock rose $15.56 1/4 on Monday to $105.06 1/4 on the Nasdaq  
Stock Market. Shares of USA Networks fell 12 1/2 cents to $35.25, and 
Ticketmaster City-Search's stock rose $2.06 1/4 to $30.56 1/4, also on 
Nasdaq. 

</P>
</TEXT>
