<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Furriers Fight 'Anti-Fur' Coat Tags </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEVERLY HILLS, Calif. (AP) -- Furriers in this well-heeled city  
are optimistic that voters will reject a measure that would require 
merchants to attach tags to coats and stoles explaining how the 
animals died. 
</P>
<P>
	Measure A is the only issue on today's ballot, and many  
customers at Somper Furs are angry over the $60,000 the city is 
spending on the special election, said store manager Douglas Fine. 
</P>
<P>
	The proposal is ``one more attempt by the extreme animal  
activists to generate publicity to hurt the fur industry,'' Fine 
said Monday. 
</P>
<P>
	The credit card-sized tags on fur products costing over $50  
would tell would-be buyers that the pelts came from animals that 
may have been electrocuted, gassed, poisoned, clubbed, stomped, 
drowned or caught in steel-jaw leg traps, or had their necks 
broken. Violators could be fined $100 per item. 
</P>
<P>
	The ordinance would exempt fur makers who use humane methods,  
such as lethal injection administered by a licensed veterinarian. 
</P>
<P>
	Some famous residents including Jack Lemmon, Sid Caesar and  
Larry King are among backers of the initiative. 
</P>
<P>
	The leader of the group which has spent $75,000 to push the  
initiative said Monday the issue is consumer rights, not animal 
rights. 
</P>
<P>
	``The retailers have been caught misleading consumers by telling  
them the animals are put to sleep just like dogs and cats,'' said 
Luke Montgomery, campaign manager of Beverly Hills Consumers for 
Informed Choice. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters sent a videotape to 5,000 voters showing hidden  
camera excerpts of local fur merchants claiming the deaths were 
humane. 
</P>
<P>
	The City Clerk expects a big turnout despite the lack of any  
other matter on the ballot. More than 5,500 of the city's 20,000 
registered voters requested absentee ballots, more than double the 
absentee ballot request for most elections, City Clerk Nina Udy 
said. By Monday, 3,400 absentee votes were returned. 
</P>
<P>
	If fur products can be targeted, how about leather, which begins  
as an animal hide, too, furrier Fine wondered. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's the next step,'' said Rudy Cole, campaign manager for  
the No on A Committee. ``This is the opening gun in the efforts by 
extremist animal rights activists. 
</P>
<P>
	``In many ways, fur harvesting is more regulated and humane than  
processing for food or anything else,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A reluctant City Council voted 3-1 Feb. 2, with one abstention,  
to call the initiative election, having been forced to put the 
measure on the ballot because 3,300 registered voters had signed a 
petition on the matter. Mayor Les Bronte was the lone dissenting 
vote. 
</P>
<P>
	``We don't need a pelt posse here,'' Bronte said at the time.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
