<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Bush Picks Iowa Press Aide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) -- Texas Gov. George W. Bush has picked  
veteran political operative Eric Woolson to head his communications 
operations in Iowa, aides said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's got a good reputation in Iowa,'' said Bush aide Mindy  
Tucker. ``He's dealt with the press and in politics for a long 
time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Woolson was spokesman for former Gov. Terry Branstad, and worked  
as a journalist in the state. 
</P>
<P>
	The move is yet another expansion of Bush's effort in Iowa,  
where precinct caucuses next February launch the presidential 
nominating season. The leader in most of the early polls, Bush has 
yet to visit the state but has won the endorsement of the state's 
GOP delegation in Congress and many in the Republican 
establishment. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush has picked Des Moines lawyer Joe Gunderson to chair his  
Iowa campaign; veteran activist Luke Roth will run it on a 
day-to-day basis. 
</P>
<P>
	Woolson is a familiar figure in the state's political scene.  
He's interspersed a career in journalism with a series of political 
jobs. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a political reporter for the Waterloo Courier before  
becoming a spokesman for Sen. Joe Biden when Biden unsuccessfully 
sought the Democratic presidential nomination in 1988. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
