<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Jamir Miller Signs With Browns </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CLEVELAND (AP) -- Jamir Miller's past doesn't concern the  
Cleveland Browns, who are convinced the outside linebacker can be 
part of their future. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, who led the Arizona Cardinals in tackles last season,  
agreed to terms on a one-year contract with Cleveland on Tuesday. 
The 25-year-old Miller will make $1.3 million this season and could 
earn an additional $900,000 with incentives. 
</P>
<P>
	The team finalized the deal on Tuesday with Miller's agent,  
Leigh Steinberg, who reportedly was angry with the Browns for the 
way they treated another of his clients, quarterback Akili Smith, 
leading up to the NFL draft. 
</P>
<P>
	But Miller also comes to the new Browns with some old baggage --  
a history of off-the-field legal problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller played the last five seasons for Arizona, but turned down  
a two-year deal from the Cardinals in March thinking he could get 
more on the free-agent market. 
</P>
<P>
	But there was little interest, perhaps because the 6-foot-5,  
266-pounder was suspended for four games in 1995 for violating the 
NFL's substance-abuse policy. It was Miller's second strike in the 
league program; a third one would mean a one-year suspension. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller was also accused of pointing a gun at a bouncer in May  
1995, and he was arrested twice while at UCLA -- for possession of 
$13,000 in stolen stereo and computer equipment and unlawful 
possession of a gun. He pleaded no contest to the charges and was 
put on probation. 
</P>
<P>
	``I discussed it with him, and he feels like he's made some  
mistakes in his time,'' Dwight Clark, Cleveland's director of 
football operations told the Akron Beacon Journal. ``He's matured. 
He's got a family now and he thinks he's straightened his life out 
the last four years, and I have no reason to disagree with that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	A 1994 first-round pick out of UCLA -- the 10th overall -- Miller  
led the Cardinals in tackles last season with 150 -- including 87 
solos. He also recorded three sacks and started in all 16 games for 
the third straight year in 1998. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller should immediately move into the starting outside  
linebacking position for the Browns, who are planning to use a base 
4-3 defense in their first year back in the league. 
</P>
<P>
	Miller will likely start alongside Chris Spielman and John  
Thierry, giving the Browns a solid linebacking corps. Lenoy Jones 
had been penciled in as the Browns' starter on the weak side. 
</P>
<P>
	``The addition of Jamir Miller fills a hole at the outside  
linebacking position,'' Clark said. ``He has an outstanding 
combination of speed and size, and his NFL experience will enable 
him to provide leadership in the locker room.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Miller, 25, is the second high-profile player to leave the  
Cardinals for the Browns. Offensive left tackle Lomas Brown joined 
Cleveland earlier this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
