<HEADLINE> AP Top News at 8 p.m. EDT  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NATO Airstrikes Continue  
</P>
<P>
	BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) -- NATO continued its airstrikes on  
Yugoslavia today, saying it does not believe Serb forces are being 
withdrawn from Kosovo. At least seven people were killed in the 
allied attacks, Serb media said. NATO said there was no evidence 
Yugoslavia had withdrawn any of the estimated 40,000 troops and 
special police from the Serbian province. In Washington, Defense 
Secretary William Cohen said NATO will accept nothing less than a 
total withdrawal of forces from Kosovo as part of its conditions to 
halt the air campaign. 

</P>
<P>
	China, Russia Agree NATO Must Stop  
</P>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- A spokesman for the Chinese government said a  
Russian envoy and senior Chinese leaders agreed today that NATO 
must halt its bombing of Yugoslavia as a precondition for resolving 
the Kosovo crisis. The precondition appeared to go beyond a 
proposed solution to the Kosovo crisis that Russia agreed to last 
week. Meanwhile, protests against NATO's accidental bombing of the 
Chinese embassy in Yugoslavia ebbed today, but the U.S. ambassador 
warned that the return to Beijing of the remains of three Chinese 
killed in the attack could touch off more unrest. 

</P>
<P>
	Ex-Welfare Recipients Studied  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Most Americans who have been swept from  
welfare rolls have jobs and earn more than they got from the 
government -- but not enough to escape poverty. That's the picture 
painted by 21 state studies that, after much speculation, provide 
the first glimpse of what has happened to the millions who have 
left welfare amid tough new rules and unprecedented economic 
growth. While homelessness and other worst-case scenarios are rare, 
a substantial number of these families face hardships, such as 
trouble paying for food and utility bills, an Associated Press 
review of the studies shows. 

</P>
<P>
	Chung Testifies Before House Panel  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Weaving a tale of intrigue, fund-raiser Johnny  
Chung testified today he took $300,000 from a Chinese intelligence 
official who wanted to re-elect President Clinton. He alleged he 
later was offered hush money to discourage his cooperation with the 
FBI. But Chung told lawmakers in his first public testimony that he 
never acted as an agent for the Chinese government. Chung became a 
cooperating witness in the federal investigation of campaign fund 
raising after pleading guilty to making illegal contributions to 
Clinton and other Democrats. 

</P>
<P>
	USA Networks To Abandon Lycos Plan  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Media mogul and renowned negotiator Barry Diller  
will officially abandon his plans tomorrow to buy the top-rated 
Internet site Lycos Inc., according to people close to the 
situation. Diller had planned to create a company worth $22 billion 
by combining Lycos with his Home Shopping Network and Ticketmaster 
Online-Citysearch Inc., a ticket agency and online entertainment 
directory. But Diller couldn't win over small day traders who own a 
major stake in Lycos. 

</P>
<P>
	FDA Issues Warning on 'Party Drugs'  
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Americans should avoid more than a half-dozen  
sleep aids and ``party drugs'' sold in health food stores and on 
the Internet because they can send people into comas or even kill, 
the government warned today. The urgent consumer warning is part of 
repeated Food and Drug Administration efforts to remove from the 
market chemicals related to a party drug called GHB that was banned 
in 1991. The FDA warned about products sold under the names 
Revitalize Plus, Serenity, Enliven, GHRE, SomatoPro, NRG3, Thunder 
Nectar and Weight Belt Cleaner. At least three deaths are linked to 
the products 

</P>
<P>
	Star Wars Tickets Available Wed.  
</P>
<P>
	LOS ANGELES (AP) -- For fans, distributor 20th Century Fox and  
theater operators, the start of advance ticket sales for ``Star 
Wars: Episode I -- The Phantom Menace,'' at 3 p.m. EDT tomorrow is 
an event nearly as big as the movie itself. Ticket sellers were 
gearing up for the onslaught by adding staff and equipment. 
MovieFone, the company that sells tickets over the telephone and 
Internet, boosted its Web capacity to enable 10 times more people 
than usual to use the service. ``Phantom Menace'' doesn't actually 
open until May 19. 

</P>
<P>
	Dow Sees Modest Gains  
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 18.90  
at 11,026.15 today. Advancing issues on the New York Stock Exchange 
led decliners 1,717-1,320. The Nasdaq was up 40.27 to 2,566.66. 

</P>
<P>
	Silas Gets 4-Year Deal From Hornets  
</P>
<P>
	CHARLOTTE, N.C. (AP) -- Paul Silas, who moved from a backup role  
to transform the Charlotte Hornets into a winning team, signed a $6 
million contract today to coach the NBA club for the next four 
seasons. Silas was an assistant when coach Dave Cowens resigned in 
March in a salary dispute. Behind Silas, the Hornets put together a 
22-13 record and missed making the NBA playoffs by one game. 

</P>
<P>
	AP NewsBrief by GABRIEL MADWAY  

</P>
