<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Speaker Guilty of Tax Evasion </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) -- A former House speaker and his wife were  
found guilty Tuesday of failing to report hundreds of thousands of 
dollars in income on their tax returns. 
</P>
<P>
	Bolley ``Bo'' Johnson, 47, was convicted on four of five tax  
evasion counts and his wife, Judi, was convicted on three of four 
counts. 
</P>
<P>
	Mrs. Johnson looked stunned and her husband bit his lip as the  
court clerk read the verdicts. Both were taken into custody by 
marshals. The judge said he would consider written motions for 
their release prior to sentencing July 27. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson faces a maximum sentence of 12 years in prison. For Mrs.  
Johnson, 48, faces a maximum 9 years. 
</P>
<P>
	Johnson, a Democrat, served in the Legislature through November  
1994 when his two-year term as speaker ended. He works in Pensacola 
as a real estate broker. His wife is a former state Department of 
Revenue sales tax analyst. 
</P>
<P>
	The prosecution alleged they tried to hide income they received  
for lobbying on behalf of casino gambling, road building, lobbying, 
health care and other businesses. Johnson had strong ties to Gov. 
Lawton Chiles and other powerful officials. 
</P>
<P>
	The couple received $1.6 million in consulting fees from 1992  
through 1996, failing to report $503,861. Defense lawyers argued 
the omissions were unintentional, and therefore, not a crime. 
</P>
</TEXT>
