<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 09:25:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> A Down-Home Musical Couple for NYC </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- As a music producer and bar owner in New York's  
East Village, Eric ``Roscoe'' Ambel has two reasons for being 
inundated with tapes from struggling musicians looking for a big 
break. 
</P>
<P>
	Most are depressingly bad and wind up being tossed aside. So it  
was with some trepidation that he accepted the tape handed to him 
by Mary Lee Kortes. 
</P>
<P>
	They'd been dating for a few months and it was dawning on Ambel  
that he had fallen in love. This was a real complication. What if 
he listened and heard no discernible talent? What would he say 
then? 
</P>
<P>
	What if it were really bad?  
</P>
<P>
	Fortunately, it wasn't. He heard a lovely voice and a talent for  
pop songwriting, the same thing the public can now hear on an album 
by her band, Mary Lee's Corvette. 
</P>
<P>
	It was safe for Ambel to exhale. Even now, approaching the  
eighth anniversary of their wedding, the alternative is too painful 
to consider. 
</P>
<P>
	``That's one of those things where there's no reason to even  
think about it,'' Ambel said, sipping a soda at his bar, the 
Lakeside Lounge, and glancing at his wife. ``And I'm happy about 
that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The two grew up far from New York -- Kortes in Montana, Ambel in  
Illinois. Now they're the quintessential New York City couple, yet 
lately have built their careers on music not necessarily associated 
with the city. 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Lee's Corvette often sounds like it belongs in a Paris  
cafe. It's pure pop music for adults that's given a melancholy air 
by Joe Chiofalo's accordion, the band's most dominant instrument 
after Kortes' voice. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambel is a prominent producer in the alternative country scene,  
after stints as a guitarist with Joan Jett's Blackhearts and New 
York's tough guy rockers of the 1980s, the Del Lords. Missouri's 
Bottle Rockets and North Carolina's Backsliders are two recent 
clients. 
</P>
<P>
	While a team off-stage, Kortes and Ambel have generally followed  
their own musical paths. They both write songs, but haven't written 
together. When Kortes asked him to play guitar in her band, Ambel 
declined. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're married and I take that commitment very seriously,'' he  
said. ``I've been in a lot of bands in my life, and every band I've 
ever been in broke up. I just said, `I will find you a guitar 
player.''' 
</P>
<P>
	Where she used his expertise was in making her record, ``True  
Lovers of Adventure.'' Neither had ever been satisfied with 
recordings of her music before. They had usually reflected the 
taste of the producer, and Kortes' personality never seemed to come 
through as it did in club shows with just a few players. 
</P>
<P>
	She asked Ambel to produce her record and was pleased with the  
result. Put it this way: They're still married. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was the first recorded stuff I had that made people respond  
emotionally,'' she said. ``That was a real godsend. Being in the 
studio with him was wonderful because he just knows when the moment 
is magic. He knows when you got it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ambel -- perhaps with an assist from Ed McMahon -- is responsible  
for the name of Kortes' band. 
</P>
<P>
	Sifting through her mail one day, she came across a sweepstakes  
letter that told her she may have already won $75,000 or a free 
Corvette. The letter had several tiny pictures of a car, and under 
each one it said, ``Mary Lee's Corvette.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Eric saw it and said, `There's your band name.' I still have  
the letter. I didn't send it in,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Some of Kortes' songs will make you smile: ``The Status With  
Gladys'' is about a woman who tries to hide the fact that she's gay 
from an older sister. Many more will bring a tear, or tug at the 
heart, which is where Chiofalo's accordion comes in handy. 
</P>
<P>
	``It sort of intrinsically has that feeling of longing,  
depending on how it's played,'' she said. ``Eric refers to it as 
the red wine style.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Joe is red wine as opposed to red peppers,'' Ambel continued.  
``I think we've all had enough of the red pepper zydeco playing. I 
have. The red wine accordion is a beautiful thing.'' 
</P>
<P>
	While threads of Kortes' life run through her songs, she's quick  
to volunteer that there's nothing autobiographical about ``Why 
Don't You Leave Him,'' a chilling composition about a woman who 
won't leave an abusive man. ``He says he'll kill me,'' the narrator 
sings, ``and I believe him.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Mary Lee's Corvette performed the song this spring at a meeting  
of the Pennsylvania Coalition Against Domestic Violence. The song 
is being used by the Nicole Brown Charitable Foundation to raise 
awareness about domestic violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Ambel has put out a couple of albums with his loosely defined  
band, Roscoe's Gang, but for the past couple of years, he has 
concentrated on producing. Now he's ready to devote his summer to 
writing songs. A CD compilation of the criminally overlooked Del 
Lords is also due soon. 
</P>
<P>
	He is also opening another Lakeside Lounge in Raleigh, N.C. The  
Manhattan bar, named after his parents' summer home in the Midwest, 
is both a comfortable neighborhood hangout and an intimate showcase 
for musicians. The well-stocked jukebox is the star of the place. 
</P>
<P>
	Sometimes a friend at a record company will ask Ambel to set up  
a show for an artist the label is thinking of signing. 
</P>
<P>
	But for all the record companies based in New York, and all of  
the musicians who come to the city seeking fame and fortune, it's 
not always the best place for them to be. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you think about it, there are not that many bands from  
New York,'' he said. ``It's a hard place to break out of. It's 
easier to get an A&AMP;R guy to go to Tucson to see a band, where he 
can go there for three days and play golf, than to get the guy to 
come down to Avenue B.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0218 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 01:31:08 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Veto Threatened on Kosovo Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- House-Senate negotiators hoping to ship  
President Clinton legislation this week paying for the fight with 
Yugoslavia, aid to Central America and other items are facing a new 
veto threat from the White House. But it seems likely that such a 
confrontation will be avoided. 
</P>
<P>
	Lawmakers from the two chambers planned to meet this afternoon  
to begin crafting a compromise, multibillion-dollar package. But 
Monday evening, White House officials threatened for the first time 
to veto it, citing a host of objections. 
</P>
<P>
	Previously, the administration had threatened to veto a  
stand-alone aid measure for Central America and U.S. farmers 
because it would cut domestic programs and add environmental and 
other items the White House opposes. They had also complained about 
-- but not threatened to veto -- a separate bill in which the House 
more than doubled Clinton's $6 billion request for the fight over 
Kosovo. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, however, White House officials warned that the new,  
blended legislation was in danger of being rejected. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a number of very troubling issues ... and the  
president's senior advisors would continue to recommend that he 
veto this legislation unless the objectionable provisions are 
resolved in a satisfactory manner,'' said a letter to House leaders 
from White House budget chief Jacob Lew. 
</P>
<P>
	Asked specifically about the extra House-approved defense funds,  
Lew said in an interview, ``It's important to scale it back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Members of both parties have said privately that they don't  
think Clinton would veto the Kosovo package as long as it is kept 
at roughly the $13 billion range the House approved last week. 
Congressional bargainers seem likely to pare it back even further, 
perhaps to about $10 billion, said participants who spoke on 
condition of anonymity. 
</P>
<P>
	These officials say that with American troops in the field and  
with Clinton himself saying the Pentagon needs more money, he would 
be hard-pressed to reject such a measure. 
</P>
<P>
	The extra money the House added was for U.S. military operations  
and installations around the world, and a pay raise for the troops. 
The most likely item to be dropped is $1 billion the House added to 
modernize U.S. bases overseas, aides say. 
</P>
<P>
	``We really haven't settled anything yet,'' House Appropriations  
Committee Chairman Bill Young, R-Fla., said in an interview. 
</P>
<P>
	On Feb. 16, Clinton requested nearly $1 billion to help Honduras  
and other Central American nations devastated by last autumn's 
deadly Hurricane Mitch. He later asked for $152 million to help 
U.S. farmers hurt by record-low prices for wheat, corn and other 
farm products. 
</P>
<P>
	On March 23, the Senate approved a $2.5 billion bill for Central  
America and farmers, which included aid they had added for the U.S. 
steel, oil, gas and mining industries. The next day, the House 
approved a $1.3 billion version without the Senate add-ons. 
</P>
<P>
	Administration objections include Senate language that would bar  
the federal government from sharing in the $246 billion settlement 
states have won from the tobacco industry, delay increases in 
royalties oil companies pay for using federal lands and postpone 
stricter requirements for hardrock mining on government property. 
</P>
<P>
	The White House also opposes GOP plans to pay for the Central  
America aid with cuts in food stamps, along with money the United 
States uses to back loans by international lending agencies and 
other programs. 
</P>
<P>
	The administration prefers using this year's expected federal  
surplus. Many aides from both parties, however, believe a 
compromise will be reached on spending reductions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0219 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 10:05:09 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Offer Made for Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- An unidentified buyer has come forward with an  
offer of $85 million to buy and move the financially troubled 
Pittsburgh Penguins, an NHL lawyer said today. 
</P>
<P>
	William Daly, the league's vice president for legal affairs,  
would not identify the buyer who emerged during the last two weeks. 
</P>
<P>
	The offer was revealed as a judge in U.S. Bankruptcy Court heard  
the league's request to move up a review of the league's plan to 
break the team up. 
</P>
<P>
	Bankruptcy Judge Bernard Markovitz approved the request and  
scheduled the hearing for May 19, 12 days ahead of the NHL's 
deadline for resolving the Penguins' ownership. 
</P>
<P>
	That is also the day of Game 6 of the Penguins' playoff series  
with Toronto, if it is necessary. The series is tied 1-1. 
</P>
<P>
	The league is using the prospect of losing the team as leverage  
to direct the Penguins toward its preferred buyer, Mario Lemieux, 
whose investment group is offering $50 million in cash. 
</P>
<P>
	Jeffrey Levitan, another NHL lawyer, also said the team could be  
broken up. Levitan said assets including players would be sold 
piecemeal, although that would fetch much less than $85 million. 
</P>
<P>
	The team's largest creditors, banks and insurers, favor a vote  
on the NHL's plan at the same time Lemieux's plan is considered. 
Other creditors oppose that, saying it could be confusing. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins find themselves entangled in a scenario previously  
unseen in major U.S. pro sports, with the franchise's fate being 
played out in bankruptcy court at the same time the team is in the 
NHL playoffs. 
</P>
<P>
	Hockey players are accustomed to regularly changing uniforms,  
cities and addresses, so the possibility they might leave 
Pittsburgh probably is more unnerving to their fans than it is to 
them. 
</P>
<P>
	Perhaps that is why coach Kevin Constantine got testy Monday  
when a TV station producer asked him yet again about the 
difficulties of leading a team that may be out of money before it 
runs out of games to play. 
</P>
<P>
	The Penguins play Game 3 of their conference semifinal series  
against the Toronto Maple Leafs tonight at the Civic Arena. 
</P>
<P>
	``Not to be rude, but I'll say it for the 1,000th time,  
bankruptcy is not an issue,'' Constantine said. ``It shouldn't be, 
it can't be and it isn't. ... It doesn't affect the coaches or 
players. The playoffs are the only thing we're focused on.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That can't be said for all of the Penguins' nervous employees.  
</P>
<P>
	The NHL strongly supports Lemieux's bid, but wants the Penguins'  
situation to be sorted out by June 1, or the franchise likely will 
be disbanded or sold elsewhere. 
</P>
<P>
	Lemieux's bid is expected to get a financial boost when his  
group finalizes an agreement with Internet millionaire Mark Cuban 
to join him. Cuban, who founded the Broadcast.com web site that 
carries pro and college sports, concerts and radio stations on the 
Internet, is a Mount Lebanon, Pa., native who wants to keep the 
Penguins in Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Cuban and his partners recently sold Broadcast.com to Yahoo! for  
$6.1 billion. 
</P>
<P>
	Penguins star Jaromir Jagr can't think of a better scenario: a  
well-funded ownership group led by Lemieux, the team's former star. 
</P>
<P>
	``He loves offense. He loves to have a winning team. He would do  
anything to win a Stanley Cup,'' Jagr said. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, Jagr said he hasn't closely followed the case, and he  
learned the details only upon visiting briefly with Lemieux. 
</P>
<P>
	``I don't worry about that stuff ... it's all about the lawyers  
and I don't understand that stuff,'' Jagr said. ``Mario explained a 
little bit about it, but I have no clue what is going to happen.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Jagr joked that if Lemieux became his boss, he would  
not renegotiate his $48 million contract. Part of the Penguins' 
current financial problems stem from the estimated $26 million in 
deferred salary owed Lemieux. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are two different kinds of owners: owners who are  
businessmen and owners who love the game, and I'd put Mario in that 
second category,'' Jagr said. ``Some of the owners, it's a game, 
but they just don't understand it. 
</P>
<P>
	``It would be a lot better for everybody (if Mario got the  
team),'' he said. ``The fans would start coming more. They don't 
know if the Pens are going to be here or not. Mario Lemieux could 
put the team in the right direction and turn the franchise 
around.'' 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0220 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 12:05:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Garciaparra Speechless After 2 Slams </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- By the time he crossed the plate after his third  
home run of the night -- his second grand slam -- Nomar Garciaparra 
was speechless. 
</P>
<P>
	``It was amazing,'' Garciaparra said. ``I've never hit three  
home runs in a game before -- not in Little League, college, 
nowhere. I'm glad I waited until the big leagues to do it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra became the first American Leaguer in 24 years with  
10 RBIs in one game, and became just the 11th player in major 
league history to hit a pair of grand slams in a game. 
</P>
<P>
	Ted Williams never did it. Neither did Jim Rice nor Mo Vaughn.  
</P>
<P>
	``You just shake your head and tip your cap at what happened,''  
Ken Griffey Jr. said after Garciaparra led the Boston Red Sox over 
the Seattle Mariners 12-4 Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	Former Boston center fielder Fred Lynn had been the last AL  
player with 10 RBIs, accomplishing the feat at Tiger Stadium on 
June 18, 1975. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra, 25, had some pretty impressive accomplishments even  
before Monday night. He was the Red Sox's first pick in the 1994 
amateur draft, he won the 1997 AL Rookie of the Year award after 
leading the league with 209 hits. He put together a rookie record 
30-game hitting streak, and set the major league record for RBIs by 
a leadoff hitter with 85. 
</P>
<P>
	In his second season, the All-Star shortstop became just the  
fifth major leaguer with 30 or more homers in each of his first two 
seasons, following his rookie year total of 30 with 35. Rudy York 
(1936-37), Ron Kittle (1983-84), Jose Canseco (1986-88) and Mark 
McGwire (1987-90) were the others. 
</P>
<P>
	Midway through 1998, the Red Sox inserted Garciaparra into the  
cleanup spot, where he has remained. 
</P>
<P>
	His power was not evident the first month of this season. The  
club lost Vaughn, who batted ahead of him, to Anaheim. Many 
predicted Garciaparra's pitch selection and his power numbers would 
be reduced. 
</P>
<P>
	After missing six games early in the year with a bad hamstring,  
his power game got off to a slow start. He didn't hit his first 
homer until last Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	``I never got down,'' he said. ``I remained positive. I was  
swinging the bat well. It was bad luck here or there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Then he beat up a Mariners' staff that began Tuesday with the  
highest ERA in the major leagues (6.54). Seattle has allowed 50 
homers, the most in the majors. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra's first grand slam came before rookie Brett  
Hinchliffe (0-2) retired a batter. Garciaparra then sliced a 
two-run shot around the right-field foul pole off Hinchliffe in the 
third for a 6-2 lead. 
</P>
<P>
	After fouling out in the fourth and walking in the sixth,  
Garciaparra hit his second slam off Eric Weaver in the eighth. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was seeing the ball well and I threw one right down the  
middle,'' Weaver said. ``You can't do that.'' 
</P>
<P>
	All five of Garciaparra's homers this season have come in the  
last six games. 
</P>
<P>
	``When you're swinging the bat well good things happen,'' he  
said ``It's nice to have a night like this. They don't happen very 
often. I'm just going to enjoy it.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The 10 RBIs tied the Boston record that Lynn shared with Norm  
Zauchin (May 27, 1955) and York (July 27, 1946). 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, he became the first major leaguer to drive in 10  
runs since Mark Whiten had 12 RBIs and four homers for St. Louis on 
Sept. 7, 1993, at Cincinnati. 
</P>
<P>
	Garciaparra became the second player this year to hit two grand  
slams in a game -- the Cardinals' Fernando Tatis hit two in one 
inning on April 23. Never before had two players accomplished the 
feat in the same season. 
</P>
<P>
	Two other Red Sox players had two in a game -- York in that 1946  
game and Jim Tabor on July 4, 1939. Garciaparra became the first 
player ever to do it in Fenway Park. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's pretty amazing,'' winner John Wasdin (1-0) said. ``That's  
the great thing about baseball. Another history-making night in 
Fenway Park. What better place to do it?'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
