<DOCNO> APW19990511.0221 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 16:05:01 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Ex-Welfare Recipients' Work Rates </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	In the last few years, nearly two dozen states have released  
studies tracking people who have left welfare. Some examine state 
wage reports -- filed by employers for all workers -- to see if 
former recipients are working. Others interview a sample of people 
who have left the rolls. 
</P>
<P>
	It is difficult to compare one state to another because of  
differences in methodology and timing. 
</P>
<P>
	This list shows the states that have released studies, followed  
by the month of release in parentheses and data on how many people 
are working. 
</P>
<P>
	Unless otherwise noted, the percentage given represents those  
working at the time of the survey, as a portion of all people 
surveyed. Four states -- Arkansas, Georgia, Maryland and New York -- 
defined ``working'' as earning at least $100 during a three-month 
period. 
</P>
<P>
	------	 
</P>
<P>
	Arkansas (February 1999): 50 percent working in first quarter  
after leaving welfare. Average income $1,979 over three months. 
Portion with earnings above poverty line was 16 percent after three 
months and 27 percent after a year. 
</P>
<P>
	Florida (March 1999): 76.5 percent working. Of them, 59.5  
percent earned between $5.16 per hour and $7.99 per hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Georgia (November 1998): 63 percent working in first quarter  
after leaving; 52 percent of these workers earned more than $2,000 
in the quarter, with 27 percent earning more than $3,000. 
</P>
<P>
	Indiana (September 1997): 64 percent working.  
</P>
<P>
	Iowa (May 1997): 53 percent of people forced off rolls for  
failing to follow rules were working. Average earnings were $170 
per week. 
</P>
<P>
	Kansas (November 1998): 40 percent of families that had not  
returned to welfare said they were getting by financially by 
working. 
</P>
<P>
	Kentucky (January 1998): 49 percent working. Of them, 50 percent  
earning between $5.16 per hour and $7.99 per hour; about half of 
the others earned more and half earned less. 
</P>
<P>
	Maryland (March 1998): 52 percent working in first quarter after  
leaving welfare. Median income was $2,039 over three months of 
those who were working. 
</P>
<P>
	Massachusetts (April 1999): 71 percent of those who did not  
return to welfare were working; among full-time workers, average 
earnings were $1,399 per month. 
</P>
<P>
	Michigan (May 1997): 45 percent said they were meeting daily  
needs through employment. 
</P>
<P>
	Mississippi (January 1999): 27 percent of people in rural areas  
working, 46 percent in urban areas. Average wages were $5.77 per 
hour, and the average worker worked 35 hours per week. 
</P>
<P>
	New Jersey (July 1998): 19 percent of those removed from welfare  
due to failure to meet requirements said they supported their 
families by finding a job. 
</P>
<P>
	New Mexico (September 1997): 56 percent working; average wage  
was $6.66 per hour, with an average of 34 hours worked. 
</P>
<P>
	New York (March 1998): 39.7 percent working in September 1996;  
36.6 in December 1996; 29.1 percent in March 1997. 
</P>
<P>
	Oklahoma (September 1998): 25 percent working full-time, 25  
percent working part-time. Average wage of $6.51 per hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Pennsylvania (March 1998): 53 percent working; of them, 59  
percent earn more than $6.50 per hour. 
</P>
<P>
	South Carolina (October 1998): 62 percent working. Average wage,  
$6.45 per hour; average of 36.4 hours per week. 
</P>
<P>
	Tennessee (March 1998): 48 percent working full time; 25 percent  
working part time. Average wage, $5.67 per hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Texas (December 1998): 50 percent working. Average wage of $6.15  
per hour; average of 34.7 hours per week. 
</P>
<P>
	Washington (January 1999): 71 percent of those who had not  
returned to welfare working. Median wage of $7.22 per hour. 
</P>
<P>
	Wisconsin (January 1999): 62 percent working; median wage of $7  
per hour. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
