<DOCNO> APW19990511.0223 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 20:13:37 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Obituaries in the News  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
                          *Vern Countryman    	
</P>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Vern Countryman, a retired professor at  
Harvard Law School who was a specialist on commercial and 
bankruptcy law, died May 2 of heart failure. He was 81. 
</P>
<P>
	He worked at the National Labor Relations Board in Seattle  
before becoming a clerk for Supreme Court Justice William O. 
Douglas in 1942 and 1943. Countryman remained close friends with 
the justice over the years, and wrote three books about him. 
</P>
<P>
	He was a dean of the University of New Mexico School of Law  
before joining the faculty at Harvard Law in 1964. 
</P>
<P>
	Countryman co-authored the texts ``The Lawyer in Modern  
Society,'' ``Commercial Law,'' and ``Debtors' and Creditors' 
Rights.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He was a founding trustee of the National Consumer Law Center,  
which presents the annual Vern Countryman Award to recognize 
attorneys who have contributed significantly to the rights and 
welfare of low-income consumers. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Edwin L. Dale Jr.    	
</P>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Edwin L. Dale Jr., a former New York Times  
reporter and spokesman for the White House Office of Management and 
Budget, died Monday of cancer. He was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale served as assistant director of public affairs at OMB  
between 1981 and 1987 during the Reagan administration. 
</P>
<P>
	He then spent two years as a counselor to Commerce Secretary C.  
William Verity before returning to the budget office as a director 
of external affairs. He worked in the area of policy studies before 
retiring in 1992. 
</P>
<P>
	Known for his mastery of the federal budget, Dale took as many  
as 110 calls in a day during the height of budget season. 
</P>
<P>
	Dale came to Washington in 1951 as a reporter for the New York  
Herald Tribune. Four years later, he began covering economics for 
the Times. He spent several years in Paris, and later returned to 
Washington with assignments at the White House and the State 
Department. In 1977, Dale went to work on Capitol Hill. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the author of ``Conservatives in Power'' in 1960 and was  
the primary author of ``The People's Budget,'' published in 1995. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, Meredith, and two stepchildren.  

</P>
<P>
                            *Joe Flowers    	
</P>
<P>
	PENSACOLA, Fla. (AP) -- Joe Flowers, a former Escambia County  
comptroller who lost millions of taxpayer dollars by investing in 
risky securities, died Monday at age 79. 
</P>
<P>
	He had a reputation as the watchdog of public finances for  
almost 40 years, but it was shattered in 1994 when Escambia County 
lost nearly $15 million as the value of its investments in 
derivatives dropped dramatically. 
</P>
<P>
	Four Texas securities brokers subsequently were convicted of  
conspiracy, racketeering and fraud for duping Flowers into 
purchasing the securities. 
</P>
<P>
	Many other public and private investors also lost millions on  
derivatives, whose value is based on -- or derived from -- an 
underlying asset such as a commodity or swings in interest rates. 
</P>
<P>
	The largest municipal bankruptcy in U.S. history, the December  
1994 collapse of Orange County, Calif.'s investments, also was tied 
to bad bets on derivatives. 
</P>
<P>
	Flowers resigned in 1995 and the Legislature abolished his  
position, which had been made an elected one in 1972. He also was 
indicted on lesser charges of mishandling public money and pleaded 
no contest. He was ordered to pay $1,600 in court costs. 

</P>
<P>
                        *Charles K. McWhorter    	
</P>
<P>
	BOSTON (AP) -- Charles K. McWhorter, who served under Vice  
President Richard M. Nixon and remained active in Republican 
politics throughout his life, died Monday from injuries sustained 
in a May 1 car accident. He was 77. 
</P>
<P>
	After working for Nixon's legislative assistant from 1957 to  
1961, McWhorter served as an attorney for AT&AMP;T until his retirement 
in 1987. 
</P>
<P>
	He involved himself in GOP affairs throughout his career, and  
after retirement he worked as a consultant who frequently did 
business in Washington. 

</P>
<P>
                         *Gilbert Millstein    	
</P>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Gilbert Millstein, who brought attention to Jack  
Kerouac with a favorable review of the Beat Generation writer's 
novel ``On the Road,'' died Friday of kidney failure. He was 83. 
</P>
<P>
	Millstein's 1957 New York Times review of ``On the Road''  
described the novel as a beautifully executed work of art and 
helped propel Kerouac into the public consciousness. 
</P>
<P>
	Millstein wrote book reviews and articles for the Times from  
1949 to 1963. He also wrote for The Saturday Evening Post. 
</P>
<P>
	He was the news editor of the ``NBC Nightly News'' from the  
mid-1970s to the mid-1980s. 

</P>
<P>
                            *James Nance    	
</P>
<P>
	MONROE, N.C. (AP) -- James ``Bud'' Nance, a retired Navy admiral  
who became one of the most trusted foreign policy advisers of 
boyhood friend U.S. Sen. Jesse Helms, died Tuesday at age 77. 
</P>
<P>
	Nance served as the chief of staff on the Senate Foreign  
Relations Committee, of which Helms is chairman. Nance also worked 
for Henry Kissinger under President Nixon when Kissinger was 
national security adviser. He was a former White House aide to 
President Ronald Reagan for national security affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	After military retirement, Nance served as a consultant on the  
foreign relations committee during SALT II deliberations and was 
Reagan's deputy assistant for National Security Affairs. In 1983, 
he advised the Navy on aviation issues for the Boeing Co. 
</P>
<P>
	Helms pulled Nance out of retirement in 1991 to work for him on  
Capitol Hill and later became the committee's chief of staff. 

</P>
<P>
                         *William E. Porter    	
</P>
<P>
	ANN ARBOR, Mich. (AP) -- William E. Porter, professor emeritus of  
journalism at the University of Michigan, died April 21 at age 80. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter taught courses in mass media writing, the foreign press,  
and media and politics at Michigan starting in 1962. He also served 
as chair of the journalism department from 1966 to 1973 and later 
chaired the communication department in the 1980s. He retired in 
1989. 
</P>
<P>
	Porter also taught at the University of Iowa for 18 years and  
worked as a freelance writer for magazines such as The Saturday 
Evening Post, Collier's, Cosmopolitan and Better Homes &AMP; Gardens. 
He also wrote the 1955 novel ``The Lawbringers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In 1976, he wrote the book ``Assault on the Media: The Nixon  
Years,'' and earlier co-authored ``The Rest of the Elephant: 
Perspectives on the Mass Media.'' 
</P>
<P>
	He is survived by wife, Lois; a son, a daughter and six  
grandchildren. 

</P>
<P>
                            *Harry Sayen    	
</P>
<P>
	PRINCETON, N.J. (AP) -- Harry Sayen, a businessman and columnist  
for the Times of Trenton, died Monday at age 77. 
</P>
<P>
	He served as chairman of the Mercer County Republican Party from  
1970 to 1975 before making an unsuccessful bid to become Mercer's 
first elected county executive. 
</P>
<P>
	Sayen joined his family business, Mercer Rubber Co., in 1949. He  
rose through the ranks to become president in 1979 before selling 
the company in 1981. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, Isabelle Burns Guthrie; and four  
sons. 

</P>
<P>
                          *Robert H. Werley    	
</P>
<P>
	YUMA, Ariz. (AP) -- Robert H. ``Bob'' Werley, who spent 46 years  
as a reporter and editor for The Yuma Daily Sun, died Monday. He 
was 75. 
</P>
<P>
	Werley worked at a weekly newspaper in Miami, Ariz., before  
joining the Daily Sun in 1951 as sports editor. He became news 
editor two years later and was promoted to managing editor in 1958. 
</P>
<P>
	Werley was named associate editor in 1980. He retired in 1997  
but wrote a weekly Saturday column, ``Recollections of Yuma,'' 
until his death. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Werley's supervision, the Daily Sun became the first  
newspaper in Arizona to go to offset printing and the first to 
switch to video display terminals in the mid-1970s. 
</P>
<P>
	Werley was a past president of the Arizona Associated Press  
Managing Editors and the Arizona Press Club. 
</P>
<P>
	Survivors include his wife, Lenora; three sons and three  
grandchildren. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0224 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 08:45:14 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> EU Energy Unions Expect Job Losses </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) -- Labor unions representing energy  
industry workers in the European Union said Tuesday that 25 percent 
of jobs in the EU electricity and gas sector could be lost in the 
next four years as plans to break up state monopolies are 
implemented. 
</P>
<P>
	``Already 250,000 jobs have been lost due to restructuring,''  
said Carola Fischbach-Pyttel, General Secretary of the European 
Federation of Public Service Unions, or EPSU. 
</P>
<P>
	Fischbach-Pyttel made these comments in a statement released  
ahead of a demonstration of energy workers outside a meeting of 
energy ministers from the 15 EU nations. Hundreds of protesters 
demanded measures to compensate workers who lose out because of the 
break up of national gas and electricity monopolies. 
</P>
<P>
	EU rules call for the gradual opening of the electricity and gas  
markets to private competition. 
</P>
<P>
	EU energy spokesman Costas Verros said that the European  
Commission will present a general study on the job losses in the 
energy and gas sector in the next six months. 
</P>
<P>
	EPSU Unions represents 10 million workers providing services to  
local, regional and central governments and utilities in energy, 
water and waste. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0225 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 05:06:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mourning Gets Help Against Knicks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MIAMI (AP) -- Alonzo Mourning turned in another strong  
performance against the New York Knicks, and this time he had some 
help. 
</P>
<P>
	Mourning scored 26 points Monday night and anchored the Miami  
Heat's defense, as usual, leading them past the New York Knicks 
83-73 in Game 2 of the best-of-5 series. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's the MVP of the league,'' Knicks counterpart Patrick Ewing  
said. ``If he doesn't get it, there's something wrong with you all 
who vote.'' 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 1, a 20-point Heat loss, Mourning was a one-man show.  
But in Game 2, he enjoyed plenty of support from guards Tim 
Hardaway, Dan Majerle and Terry Porter. 
</P>
<P>
	Hardaway had another poor shooting game, going just 1-for-5 and  
scoring 11 points, but he dished out 11 assists. Majerle made two 
3-pointers, his first baskets of the series, to hold New York at 
bay in the final quarter. And Porter had 11 points and six rebounds 
off the bench. 
</P>
<P>
	``Those guys stepped up and made a difference in the game,''  
Mourning said. ``They made plays for everybody. It's about 
penetrating and knocking shots down, and those three are the 
MVPs.'' 
</P>
<P>
	On Saturday, when Mourning had 27 points, the rest of the Heat's  
starting lineup shot 24 percent. 
</P>
<P>
	``The other night, there was only one guy that showed up for  
us,'' forward P.J. Brown said. ``That was Zo, and everybody knows 
it. There was no way we could win this playoff series if only one 
guy is showing up to play.'' 
</P>
<P>
	But the Heat also know they need Mourning to lead the way, which  
he did Monday by making 10 of 16 shots, grabbing eight rebounds and 
blocking four shots in 46 minutes. 
</P>
<P>
	``He was very active,'' Heat coach Pat Riley said. ``He played  
great the other night, and he played great tonight. He's so 
physical, and he's so needed by us out there. 
</P>
<P>
	``His presence in the middle can change a lot of things.  
Anything that was coming to the basket, he was changing. He 
definitely gave us the game we needed to win.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Ewing had 16 points and 15 rebounds but struggled to stop  
Mourning. The former Georgetown alums were matched up more 
frequently than in Game 1. 
</P>
<P>
	``Patrick and I have had some battles,'' Mourning said. ``But  
it's a 5-on-5 competition. It's not a boxing match.'' 
</P>
<P>
	And in 5-on-5, the Heat had the edge Monday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 05:06:05 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  Mourning Gets Help Against Knicks </HEADLINE>
