<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 05:16:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE>  NHL Playoffs Roundup </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- Once Pavol Demitra became accustomed to the  
playoff grind, his game took off again. 
</P>
<P>
	Demitra, the St. Louis Blues' leading scorer in the regular  
season, continued a postseason surge when he beat Ed Belfour in 
overtime for a 3-2 victory over the Dallas Stars on Monday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``I scored almost 90 points and all of a sudden, I'm  
struggling,'' Demitra said. ``But I'm back.'' 
</P>
<P>
	So are the Blues, who cut their series deficit against the NHL  
regular-season champions to 2-1 heading into Game 4 Wednesday night 
in St. Louis. 
</P>
<P>
	``I can't wait,'' Demitra said. ``I'm so excited, I wish we can  
play right away. I'm just so pumped up.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The other Western Conference series continues tonight with  
Detroit playing host Colorado and holding a 2-0 lead. In the East, 
Toronto visits Pittsburgh tonight, and Boston is at Buffalo on 
Wednesday night. Both of those series are tied 1-1. 
</P>
<P>
	Demitra, who was 10th in the NHL with 89 points, has three goals  
and an assist in the last two games since making the adjustment to 
the tighter checking and close quarters of playoff competition. 
That represents half of his postseason output; before Monday, he 
was a team-worst minus-4. 
</P>
<P>
	In Game 3, he was plus-2 and also scored his first points in a  
Blues' playoff victory. 
</P>
<P>
	``He's worked harder in determination to come up with loose  
pucks and taking it to the net more,'' coach Joel Quenneville said. 
``And he's getting in place in the high-traffic areas.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Demitra got to just such an area, outside the crease at the  
right side of the net, when he scored the winner at 2:43 of 
overtime off a feed from Geoff Courtnall. 
</P>
<P>
	``Every time I'm on the ice with him, I feel I can score,''  
Demitra said. ``He fed me last year all the time.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues' third goal also was a Demitra production. After  
avoiding a check from Richard Matvichuk, Demitra slipped the puck 
to rookie Jochen Hecht, who slid in a backhander for a 2-1 lead at 
4:52 of the third. 
</P>
<P>
	Hecht and Mike Eastwood, who also scored for the Blues, were  
unlikely offensive sources. Hecht had a team-leading 56 points with 
the Worcester Icecats of the AHL, but wasn't summoned until 
Saturday after they were eliminated from the playoffs. Eastwood, a 
faceoff specialist, has seven goals in 62 career playoff games and 
two points in 10 playoff games this season. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are a lot of unsung heroes in the playoffs and we're  
getting that right now,'' Blues right wing Scott Young said. 
``That's why we've been successful.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars, the NHL regular-season champions with a  
franchise-record 114 points, missed a chance to put the Blues in a 
huge hole. Only two teams have recovered from a 3-0 series deficit, 
the last the New York Islanders in 1975 against Pittsburgh. 
</P>
<P>
	Dallas' team-record six-game playoff winning streak also came to  
an end. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're not going to go 16-0,'' defenseman Derian Hatcher said.  
``You expect to lose a game here or there.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Brett Hull scored in his first postseason game in St. Louis  
since leaving the Blues after a decade of stardom last summer, and 
Darryl Sydor added his first of the playoffs for Dallas. A crowd of 
19,268, the Blues' first sellout of the playoffs, booed when Hull's 
name was announced. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues largely silenced Joe Nieuwendyk, who had an assist and  
only one shot. Nieuwendyk had two goals and an assist, including 
the game-winner in overtime, in Game 2. 
</P>
<P>
	The Stars may be without center Jere Lehtinen in Game 4.  
Lehtinen injured his right knee in the second period and is listed 
as day-to-day. 
</P>
<P>
	Sydor forced the overtime with his first goal of the playoffs at  
9:08 of the third. Grant Fuhr got a glove on Pat Verbeek's drive 
from the slot, and Grant Marshall got his stick on the rebound 
before Sydor tapped it in. 
</P>
<P>
	A four-minute high-sticking penalty on Blues captain Chris  
Pronger, who caught Hatcher in the face, helped the Stars get off 
to a fast start. Hull scored his second goal of the playoffs, and 
only Dallas' third in 33 power-play opportunities, with a shot from 
the left circle at 3:07. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues got off only three shots in the first period, but tied  
it on a fluky goal at 2:58 of the second. Ricard Persson flipped 
the puck end-over-end toward the net and it deflected off 
Eastwood's glove and Sergei Zubov's stick before eluding Belfour. 
</P>
<P>
	The Blues outshot the Stars 24-18 in regulation and took the  
only four shots in overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	``We didn't shoot enough,'' Stars forward Jamie Langenbrunner  
said. ``Instead of putting it on net, we passed.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
