<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Blues Getting Used To Overtime Duty / Hockey Game Story  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	ST. LOUIS (AP) -- The St. Louis Blues know all about extra effort  
in the playoffs, considering half of their games have gone into 
overtime. 
</P>
<P>
	After cutting the Dallas Stars' second-round series lead to 2-1  
on Pavol Demitra's goal at 2:43 of the extra period in Game 3 
Monday night, the Blues are getting used to life on the high wire. 
</P>
<P>
	``You're on pins and needles the whole time you're out there,''  
said center Craig Conroy, whose team will try to even the series 
Wednesday night. ``Emotionally, it's a big swing. You go from the 
other night in Dallas where your heart just feels like it drops, 
and then last night there's the joy of winning. 
</P>
<P>
	Demitra's game-winner handed the Stars their first loss in seven  
playoff games. 
</P>
<P>
	But it hasn't all been roses for the Blues in OT. Shane Doan  
gave the Phoenix Coyotes the victory in Game 2 of the first round 
and Dallas' Joe Nieuwendyk ended Game 2 of this series. 
</P>
<P>
	After Nieuwendyk's second overtime goal of the playoffs, the  
Stars appeared unbeatable. The regular-season champions, who had 27 
more points than the Blues in the regular season, entered Game 3 
with a six-game playoff winning streak. 
</P>
<P>
	A victory would have given Dallas a virtually insurmountable  
lead. Only two teams have rallied from a 3-0 series deficit in NHL 
history, with the 1975 New York Islanders the last to do it. 
</P>
<P>
	``This was a pivotal game,'' Stars center Mike Modano said. ``We  
could have taken a stranglehold on the series, but we let them get 
right back in it. It's a disappointing game for a lot of guys.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Not that they're overly discouraged heading into Game 4.  
</P>
<P>
	``You never expect to sweep a team,'' goalie Ed Belfour said.  
``The key will be how we bounce back the next game. We expect them 
to come out strong.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Coach Ken Hitchcock said the major difference in the 114-point  
Stars and 87-point Blues is St. Louis had to use five goaltenders 
due to injuries and Dallas went wire to wire with Belfour. Both 
teams play a defensive, territorial game. 
</P>
<P>
	``We anticipate there's going to be more overtime games,''  
Hitchcock said. ``It's going to get closer, not further away. If it 
goes seven, as long as we win, I don't care.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The overtimes haven't seemed to make a cumulative effect on the  
Blues. The only concessions the team made Tuesday was giving 
36-year-old goalie Grant Fuhr and iron man defenders Chris Pronger 
and Al MacInnis a day off. 
</P>
<P>
	Pronger and MacInnis rank first and second in playoff minutes,  
each at about 36 minutes per game. 
</P>
<P>
	``As a forward, you play 15 or 20 minutes, so it hasn't been too  
bad yet,'' Conroy said. ``I don't know about Pronger and Al, 
though. They might be a little more tired.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The excitement of the playoffs, no doubt, is enough to wash away  
the fatigue. 
</P>
<P>
	``I'm exhausted right now,'' Blues wing Scott Young said after a  
half-hour skate Tuesday, ``but tomorrow I'll be fine. Overtimes are 
fun. They're so exciting to play, and as you play more and more of 
them you're not as nervous going into them.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Hitchcock expects Jere Lehtinen, the Selke Trophy winner last  
season as the NHL's top defensive forward, to return from an 
injured right knee in Game 4. Lehtinen left in the second period of 
Game 3. 
</P>
<P>
	Defenseman Shawn Chambers and center Guy Carbonneau also might  
return to the lineup from knee injuries. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
