<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 08:05:23 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> INS Reassessing Detention Plan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- The U.S. Immigration and Naturalization Service  
is taking another look at a plan to relocate detainees on the basis 
of nationality. 
</P>
<P>
	The ``hubbing'' proposal will not be put into effect for illegal  
immigrants awaiting deportation hearings without input from 
advocacy groups, said Brian Perryman, the INS district director in 
Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Perryman met Monday with officials from the Illinois Coalition  
for Immigrants and Refugee Rights, the Midwest Immigrants Rights 
Center and several other groups. 
</P>
<P>
	INS officials had said the plan was open to revision, but  
officials wanted to begin implementation by early summer. They said 
Monday there was no timetable. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think the INS realized that they came up with a plan and  
then went to the community. Maybe it should have been the other way 
around,'' said INS spokeswoman Gail Montenegro. 
</P>
<P>
	``In doing that we made a mistake,'' Perryman added.  
</P>
<P>
	The INS has already erased the term ``hubbing,'' a reference to  
the grouping of immigrants by nationality at detention hubs. 
</P>
<P>
	``It really doesn't matter what words we use, but what plan we  
use. And Mr. Perryman agreed with that,'' said Rep. Luis Gutierrez, 
D-Ill., who was at Monday's meeting. 
</P>
<P>
	``The most important words are, we're back to square one. We're  
going to get community input on a plan, and the community input 
should help us reach our goals,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	The plan would encompass 18 states in the agency's central  
region. Detained illegal Mexican, Central American and Caribbean 
immigrants would be moved to separate facilities in Texas. All 
other immigrants in question -- those from Europe, Asia and Africa -- 
would be shipped to Chicago. 
</P>
<P>
	Currently, illegal immigrants are processed at the nearest INS  
facility. The INS says it is under pressure to quickly move 
immigrants out of detention and slash its backlog of cases and 
notes that many detainees are convicted criminals who already have 
their deportation orders. 
</P>
<P>
	Both sides agree on the main goals of any proposal: better  
access to legal representation, consular officials, family members 
and other support services; reduced time of detention; and the 
expedited deportation of criminal aliens. 
</P>
<P>
	But critics argued that what the INS proposed in the name of  
cost efficiency was essentially a plan to make it easier to deport 
all detained immigrants -- the convicted criminals as well as those 
with a legitimate claim to citizenship. 
</P>
<P>
	``There are things we feel are unfair about the system, and  
we're going to continue to advocate strongly for those people that 
we think are being treated unfairly,'' Gutierrez said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
