<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> In Funds, Know That You Don't Know </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- One of the first rules for success in mutual  
fund investing is to know what you don't know. 
</P>
<P>
	If you are like most people not endowed with the ability to see  
the future, you don't know what stock prices or interest rates are 
going to do next week, next month or next year. 
</P>
<P>
	But you don't have to be discouraged by this realization.  
Indeed, amid this lack of knowledge, you possess a valuable piece 
of information that many people fail to capitalize on: You know 
that you're in the dark. 
</P>
<P>
	So you won't lead yourself astray by guessing, or pretending to  
possess knowledge you don't have. For instance, you will be less 
inclined to jump in and out of the market constantly if you don't 
put much credence in any prediction, yours or somebody else's, 
about what's likely to happen next. 
</P>
<P>
	Instead of helter-skelter market timing, an ``I-don't-know''  
portfolio is likely to rely heavily on diversification, which is 
usually the best protection available against the uncertainties 
posed by the future. 
</P>
<P>
	You will probably put some of your money into stocks or stock  
funds, just in case the stock market keeps prospering. You will 
also probably keep some money out of stocks, socking it away in 
bond funds or money market funds, just in case the stock market 
doesn't keep prospering. 
</P>
<P>
	Quite possibly, you will divide that non-stock money between  
bond funds and money funds, keeping you in a balanced position 
whether interest rates rise, fall, or stay the same. 
</P>
<P>
	Most modern fund managers have long since joined the ``don't  
know'' club. When they are asked for a market forecast, they 
decline to give one, saying they prefer to focus on things that can 
be analyzed, such as the business prospects of individual 
companies. 
</P>
<P>
	That's a big change from 10 or 20 years ago, when money managers  
who were asked about the future of the Dow Jones industrial average 
were expected to come up with an answer that sounded good. Today's 
managers are more sophisticated than that -- and so are many of 
their shareholder-clients. 
</P>
<P>
	All that having been said, it still can be entertaining and  
informative to watch investment professionals trying to peer into 
the future. Consider how several fund-family executives responded 
at a recent symposium when challenged for ``fearless forecasts'' by 
panel moderator Myron Kandel, the longtime financial editor at CNN 
Business News: 
</P>
<P>
	Brian Storms, president of Mitchell Hutchins Asset Management,  
predicted that fund industry assets, which recently surpassed $5 
trillion, will reach $10 trillion or more in the next five years or 
so. ``The next 10 years, or possibly 15 years, will be years of 
rapid growth,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	By contrast, Jeffrey Shames, chairman of MFS Investment  
Management in Boston, said he saw signs that the growth of funds 
had leveled off. ``This has become a mature industry,'' he said, 
and predicted that it would have to contend with a bear market some 
time in the next five years. 
</P>
<P>
	Charles Johnson, president of Franklin Resources Inc., which  
manages the Franklin, Templeton and Mutual Shares fund groups, 
focused on the frustrations fund managers have felt in recent years 
trying to outperform index funds patterned on the Standard &AMP; Poor's 
500-stock composite. 
</P>
<P>
	``I predict over the next 10 years that active managers will  
outperform the S&AMP;P index substantially,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	In the course of the panel discussion, sponsored by the Forum  
For Investor Advice, a trade group for funds sold through brokers 
and other advisers, Johnson also voiced concern about investors' 
high expectations. 
</P>
<P>
	``We're in a raging bull market,'' he said. ``We hope the  
expectations that the customer has are realistic.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That comment pointed up the beauty of a ``don't-know'' approach  
to fund investing. If you know that what has happened in the recent 
past provides no guarantee of what is going to happen in the 
future, you're less likely to be surprised or disappointed by 
whatever events do occur. 
</P>
<P>
	Or, to put it another way, tempering your expectations by  
remembering that you don't know the future helps protect you from 
getting caught off guard. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
