<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Illegal Weapons Bought at Gun Show </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- State Justice Department agents found  
illegal weapons so easy to buy at a Los Angeles County gun show 
that they ran out of money after checking a handful of booths. 
</P>
<P>
	``They were readily available, all sorts of illegal weapons,''  
Attorney General Bill Lockyer said Tuesday, describing the 
undercover operation at the Great Western Gun Show in Pomona two 
weekends ago. 
</P>
<P>
	Gun shows have come under increased scrutiny since authorities  
revealed that weapons used in the Colorado high school massacre 
were purchased at shows, which are under less regulation that gun 
stores. 
</P>
<P>
	Although the laws regarding gun show sales are stricter in  
California, agents said there was still plenty of people selling 
banned weapons, and also selling legal weapons improperly. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockyer displayed nonfunctioning replicas of what the agents  
bought, including modified assault weapons and even a rocket 
launcher, at a news conference. Investigators also found 
flame-throwers and kits to convert legal guns into illegal 
automatic weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	Agents ran out of the $4,000 allocated for their operation so  
quickly that they could check only a fraction of the 5,300 booths 
at the gun show, which is billed as largest in the West. 
</P>
<P>
	Lockyer said charges will be filed this week against those who  
sold the weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	In addition, agents said they witnessed the selling of handguns  
to people who were not asked to wait 10 days for a background 
check, as required by state law. 
</P>
<P>
	``No one asked for any background checks, waiting periods, no  
paperwork,'' Lockyer said. 
</P>
<P>
	Chad Seger, operations manager of the gun show, said he had ``a  
lot of questions'' about Lockyer's allegations, including whether 
weapons were purchased from people with booths at the show, or from 
other customers. 
</P>
<P>
	``We had tons of security, including Pomona police, fairgrounds  
police, and our own security people, who are weapons experts,'' 
working to enforce the law, Seger said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
