<CATEGORY> washington </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Fasteners Bill Passes House </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Manufacturers of industrial fasteners would be  
required to state the strength and characteristics of their 
products, and would face criminal prosecution for lying about them, 
under legislation the House passed Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Supporters said the bill would lighten the regulatory burden on  
smaller businesses imposed by the 1990 Fastener Quality Act. That 
law, enacted to keep foreign manufacturers from dumping substandard 
fasteners in the U.S. market, required that all threaded, metallic, 
through-hardened fasteners of at least one-quarter-inch diameter be 
tested or documented by a laboratory certified by the National 
Institute of Standards &AMP; Technology. 
</P>
<P>
	Under Tuesday's bill, fasteners manufactured in accordance with  
accepted quality assurance systems would be deemed in compliance 
with the law. It also would require manufacturers to mark virtually 
all fasteners with registered trademarks. 
</P>
<P>
	To reduce paperwork, the bill would allow them to submit  
documents in electronic form. 
</P>
<P>
	Enforcement of the 1990 bill was delayed until June 1999 because  
of the requirement's impact on the economy, Rep. James 
Sensenbrenner, R-Wis., said during debate from the House floor. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Fastener Quality Act in its current form is unworkable,''  
Sensenbrenner said. Rep. Gil Gutknecht, R-Minn., characterized the 
law as ``a $20 solution to a $5 problem.'' 
</P>
<P>
	 *------	 
</P>
<P>
	The bill is H.R. 1183.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
