<CATEGORY> international </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> North Korea's Famine May Be Easing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	BEIJING (AP) -- The worst of North Korea's famine may have passed  
and large-scale starvation will probably be averted this year, a 
U.N. official said Tuesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Tun Myat, director of resources for the U.N.'s World Food  
Program, and WFP donors who visited North Korea in early May 
believe 1997 was the worst year in the four-year famine, although 
they found no evidence that the cycle of famine and aid dependence 
will end soon. 
</P>
<P>
	Food aid is, however, getting to those who need it, and North  
Koreans are now producing ``alternative foods'' -- typically meal 
made from ground husks, stalks and wild plants -- on a large scale, 
said Tun Myat. 
</P>
<P>
	Although such diets provide little nutrition and may lead to  
intestinal problems, they help prevent large-scale starvation, Tun 
Myat said. 
</P>
<P>
	Two years ago, '' `A famine in slow motion' was how I depicted  
the situation. I have no reason to change that other than to say 
maybe that the slow is getting even slower,'' Tun Myat said. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korea's food stocks ran out early last month, and May and  
June will be ``hungry months,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	WFP is distributing 200,000 tons of wheat in those months to  
children under 12, hospitals, nursing mothers and 1.65 million 
persons participating in food-for-work programs. 
</P>
<P>
	Four years of food shortages have forced the highly secretive  
communist country to open up slightly. North Korea released to aid 
officials figures showing that 220,000 people died of famine 
between 1995 and 1998, Tun Myat said. 
</P>
<P>
	The organization is still checking the accuracy of North Korea's  
estimates. U.S. and South Korean estimates put the number at 2 
million to 3 million. 
</P>
<P>
	But even the release of the figures is ``highly significant,''  
Tun Myat said. North Korea used to refuse comment entirely on 
famine dead. 
</P>
<P>
	Donors are also being taken to parts of the country that were  
once off-limits to foreigners and allowed to visit farms and meet 
with families, he said. 
</P>
<P>
	North Korean officials have stopped insisting that the famine  
was caused solely by natural disasters, admitting to the delegation 
that it resulted partly from the loss of foreign trade in the early 
1990s after the former Soviet Union collapsed, Tun Myat said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
