<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 12:05:16 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> entertainment </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Morning Show Stunts Suffer Setbacks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	NEW YORK (AP) -- Hitting the road is a time-honored ratings stunt  
for morning news shows. But this week, the road is hitting back. 
</P>
<P>
	After enduring an uncomfortable night on the side of Mount  
Everest, Matt Lauer of NBC's ``Today'' show was prevented Tuesday 
from traveling to a second mystery location when the Indian 
government grounded his chartered plane. 
</P>
<P>
	Hostile weather in this country forced Charles Gibson, Diane  
Sawyer and the crew of ABC's ``Good Morning America'' to travel 10 
hours by bus from Austin, Texas, to New Orleans in time for 
Tuesday's show -- and another downpour. 
</P>
<P>
	Both shows are traveling to drum up interest during a ratings  
``sweeps'' month. For the second straight year, NBC's ``Where in 
the world is Matt Lauer'' promotion sends the anchorman on a 
week-long mystery tour to destinations unknown to viewers. 
</P>
<P>
	He made it to the slopes of the world's tallest mountain Monday,  
but it's been all downhill since. 
</P>
<P>
	Fog obscured views of the peak and prevented Lauer from leaving  
after Monday's show. He was stuck in a shack with his wife, model 
Annette Roque Lauer, eating ravioli and crackers, and sleeping in 
sleeping bags. There was no running water, only an outhouse 
accessible after a jog in the freezing cold. 
</P>
<P>
	The fog finally lifted enough for Lauer to get off the mountain  
and fly to Katmandu, Nepal. But he waited on a runway there for 
more than six hours when officials refused permission to fly over 
Indian airspace. 
</P>
<P>
	By the time Lauer finally took off, it was too late to reach his  
second destination in time for Tuesday's show, said Jeff Zucker, 
``Today'' executive producer. He was rerouted in the air to his 
planned third destination. 
</P>
<P>
	NBC scrambled overnight to fill time, calling former ``Partridge  
Family'' actor Danny Bonaduce after midnight for an interview on 
the perils of child stardom. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's all part of the game,'' Zucker said. ``In order to score  
big, you've got to take big chances.'' 
</P>
<P>
	``Good Morning America'' picked Austin for its first stop in a  
bus tour of the South. But Gibson and Sawyer were planning to cheat 
Monday -- traveling by plane to Lafayette, La. -- and ride the bus 
from there to New Orleans. Instead, their plane was grounded and 
everyone had to make the long drive. 
</P>
<P>
	Lafayette, and about 2,000 people who were waiting to greet the  
crew, were bypassed. 
</P>
<P>
	In New Orleans, a downpour Tuesday forced ``GMA'' to move its  
broadcast site from the outdoor Jackson Square to the nearby 
Pontalbo Cafe. The Neville Brothers had to cancel a performance 
because their equipment was drenched, said Shelley Ross, the show's 
executive producer. 
</P>
<P>
	``We were all calm,'' Ross said. ``A zen came over our  
production. In a funny way, I think we had a better show. It had 
energy and spontaneity.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0255 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 09:55:10 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tree Clearing Urged on Mass. Island </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CAMBRIDGE, Mass. (AP) -- Clearing more than 1,100 acres of trees  
on Martha's Vineyard could restore habitat for rare plants and 
animals on one of New England's most unusual landscapes, according 
to a new study. 
</P>
<P>
	Officials at the state Department of Environmental Management,  
which runs the Manuel F. Correllus State Forest in the middle of 
the island, haven't approved the proposed clearing plan, but they 
agree with the study's goal, The Boston Globe reported today. 
</P>
<P>
	The Harvard University study comes amid growing concern over  
development on Martha's Vineyard, a popular vacation getaway and 
second-home market. More land has been developed in the last three 
decades than since it was first settled by Europeans 330 years ago. 
</P>
<P>
	In 1925, hundreds of acres of spruce and pine trees were planted  
in hopes of creating a lumber industry. The trees, which now cover 
23 percent of the 5,200-acre state forest, never grew well in the 
sandy soil, and the red pines began dying from disease in the 
1960s. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers found the forest -- a rare sand plain where  
farmers had never tilled on a large scale -- even more ecologically 
valuable than previously believed. Farming destroys native plants, 
but tree plantations only gradually choked them off, they said. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is a huge area for a relatively small island and ...  
hidden by these (pine and spruce) plantations, there is this native 
landscape just ready to emerge,'' said David Foster, director of 
the Harvard Forest and co-author of the new report. 
</P>
<P>
	The researchers offered no timetable for the clearing but  
recommended that the youngest spruce and pine trees, planted in the 
1960s, be removed immediately, along with the diseased trees. 
</P>
<P>
	One species that won't come back no matter what the scientists  
do is the heath hen, known for its booming mating calls, which once 
prospered on the island's sandy plains. It has been extinct since 
1932. Some Vineyard residents would like to import prairie chickens 
from the West as a replacement, because they are similar. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0256 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 04:25:06 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> usa </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> The Nation's Weather  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Showers and thunderstorms formed over the middle third of the  
nation today while rain clouds hovered from Tennessee to Wyoming. 
Only the Southwest was expected to fully escape the gray skies. 
</P>
<P>
	While high pressure was expected to build over parts of the  
East, a slow moving storm system was forecast to dampen most of the 
Plains, particularly from Wisconsin to Louisiana. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain showers and thunderstorms were expected over Wisconsin,  
Illinois, Kentucky, Tennessee, Mississippi and Louisiana. Humid air 
from the Gulf Coast also could bring rain to Alabama, Georgia and 
Florida. 
</P>
<P>
	Northern New England was forecast to be blustery across Maine  
and New Hampshire with some afternoon showers and sprinkles 
possible. The rest of the East was expected to be dry and fair. 
</P>
<P>
	An arc of low pressure in the nation's midsection was expected  
to bring a second day of storms from the Dakotas through northern 
Texas. Minnesota through Oklahoma also could be affected, while 
more scattered activity was predicted in Missouri, Arkansas and 
Iowa. 
</P>
<P>
	On Monday, wind gusts exceeding 60 mph accompanied storms in  
Texas, which also dumped hail up to three-quarters of an inch in 
diameter in the Dallas-Fort Worth area and along the Panhandle. 
</P>
<P>
	Rain from the northern Plains was forecast to spill into  
Montana, Wyoming and Colorado. Clouds and drizzle were predicted 
from Washington to California. 
</P>
<P>
	The remaining Western states should be dry and fair.  
</P>
<P>
	The highest temperature in the continental United States on  
Monday was 96 degrees at McAllen, Texas. The low was 14 degrees at 
Ely, Nev. 
</P>
<P>
	Highs today were forecast to reach the 40s and 50s in Maine and  
the mountains of Montana, Wyoming and Colorado; the 60s and 70s 
from New England through the upper Great Lakes, Pennsylvania 
through North Carolina, and Minnesota through Kansas; and the 80s 
and 90s in Texas, California, the Southwest and the central Plains. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
