<CATEGORY> sports </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> New Is Offer Made for the Penguins </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	PITTSBURGH (AP) -- Pittsburgh moved closer Tuesday to joining  
Hartford, Winnipeg, Quebec and other cities that lost NHL teams. 
</P>
<P>
	NHL lawyer Jeffrey Levitan said a person has offered $85 million  
to buy the Pittsburgh Penguins and move the franchise. Levitan did 
not reveal the identity of the potential buyer. 
</P>
<P>
	During a hearing on the league's request for quick work on the  
fate of the team, which is in U.S. Bankruptcy Court proceedings for 
the second time in 25 years, Levitan said the Penguins' assets also 
could be sold piecemeal to other teams, although he said that would 
bring in much less than $85 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Assets include players such as NHL scoring champion Jaromir  
Jagr. 
</P>
<P>
	The potential deal for the team would go through after the NHL  
terminates the franchise, Levitan said. 
</P>
<P>
	The mystery bid represents $35 million more than the offer from  
a group led by former Penguins star center Mario Lemieux and 
endorsed by the NHL. The team's 200 creditors could stand to earn 
more if the mystery bid goes through. 
</P>
<P>
	Chuck Greenberg, Lemieux's lawyer, said the assumption of debt  
will eventually make the Lemieux bid more attractive than the 
latest offer but would not elaborate. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not surprised that another party is interested in the  
team. There were a number of bidders who emerged the last time the 
league expanded,'' Greenberg said. ``We are not going to concern 
ourselves with what might happen if our bid is not confirmed. We 
want to put all our energies into making this a viable franchise in 
Pittsburgh.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Financial trouble under current owners Roger Marino and Howard  
Baldwin and uncertainty about the looming season have reduced the 
team's value, said William Daly, the league's vice president for 
legal affairs. 
</P>
<P>
	``These are not ideal conditions under which to be selling a  
sports franchise,'' he said. 
</P>
<P>
	A court and creditors' review of the NHL's plan to dissolve the  
Penguins has been scheduled for May 19, 12 days before the NHL's 
deadline for resolving Penguins' ownership and the same day as a 
possible Game 6 of Pittsburgh's series against Toronto. 
</P>
<P>
	Daly said the league wants to begin scheduling the 1999-2000  
season and needs to know how many teams it will have and whether 
they will travel to Pittsburgh or another city for games. 
</P>
<P>
	The league is using the prospect of losing the team to push the  
Penguins toward Lemieux and his investors. 
</P>
<P>
	``We are not here to hasten the departure of the team,'' Daly  
said. ``Our priority is to keep the team in Pittsburgh. ... But 
time is a real issue here.'' 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0260 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 02:54:00 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Tenn. Jury Sides With Tobacco Cos. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) -- Big Tobacco cannot be forced to pay  
damages for the lung-cancer deaths of three former smokers, a jury 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	The Shelby County jury found Monday that the nation's three  
largest cigarette makers couldn't be conclusively linked to the 
deaths of two Memphis residents, and was only partly responsible 
for the third death. 
</P>
<P>
	The suits were filed by the families of Bobby Newcomb, a retired  
trucker who died last year at age 64; Florence Bruch, a 63-year-old 
homemaker who died in 1996; and James Karney, a retired trucker who 
was 71 when he died in 1996. 
</P>
<P>
	The three lawsuits, consolidated for a single trial, accused  
Philip Morris Inc., R.J. Reynolds Tobacco Co. and Brown &AMP; 
Williamson Tobacco Corp. of knowingly selling a dangerous product 
and conspiring to cover up that danger. 
</P>
<P>
	The families had been seeking more than $431,000 for medical  
bills and unspecified punitive damages that could have reached into 
the millions of dollars. 
</P>
<P>
	The tobacco companies denied the three died because of smoking  
or that cigarettes are unreasonably dangerous. They also argued the 
three could have quit smoking if they wanted to. 
</P>
<P>
	James Johnson, a lawyer for R.J. Reynolds, said he was pleased  
that after four months of testimony the jury ``conscientiously 
applied the law to (the) evidence and determined that somebody who 
smokes, and being fully aware of the risks of smoking, ought not 
collect money.'' 
</P>
<P>
	That argument resonated with juror Carrie Jester.  
</P>
<P>
	``It's kind of like alcoholism. We know it's bad for you, but we  
make a decision to drink,'' Jester said after the verdict. ``It's 
the same with smoking. We know it's bad for us.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The jury decided Newcomb was at least 50 percent responsible for  
his cancer. Under Tennessee law, that means the tobacco companies 
could not be assessed damages. 
</P>
<P>
	Martin Feldman, a tobacco analyst with Salomon Smith Barney,  
said a loss by the tobacco companies would have been especially 
painful since the cases were taken to trial in a conservative 
Southern city. 
</P>
<P>
	``This doesn't mean that litigation challenges don't remain.  
California and the West Cost generally remain a problem,'' Feldman 
said. 
</P>
<P>
	In similar cases this year a San Francisco woman with inoperable  
lung cancer was awarded $26.5 million and the family of a Portland, 
Ore., man who died of lung cancer was awarded $81 million. 
</P>
<P>
	Curtis Johnson Jr., a lawyer for the plaintiffs, vowed to  
continue taking the tobacco companies to court. 
</P>
<P>
	``This is one case, this is one verdict and we'll be back  
again,'' he said. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
