<CATEGORY> political </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Dole Opposes Concealed Weapons Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	WASHINGTON (AP) -- Elizabeth Dole, distinguishing herself from  
front-runner George W. Bush and the rest of the GOP presidential 
field, said Tuesday that Americans should not be allowed to carry 
concealed weapons. 
</P>
<P>
	``I think police work is hard enough already,'' she said in a  
draft of a speech to a gathering of working women. Mrs. Dole added, 
however, that the issue is ultimately in the hands of state 
legislators. 
</P>
<P>
	Still, the remarks moved the former American Red Cross president  
squarely in the political middle on the contentious gun control 
issue, leaving some GOP consultants wondering whether conservative 
primary voters will accept the stance. 
</P>
<P>
	``It is odd. It's certainly attention-getting for the national  
media,'' Republican consultant Michael Hudome said. ``But it 
probably won't work in a Republican primary.'' 
</P>
<P>
	However, Scott Reed, who managed the 1996 presidential campaign  
of Dole's husband, Bob Dole, called it a wise strategy. ``She is 
differentiating herself from the front-runner and attracting a 
coalition back to the GOP -- a coalition made up of women and 
mothers.'' 
</P>
<P>
	Three weeks after the Colorado high school shooting, Republican  
presidential candidates are staking out territory on guns and 
school violence. 
</P>
<P>
	Other than Bush and Dole, no GOP candidate supports further  
legislation to restrict access to guns. Typical of the rest of the 
field is Gary Bauer, the conservative activist who says the 
shootings are the result of deeper social problems. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush and Dole already have said they support the federal bans on  
assault weapons and armor-piercing bullets. Mrs. Dole unveiled 
those stances in a New Hampshire gathering of presidential 
hopefuls, drawing a cool reception from activists. 
</P>
<P>
	Bush, as Texas governor, signed into law a measure allowing  
state residents to get a license to carry a concealed weapon; it 
requires training and a background check. 
</P>
<P>
	``Governor Bush has a record of doing in office what he says he  
will do on the campaign trail,'' spokeswoman Karen Hughes said, a 
subtle reference to the fact that Mrs. Dole has never held elective 
office. 
</P>
<P>
	``I know many women and men in Texas who have gone through the  
training and who have a license and who feel safer because of that 
legislation -- particularly women who travel or work late at 
night,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Dole's campaign believes there is growing support for her  
position on guns -- even among GOP voters -- and they are betting 
that she will get credit for taking a tough stand even if their 
polls are wrong. 
</P>
<P>
	``It's the right thing to do and I won't shy away from the tough  
issues, even if some in my party don't like it,'' Mrs. Dole said 
Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
	``That includes issues like allowing people to carry concealed  
weapons. While that's a matter for the states to decide, I think 
police work is hard enough already. No one should make it harder. I 
think it's wrong to let people carry concealed weapons,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	She also announced her support of a mandatory requirement that  
guns be sold with child safety locks. Bush supports a voluntary 
effort. 
</P>
<P>
	Earlier Tuesday in Philadelphia, Mrs. Dole took a jab at the  
entertainment industry. She said TV and movie executives should 
take into account the effect of sex and violence on young minds. 
</P>
<P>
	``The Hollywood folks have got to realize with their First  
Amendment rights come responsibilities in terms of what is 
presented to our children, because kids tend to emulate what they 
see,'' the Republican presidential candidate told reporters after a 
speech to 1,500 people at the 15th annual Philadelphia Leadership 
Prayer Breakfast. 
</P>
<P>
	``There's far too much violence and casual sex and all the rest  
today,'' she said. 
</P>
<P>
	Bob Dole was a frequent critic of the entertainment industry  
during the 1996 campaign. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
