<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Crude Oil Down; Coffee, Cattle Up  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	Crude oil futures retreated Tuesday on the New York Mercantile  
Exchange as major oil companies indicated they are cutting back on 
refining operations, moves that could negate the effects of 
producer cutbacks on output. 
</P>
<P>
	On other markets, coffee and cattle futures jumped.  
</P>
<P>
	Crude fell after Royal Dutch-Shell Group and BP Amoco, the  
world's No. 1 and No. 3 refiners, indicated that weaker profit 
margins caused them to cut back on refining in the three months of 
the year. Slower purchases of crude by refiners could thwart the 
intended effect of the output cuts, which were meant to lift oil 
prices by limiting supply. 
</P>
<P>
	Refiners' profits have weakened because crude prices rose  
sharply in the face of promised output reductions from the 
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries, Norway, Mexico and 
others, while prices for refined products such as heating oil have 
not risen as quickly. 
</P>
<P>
	A report released Monday by the International Energy Agency  
examining OPEC's April production showed 85 percent compliance of 
the planned 1.72 million barrels in cuts, but analysts said that 
could be negated if refiners continue to cut back on purchases. 
Many noted the International Energy Agency also had revised 
downward its estimates of the amount of world demand for oil over 
the next few months. 
</P>
<P>
	Market participants also are worried that fluctuations in price  
could cause producers to begin secretly cheating on their promised 
cuts to make as much money as they can at the expense of others. 
</P>
<P>
	The American Petroleum Institute reported after trading had  
ended that crude stockpiles continued to decline, falling 2.3 
million barrels last week. That signals that the producer cuts are 
still holding. 
</P>
<P>
	Crude for June delivery fell 57 cents to $18 a barrel; June  
heating oil fell .77 cent to 43.09 a barrel; June unleaded gasoline 
fell .78 cent to 53.19 cents a gallon; June natural gas fell 6.6 
cents to $2.236 for each 1,000 cubic feet. 
</P>
<P>
	Coffee futures rose sharply on the Board of Trade of the City of  
New York, extending a rally from a day earlier, as Brazil headed 
into more dicey winter growing months. 
</P>
<P>
	Futures prices typically become volatile at this time of year  
since Brazil is the world's largest grower and any sustained freeze 
could cause significant crop damage. Some speculators are betting 
Brazil cannot have a third consecutive year of mild temperatures 
that have led to bumper harvests. 
</P>
<P>
	The investment chief for George Soros' Quantum Fund said  
commodity prices, particular those for coffee and cocoa, were 
poised to go higher. 
</P>
<P>
	July arabica coffee rose 2.05 cents to $1.074 a pound.  
</P>
<P>
	Cattle futures rose sharply on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange  
as market participants bet the upcoming Memorial Day holiday will 
spur retail demand. 
</P>
<P>
	With meteorologists predicting above-normal temperatures for the  
next 10 days in some of the larger consumption areas, analysts said 
grilling demand could surge. Beef demand is at its highest between 
Memorial Day and the Fourth of July holidays. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .45 cent to 61.40 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose 1 cent to 73.17 cents a pound. 

</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0268 </DOCNO>
