<HEADLINE> Wheat Up, Corn Mixed, Soybeans Down / Board of Trade  </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	CHICAGO (AP) -- Wheat futures rose Tuesday on the Chicago Board  
of Trade, while corn finished mixed. Soybeans moved lower. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat fell on concerns about variable yields across the winter  
wheat belt. Corn seesawed as investors squared positions in advance 
of the government's new supply and demand estimates due Wednesday. 
</P>
<P>
	Soybeans were pressured by the Agriculture Department's crop  
update report released late Monday that showed 12 percent of 
soybeans were planted as of last week, up 1 percent from the 
five-year average. Investors expect planting to accelerate in 
coming weeks as the window for planting corn closes. 
</P>
<P>
	Wheat for July delivery rose 3 cents to $2.67 a bushel; July  
corn rose 1/2 cent to $2.22 1/4 a bushel; July oats fell 1 1/2 cents to 
$1.27 1/4 a bushel; July soybeans fell 1 1/2 cents to $4.77 1/2 a bushel. 
</P>
<P>
	Beef futures rose strongly on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange,  
while pork futures fell sharply amid falling cash-market prices 
tied to heavy competition. 
</P>
<P>
	June live cattle rose .45 cent to 61.40 cents a pound; August  
feeder cattle rose 1 cent to 73.17 cents a pound; June lean hogs 
fell .73 cent to 59.97 cents a pound; July pork bellies fell 2.12 
cents to 59.05 cents a pound. 
</P>
</TEXT>
