<CATEGORY> financial </CATEGORY>
<HEADLINE> Motorola Sells Chip Unit for $1.6B </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
	SCHAUMBURG, Ill. (AP) -- A group of investors is buying Motorola  
Corp.'s semiconductor components unit for more than $1.6 billion, 
the company announced today. 
</P>
<P>
	The sale to Texas Pacific Group, based in Fort Worth and San  
Francisco, comes a day after another group that also included 
Motorola executives disclosed it had made a similar offer. 
</P>
<P>
	Under terms of the proposed transaction, Motorola would receive  
$1.6 billion in cash, notes and approximately 10 percent of the 
stock of the new company. The transaction is expected to be 
completed in the second half of 1999, subject to regulatory and 
other approvals. 
</P>
<P>
	The news helped send Motorola's stock price higher today. In  
afternoon trading, Motorola shares were up $2.81 1/4 or 3.4 percent at 
$84.68 3/4 on the New York Stock Exchange. 
</P>
<P>
	The buyer is a private investment partnership with capital of  
approximately $2.5 billion. It's principals include David 
Bonderman, James G. Coulter, and William S. Price. 
</P>
<P>
	The group said it will keep Steve Hanson, Motorola senior vice  
president and general manager of the Semiconductor Components 
Group, in his position as president, while the present management 
team and employees of the unit will become employees of the new 
company. 
</P>
<P>
	``As an independent enterprise, we will focus on the strengths  
that have made us one of the world's largest components 
suppliers,'' Hanson said. ``This will enable us to develop and 
implement a business model fully suited to our mission, while 
continuing a strong tie with Motorola.'' 
</P>
<P>
	The announcement comes after a group of former and present  
Motorola executives disclosed they had made an unsolicited offer 
March 30 for the unit. TFG Acquisition Group said it had recently 
refined it to profess job security for most of the approximately 
10,000 workers at plants in eight countries. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola is restructuring its chip-making business to make it  
more profitable after a major downturn in the industry last year 
that came partly as a result of the Asian economic crisis. There 
was some speculation in February that the Schaumburg, Ill., 
equipment maker was shopping the chip components unit around for a 
sale. 
</P>
<P>
	Motorola hopes to concentrate on the high-end semiconductor  
business that provides embedded chips, while keeping some interest 
in the components business, said company chief executive 
Christopher Galvin. 


</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> APW19990511.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-05-11 12:45:11 </DATE_TIME>
